<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 0333EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     04-20 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pianist-Singer Michael Feinstein Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pianist-singer Michael Feinstein says that he
considers theater songs chums. Theater songs are lucky to have such
a chum and champaion.
   Feinstein, who has become the darling of the supperclub set in
just two years, added to his laurels on Tuesday by becoming the
cabaret toast of Broadway. He did it by singing mainly theater
songs, accompanying himself on piano, in a straightforward, smooth,
engaging style, neither belting, coy, jazzy, mannered nor gimmicky.
   Feinstein opened for a limited engagement, through May 15, at
Broadway's Lyceum Theater.
   Six musicians on a platform behind him during his nearly
two-and-a-half hour show enable Feinstein occasionally to leave his
piano bench and sing with a hand mike, straddling a chair, on a
high stool or even atop his piano.
   His voice is on the light side, with a soft throb, which makes
his most effective vehicle the romantic ballad. Without phrasing to
call attention to his articulation, he manages to enunciate so well
that nearly every word is understood, even in unfamiliar or fast
songs.
   At first, his presentation seems not far removed from bland. But
as the evening progresses, the 30-year-old performer turns an
almost skeptical listener into an enthusiast with his easy command
of the stage, warmth and projection of sincere appreciation of the
songs he plays and sings.
   By the time he'd been singing only a few minutes, he took the
audience into his mood while singing ``Be Careful, It's My Heart''
and ``You Keep Coming Back Like a Song.'' He threw in a few
novelties like ``Lydia the Tattooed Lady'' and very uptempo numbers
like ``Looping the Loop,'' which was cut from the musical
``Chicago.''
   He worked cataloging music for Ira Gershwin for six years, until
Gershwin died in 1983, so his warmth singing the Gershwin brothers'
last co-written song, ``Our Love Is Here To Stay,'' and their
lovely, never published ``Will You Remember Me?'' isn't surprising.
   He also did a lengthy medley of songs by composer Harry Warren,
whom he also knew. Some of Warren's songs with lyricist Al Dubin
have been heard on Broadway since 1980 in ``42nd Street.''
   Feinstein dug in vocally for a big finish with Irving Berlin's
``I Love a Piano,'' all the more effective because he hadn't been
overly emphatic before.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
