<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis     04-20 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis: `I Love New York!'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, proclaiming ``I love New
York,'' moved into the front-runner's position in the Democratic
presidential race on the strength of a resounding New York primary
win on Tuesday.
   ``In Iowa we won the bronze. In New Hampshire we won the gold.
Tonight, we won the Oscar,'' Dukakis told several hundred
supporters who jammed the ballroom of the Omni Park Central Hotel
to toast his win here.
   He contratulated both rivals, Albert Gore Jr. and Jesse Jackson,
praising them as ``outstanding candidates'' who ``both have great
futures as leaders of our party.''
   Hours earlier, Dukakis spoke to 1,500 Democrats in Philadelphia,
where the campaign now moves for Pennsylvania's primary next
Tuesday, and placed an emphasis on the Republican opposition _ all
the while contending he was not assuming he is the certain
Democratic nominee.
   Dukakis immediately was bombarded with questions from network
anchormen about whether his support was too soft or his campaign
too dull to win in Novemer.
   ``I'm somebody I think grows on people as they get to know me,''
Dukakis said on NBC. ``We're building, we're getting stronger every
week.''
   And on ABC, Dukakis said, ``You don't get re-elected governor of
Massachusetts with 70 percent of the vote because you're dull. I
may not dazzle people off of platforms but we've got a terrific
campaign here.''
   Dukakis also said that with Gore apparently out of the race, the
negative campaigning would end. He said he and Jackson are ``very
strong positive people. We have a message of hope and optimism.
Neither of us believes cutting up the other guy is a way to win
elections or the presidency.''
   The Massachusetts governor tried to look ahead to the fall
campaign.
   ``This fall George Bush is going to be judged by a Republican
legacy of more red ink than all of the administrations from George
Washington to Jimmy Carter combined, by pink slips for our workers,
golden parachuetes for high rollers and greenmail for sharp
operators on Wall Street,'' he said.
   ``If I'm the nominee, my friends, the American people will be
able to choose between a Republican legacy of eight years of record
deficits and my record of nine consecutive balanced budgets,'' he
said.
   Paul Brountas, his national campaign chairman, told reporters
traveling with Dukakis back to New York that, if he is the nominee,
Dukakis intends to continue in office as governor. He said Dukakis
would not relax his campaigning, figuring he has won the nomination.
   ``He won't let up. This campaign won't let up,'' Brountas said.
``He is cautious when it comes to campaigning. He won't count it
won till the votes are all counted.''
</TEXT>
