<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Moonwalk-Discography     04-20 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Moonwalk-Discography,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Michael Jackson Discography</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Moonwalk, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Jackson made his first record with his
brothers, Marlon, Tito, Jackie and Jermaine, in 1969. They were a
promising group of adolescent boppers known as the Jackson 5.
   Their music has spanned two decades and produced million dollar
hits.
   Jackson's career shot to hyperspace in 1979 with his solo LP,
``Off the Wall,'' a record many critics acknowledge to be the best
artistic work he's ever produced.
   However, it was the landmark ``Thriller'' LP in 1982 that
lionized Jackson and earned him a record eight Grammys. With more
than 40 million copies sold worldwide, it became the most
successful album of all time.
   His latest work, ``Bad,'' although a major hit, has failed to
reach the success levels of ``Thriller,'' winning no Grammys this
year. As of April 16, the album was No. 3 with a bullet _ which
means it's climbing _ in Cashbox.
   Here is a list of albums made by Jackson:
   _ With the Jacksons:
   ``I Want You Back'' (Motown, 1969)
   ``I'll Be There'' (Motown, 1970)
   ``Diana Ross Presents the Jackson Five'' (Motown, 1970)
   
   ``ABC'' (Motown, 1970)
   ``Christmas Album'' (Motown, 1970)
   ``Third Album'' (Motown, 1971)
   ``Maybe Tomorrow'' (Motown, 1971)
   ``Mama's Pearl'' (Motown, 1971)
   ``Never Can Say Goodbye'' (Motown, 1971)
   ``Sugar Daddy'' (Motown, 1971)
   ``Greatest Hits'' (Motown, 1972)
   ``Lookin' Through Windows'' (Motown, 1972)
   ``Skywriter'' (Motown, 1973)
   ``Dancing Machine'' (Motown, 1973)
   ``Get It Together'' (Motown, 1973)
   ``Goin' Back to Indiana'' (Motown)
   ``Moving Vibrations'' (Motown, 1975)
   ``Jacksons'' (Epic, 1976)
   ``Anthology'' (Motown, 1977)
   ``Joyful Jukebox Music'' (Motown, 1977)
   ``Goin' Places'' (Epic, 1977)
   ``Destiny'' (Epic, 1978)
   ``Zip a Dee Doo Dah'' (MFP, 1979)
   ``20 Golden Greats'' (Motown, 1979)
   ``Motown Superstar Series Vol. 12'' (Motown, 1980)
   ``Victory'' (Epic, 1984)
   
   _ Solo:
   ``Got to Be There'' (Motown, 1971)
   ``The Best of Michael Jackson'' (Motown, 1975)
   ``Off the Wall'' (Epic, 1979)
   ``Motown Superstar Series, Vol. 7'' (Motown, 1980)
   ``One Day in Your Life'' (Motown, 1981)
   ``Got to Be There'' (Motown, 1981)
   ``Ben'' (Motown, 1981)
   ``Thriller'' (Epic, 1982)
   ``Bad'' (Epic, 1987)
   ``Music & Me'' (Motown)
   ``Forever, Michael'' (Motown)
   
   _ With other artists:
   ``This Girl Is Mine'' (Paul McCartney)
   ``Say, Say, Say'' (Paul McCartney)
   ``We Are the World'' (Assorted Artists)
