<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--Financier-Extradite     04-20 0127</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Financier-Extradite,0133</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge OKs West German Businessman's Extradition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German financier accused of
defrauding Volkswagen out of an estimated $285 million is eligible
for extradition, a U.S. magistrate has ruled.
   The extradition of Joachim Schmidt, 38, was upheld Tuesday
following an hour-long hearing before U.S. Magistrate Ronald Rose,
who dismissed technical objections filed by Schmidt's American
attorneys.
   Rose said he would sign an order Monday to certify Schmidt's
transfer to Germany.
   Schmidt apparently fled to the United States after Volkswagen
discovered he had engineered a massive fraud through currency
futures purchased by the West German automaker, prosecutors said.
   The FBI arrested the financier in November 1987, when he was
living in a Hollywood apartment under an assumed name, authorities
said.
</TEXT>
