<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--JailDesegregated     04-20 0126</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Jail Desegregated,0128</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fla. Jail Desegrated by New Administrator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANFORD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Segregation at the Seminole County Jail has
been ended by its new administrator, who says racial tensions don't
justify separating blacks and whites.
   ``This is 1988,'' said Duane Rutledge, who on Monday put even
numbers of white and black inmates in the previously segregated
cellblocks. ``If they can't live together ... then they will live
in isolation.''
   Two years ago, Capt. Jay Leman, whom Rutledge succeeded in
February, created two all-black cellblocks and one all-white one in
the maximum-security area, citing racial tension. The state
Department of Corrections condoned the move.
   Guards had complained about the policy, saying white guards
feared entering the all-black cellblocks and black guards feared
the all-white cellblock.
</TEXT>
