<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 0736EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SunshineLaw     04-20 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sunshine Law,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Federal Agencies Accused of Violating Sunshine Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agencies with two notable exceptions
are generally complying with the ``sunshine'' law requiring them to
conduct important business in meetings open to the public, a Senate
hearing was told.
   The two persistent offenders were identified Tuesday as the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission and the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission. Both were accused of violating the spirit _ if not the
letter _ of the law intended to expose government decision-making
to closer public scrutiny.
   Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., chief sponsor of the 1976 law, said
recent congressional surveys reinforce his belief that ``on
balance, agencies are making efforts to comply with the law.''
   But Peter Prichard, senior news editor at USA Today, told a
Senate Governmental Affairs subcommittee headed by Chiles that
``the law does not work as well as it might.''
   Prichard, who represented the American Society of Newspaper
Editors and the American Newspaper Publishers Association, said the
law ``seems to have encouraged agencies to conduct well-scripted
meetings to fulfill the formalities of the law and to erect
memorials to decisions that actually occurred outside the public
view.''
   The law, which has no enforcement provisions, covers about 50
independent agencies but none of the Cabinet agencies headed by a
single administrator. In addition, discussions of such sensitive
issues as litigation, national security and personnel matters are
exempt.
   The NRC was singled out for criticism at Tuesday's hearing by
Ellyn R. Weiss, general counsel for the Union of Concerned
Scientists, who said there is a ``prevailing climate of public
phobia'' at the nuclear agency.
   ``The sun has not shone much over the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission,'' she said. ``NRC has for the past seven years mounted
a substantial and across-the-board assault on public participation
in its decision-making.''
   NRC spokeswoman Sue Gagner refused to comment on Ms. Weiss'
allegations.
   Claudia Withers of the Women's Legal Defense Fund, a non-profit
group that seeks elimination of sex discrimination in employment
and family law, made a similar complaint about the EEOC, the
independent agency responsible for enforcing anti-discrimination
laws.
   Ms. Withers said that after attending weekly agency meetings for
several months in 1985, ``it became clear to us that the EEOC
conducted little business of any real substance at its public
sessions'' and that detailed discussions actually took place
privately.
   She and Ms. Weiss said commissioners at both agencies evaded the
law's requirements by voting privately on policy memos circulated
among themselves, and then holding a public meeting simply to
announce their decisions.
   Ms. Withers said the EEOC ``may adhere to the letter of the
Sunshine Act, but ... sorely tests its spirit.''
   Deborah Graham, the EEOC's chief spokeswoman, denied Ms.
Withers' charges of secret decision-making and said the agency
holds weekly meetings with advance notice to the public.
   Ms. Graham said, however, that the number of closed EEOC
meetings has grown since September 1984. That is when the full
commission assumed responsibility from staff lawyers for handling
every discrimination dispute that called for possible court action,
she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
