<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 0049EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-NewYork-Democrats     04-20 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New York-Democrats,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Win Could Be Good Sign For Democrats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis handed Jesse Jackson a setback
in New York on Tuesday from which he might not recover but the
Massachusetts governor did it without alienating Jackson's black
supporters.
   Dukakis managed to stay above the fray while Albert Gore Jr. and
New York Mayor Edward Koch battered Jackson, thus keeping open the
channels of communication to the civil rights leader and his core
black constituency.
   ``We're both very strong positive people,'' Dukakis said on ABC.
``We have a message of hope and optimism. Neither of us believes
cutting up the other guy is a way to win elections or the
presidency.''
   During one Harlem campaign stop, Dukakis was criticized for
giving up the black vote to Jackson. Exit polls showed that the
black vote went overwhelmingly for Jackson, as expected. Those
polls also showed, however, that many blacks felt Dukakis wasn't
sensitive to their needs.
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr., on the other hand, was the first
Democratic candidate to go directly after Jackson, talking about
the need to elect a president not ``a preacher.''
   Then Gore picked up the endorsement of Koch and the attacks, now
coming from Koch, became more strident. Jews would have to be
``crazy'' to vote for Jackson and Jackson couldn't be trusted to
tell the truth under stress, said Koch.
   Gore, who had begun to soften his attacks on Jackson as the New
York campaign wound down and the Tennessee senator sensed his
coming defeat, eventually said Koch was ``speaking for himself.''
   Dukakis' New York victory was impressive in its own right. In
collecting about 50 percent of the vote, Dukakis bettered Walter
Mondale's 44 percent win in 1984. Jackson, running about even with
Dukakis in New York City, finished about 10 percentage points
higher than four years ago when he won 26 percent of the New York
vote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880420-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 0745EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WarPowersAct     04-20 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-War Powers Act,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nunn Says Overhaul War Powers Act To Remove Withdrawal Timetables</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The War Powers Act needs to be overhauled to
eliminate a provision that sets automatic deadlines for withdrawal
of U.S. troops from global hotspots such as the Persian Gulf, says
an influential senator on national security issues.
   ``I think it needs to be substantially revised,'' said Sen. Sam
Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee.
   Nunn said he plans to propose revisions of the 1973 law within
the next several weeks, but said his proposal would not affect the
current Persian Gulf policy.
   ``I'm just in the process of drafting it now,'' said Nunn, who
explained he wants to discuss his proposals with Senate Majority
Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., and administration officials.
   President Reagan has refused to invoke the War Powers Act for
his Persian Gulf policy, but he has consulted with congressional
leaders.
   The act requires a report from the White House within 48 hours
after U.S. troops are sent into areas of ``imminent hostilities.''
Under some circumstances, those forces would have to be withdrawn
within 60 days unless Congress votes to permit them to remain.
   Nunn said ``the automatic withdrawal provision ought to be
removed.'' Nunn has objected to the timetables because they are
arbitrary, Congress can circumvent them by using its power over the
pursestrings, and they shift the focus of the law away from
consultations between the president and Congress.
   He also plans to propose a leadership council of unnamed senior
congressional leaders who would consult with the president
regularly about national security issues.
   ``You cannot have 435 congressmen and 100 senators all be
informed,'' Nunn said. ``But you can have a leadership council and
then it becomes the job of congressional leaders to inform the
House and Senate.''
   Nunn said the law contains no enforcement provision and thus
Congress has no effective response to Reagan's refusal to invoke
the law.
   ``The law is on the books and it ought to either be obeyed or
declared unconstitutional,'' Nunn said. ``But if the president
decides he's not going to follow the law, there's nothing Congress
can do.''
   Congress has the option of passing a bill to invoke the War
Powers Act, he said, but Reagan could veto that bill and a
two-thirds vote of the House and Senate would then have to override
the veto to trigger the law.
   Reagan was widely praised on Capitol Hill this week for telling
House and Senate leaders about the planned U.S. attacks on Iranian
oil platforms before the attacks started.
   But some senators still said the War Powers Act should be
invoked, arguing that the last U.S.-Iran clash meets the
requirements of the bill.
   ``If this situation doesn't trigger War Powers, nothing will,''
said Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash., one of the chief Senate critics of
Reagan's refusal to invoke the law.
   Reagan, as have all previous presidents, contends that the act
is an unconstitutional limit on his authority to conduct foreign
policy.
   Last summer, a group of 115 legislators, most of them House
Democrats, sued in federal court here to seek an order requiring
Reagan to trigger the law. The suit was dismissed on grounds that
it was a political dispute and thus outside the reach of the
judiciary, but the legislators are appealing that ruling.
   The only time that Congress has succeeded in invoking the War
Powers law was 1983, when U.S. Marines were sent into Beirut as
part of an international peacekeeping force. Congress extended the
deployment deadline to 18 months, but the Marines were withdrawn
three months after 241 servicemen, most of them Marines, were
killed by a suicide truck bomber.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
