<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Sailor'sRemains     04-20 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sailor's Remains,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sailor's Remains Returned to United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOVER AIR FORCE BASE, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of a Navy enlisted
woman killed last week in a terrorist attack in Italy has been
returned to the United States in a flag-draped coffin.
   A C-5A Galaxy cargo jet carrying the remains of Radioman 3rd
Class Angela S. Santos landed at Dover Air Force Base just as the
sun peered from behind clouds Tuesday afternoon.
   During brief ceremonies beside the plane, her mother, Ellagene
E. Cruz, and Ms. Santos' brother James, both of Ocala, Fla., stood
with her father, James J. Santos Sr. of Isabela, Puerto Rico.
   ``She's the first Navy female killed as a result of a terrorist
act and quite possibly'' the first servicewoman ever, said Navy
spokesman Alfred R. Twyman Jr.
   Pallbearers moved slowly through the ranks of an honor guard,
while the band played the Navy Hymn, and placed the coffin in a
white hearse.
   Ms. Santos, 21, of Ocala, was among five people killed Thursday
when terrorists parked a bomb-laden car outside the USO club in
Naples. Four U.S. sailors were among 17 people wounded.
</TEXT>
