<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     04-20 0921</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lyng Meets With Canadian Counterpart On Trade Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A presidential veto of the massive trade bill
now before Congress wouldn't directly affect the free-trade
agreement between the United States and Canada, according to
Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng.
   ``There's nothing that tells me that they're connected,'' Lyng
said Tuesday. If there is a veto of the sweeping trade bill,
President Reagan's veto message would ``describe some reasons that
have nothing whatsoever to do with the free trade agreement with
Canada, as far as I can see.''
   Lawmakers are near final action on the 1,000-page trade bill,
but there have been veto threats over parts the administration find
objectionable, including a provision that would require 60-day
notice of plant closings and large-scale layoffs.
   The U.S.-Canada trade pact was signed Jan. 2 but still requires
approval by the Canadian parliament and the U.S. Congress. If
approved, the treaty will take effect Jan. 1, 1989, and will
gradually eliminate all tariffs between the two countries and
address non-tariff barriers.
   According to the Agriculture Department, U.S-Canada trade was
about $124 billion in 1986, of which $4.6 billion was agricultural.
   Lyng appeared at a news conference with Canadian minister of
agriculture John Wise following private discussions. Wise said he
was pleased by Lyng's view of the trade bill and said there is
``the absolute need and the absolute necessity for us to join
forces'' in ongoing global talks under the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade, or GATT.
   ``In fact, I think, were it not for the leadership taken by
Canada and the United States ... we probably wouldn't be at the
stage that we are now in the Uruguay Round of multinational trade
negotiations,'' Wise said.
   Both he and Lyng said the U.S.-Canada free-trade agreement would
help push the cause of global reform.
   ``It would be extremely helpful, I think, to both of us, in
sending a very legitimate and a very concrete message to our other
trading partners, particularly at GATT,'' Wise said.
   In a joint statement later, the two agricultural leaders pledged
to work together ``to ensure that the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development ministerial meeting in May and the
Toronto economic summit in June provide the necessary political
impetus'' for a midterm review of the Uruguay Round next December
in Montreal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Large Soviet purchases of wheat at subsidized
prices have helped increase grain exports and brighten financial
prospects for American farmers, says an Agriculture Department
report.
   Overall, the Soviet Union's total grain imports are at a
three-year high, despite bumper harvests the last two seasons, the
department's Economic Research Service said Tuesday.
   ``The gain is primarily from larger wheat purchases,'' the
report said. ``Aided by the Export Enhancement Program and Soviet
demand for milling-quality wheat, the U.S. share of import volume
is likely to rise to about half this year, up from less than 1
percent in 1985-86.''
   The Soviet Union is expected to import 32 million metric tons of
total grain from all foreign sources in the international marketing
year that runs through June 30, 1988. That would be the most since
imports were a record 55.5 million tons in 1984-85.
   The wheat share of this year's imports is estimated at 22
million tons, the most since 1984-85 when wheat rose to 28.1
million tons.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat.
   Soviet wheat imports dropped sharply in 1985-86 to 15.7 million
tons, when the U.S. share declined to a trickle.
   Under a five-year agreement, the Soviet Union is committed to
buy at least 4 million of wheat and 4 million tons of corn
annually. The pact expires this Sept. 30 and covers the year that
began last Oct. 1.
   Although the agreement year is three months out of step with the
July 1-June 30 marketing year, it does show a similar trend in
Soviet grain imports.
   For example, Soviet wheat purchases fell short of the pact's
minimum in 1984-85 when they dropped to 2.9 million tons, and in
1985-86 when they were only 200,000 tons. That coincided with the
``less than 1 percent'' U.S. share cited in the latest report.
   The Export Enhancement Progam, or EEP, allows exporters to sell
designated commodities to specified countries at reduced prices and
then collect free USDA-owned commodities as bonuses, or subsidies.
   Subsidized wheat sales to the Soviet Union began a year ago. So
far Moscow has bought more than 8.8 million tons for delivery in
1987-88, the final year of the grain pact.
   In addition, the Soviets have bought 4.1 million tons of U.S.
corn, 818,400 tons of soybeans and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal
for delivery through Sept. 30.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department is asking for
public comments on how to design the 1989 wheat program.
   One the biggest decisions will be whether to include an acreage
reduction program, or ARP, in next year's program. That involves
how much of a farmer's wheat base must be idled in order to qualify
for 1989 price supports and other program benefits.
   For the 1988 wheat crop, as an example, participating farmers
had to reduce plantings by 27.5 percent of their wheat base.
   The 1985 farm law requires USDA to announce the following year's
wheat ARP no later than June 1, officials said Tuesday.
   Comments can be sent by May 16 to: Director, Commodity Analysis
Division, USDA-ASCS, Room 3741-S, P.O. Box 2415, Washington, D.C.
20013.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
