<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NaturalGas     04-20 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Natural Gas,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panelists: Cheap, Plentiful Fuel Has Role In Clean-Air Efforts</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Politicians from natural-gas producing states
are trying to forge an unlikely coalition of industry and
environmental interests to promote the product and lobby Congress.
   Texas Land Commissioner Garry Mauro, who was among those
attending a symposium on the subject Tuesday, said the natural gas
industry has been timid too long.
   ``The squeaky wheel gets the oil, but natural gas hasn't been
squeaky enough,'' Mauro said. ``It's not told its story loud
enough.''
   Oilman T. Boone Pickens, general partner of Mesa Limited
Partnership, told the gathering the domestic oil industry will
never return to its former glory.
   ``There's not much future for the domestic oil industry,''
Pickens said. ``But there is a lot of potential for the natural gas
industry.''
   Many of those attending the daylong symposium agreed that
natural gas, the cleanest-burning fossil fuel, can play an
important role in efforts to rid cities of pollutants from industry
and vehicle emissions.
   Daniel Weiss, a representative of the Sierra Club, said his
group would support the use of natural gas in legislation aimed at
cleaning up the environment.
   But officials said a significant switch to natural gas or other
alternate fuels by power plants or automobiles is still years away.
   Rep. Mike Synar, D-Okla., said some pressure could come this
fall if Congress approves legislation by Aug. 31 to yank highway
and other funding from cities and states that don't comply with
clean-air standards. Congress has lifted its requirement that
cities meet those standards until the end of August.
   According to the Environmental Protection Agency, 72 cities are
not meeting clean-air requirements and are benefiting from the
congressional reprieve.
</TEXT>
