<DOCNO> AP880420-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 0131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Koch     04-20 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Koch,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Koch A Loser In NY Primary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Among the losers in New York's Democratic
primary Tuesday was Mayor Edward I. Koch, who conceded that his
bitter attacks on the Rev. Jesse Jackson were apparently a mistake.
   Despite the mayor's high-profile criticism, Jackson won New York
City by about 6,000 votes over primary-winner Michael Dukakis in a
heavy turnout of slightly less than 1 million voters. Jackson won
37 percent of the vote overall.
   ``While he was making hysteria, I was making history,'' Jackson
said after the votes were counted.
   Meanwhile, network television exit polls suggested Koch's
hardball tactics may haunt him if he runs for re-election in 1989.
   Koch, who endorsed Sen. Al Gore and then campaigned side by side
with him, has been widely criticized for his attacks.
   ``If he had been more subtle about it, it may have been more
devastating to the Jackson campaign,'' said Jackson's campaign
manager, California Assembly Speaker Willie Brown.
   ``But the flagrant display of anti-Jackson attitudes, that
appear to be primarily based on Mr. Jackson's race, have
embarrassed some of the people in New York who may have been
otherwise against Jackson.''
   Gore's 8.3 percent in New York City was even behind his 10
percent statewide total.
   In the last few days of the hard-fought primary, Koch was
seemingly always at Gore's side in his city appearances. The mayor
claimed the headlines with a steady stream of invective against
Jackson.
   Koch sharply attacked Jackson's positions on Israel, said Jews
``would be crazy'' to vote for him and then called him arrogant for
failing to march in a Salute to Israel parade.
   Asked Tuesday night if he would make the same remarks if the
clock were turned back, Koch said, ``Obviously, I would not make
them the way I did because, apparently, they were not helpful to Al
Gore.''
   Although Gore thanked Koch for his help, he also distanced
himself from the mayor's tactics. Congratulating Jackson on his
showing, Gore said he never wanted to ``stop Jackson. I just wanted
to start Al Gore.''
   A CBS-New York Times exit poll showed that voters disagreed with
Koch's criticism of Jackson by a 2-1 margin.
   In an early NBC exit poll, 60 percent of the voters said they
didn't want Koch to run for re-election next year.
   ``It looks like Ed Koch certainly didn't help Gore and may have
helped stimulate a black turnout for Jackson,'' said ABC pollster
Doug Muzzio. ``Ed Koch may be a loser here.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
