<DOCNO> AP880420-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 0406EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-JazzStars     04-20 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Jazz Stars,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jazz Festival Program Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The JVC Jazz Festival is promising something for
fans of every jazz style with headliners including Dizzy Gillespie,
Ella Fitzgerald, Lionel Hampton, B.B. King, Mel Torme and Sarah
Vaughan.
   ``Our list of artists this year reflects the myriad tastes of
the jazz fan from all eras,'' festival impresario George Wein said
Tuesday at a news conference to announce the lineup for the June 24
to July 2 event.
   Performances will not be limited to bebop, swing and Dixieland
as the event's predecessor, the Newport Jazz Festival, was when it
premiered in 1954.
   Opening night, a Friday, will feature Gillespie, Hampton, Marty
Napoleon, Arvell Shaw, Clark Terry, Roy Eldridge, Jimmy Owens,
Warren Vache, Wynton Marsalis and Jon Faddis in a tribute to Louis
Armstrong.
   Miss Fitzgerald, who is singing again after several months'
absence from the scene, will appear at Carnegie Hall the second
night, while Miles Davis and a new star, Gerald Albright, perform
in Avery Fisher Hall.
   The Toshiko Akiyoshi and Mel Lewis bands are booked at Town Hall
the same night. The evening begins with Billy Taylor playing solo
piano at Weill Recital Hall in Carnegie Hall.
   The third night offers a choice between four Duke Ellington
symphonic pieces by the American Composers Orchestra, tap-dancing
or Jim Cullum's Jazz Band interpreting ``Porgy and Bess.''
   Jay McShann of early Kansas City jazz fame and the Charles
Mingus All-Star Big Band play June 27.
   Gillespie's band and singer Carmen McRae and her quartet share
the Carnegie Hall bill June 28 while King, the Fabulous
Thunderbirds, Bonnie Raitt and Dr. John offer varieties of blues at
Avery Fisher Hall.
   The entertainment June 29 includes Torme, Cissy Houston and the
Sweet Inspirations and other singers at Carnegie and Hampton's band
and Wynton Marsalis' quintet at Avery Fisher.
   The offerings June 30 begin with Marian McPartland playing solo
piano at Weill Recital Hall. At 8 p.m., there's the choice of
hearing Miss Vaughan at Carnegie, the Carlos Santana-Wayne Shorter
Group at Avery Fisher and the Dave Brubeck Quartet at the 92nd
Street Y.
   The late Buddy Rich's big band will be at Carnegie Hall while
Kenny G and Stanley Jordan will be at Avery Fisher on July 1.
   The final night, music associated with the late Billy Holiday
will be presented at Town Hall. Miki Howard and Najee will be at
Avery Fisher and ``Latin Jazz Jam: a Tribute to Machito'' is at
Carnegie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
