<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 0138EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-VermontDemocrats 8thLd-Writethru a0466 04-20 0773</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vermont Democrats, 8th Ld-Writethru, a0466,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Jackson Fight To Draw In Vermont</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs, new vote totals, delegate projections.
Will stand for AMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANICA KIRKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson fought
to a virtual draw in Vermont's Democratic caucuses Tuesday night in
a seesaw battle that tightened dramatically as the votes piled up.
   Early Wednesday, with nearly all the votes counted, Dukakis held
a razor-thin lead. The Massachusetts governor had scored a 2-1
victory in the state's ``beauty contest'' primary last month.
   With 94 percent of 1,300 state convention delegates picked,
Dukakis had 559, or 46 percent, while Jackson had 547, or 45
percent. Albert Gore Jr. had 4, or 0 percent; 110 delegates, or 9
percent, were uncommitted.
   Dukakis would win 8 national convention delegates and Jackson 6,
if those results held up at the state convention.
   Jackson had held a narrow lead throughout most of the counting.
In New York, where he lost to Dukakis, Jackson claimed victory in
the contest here.
   ``We won Vermont tonight,'' he told supporters.
   A win for Jackson in the Democratic caucuses would be a
disappointment for the Dukakis campaign, which has most prominent
Democrats in the state behind it, including Gov. Madeleine Kunin,
Sen. Patrick Leahy, Lt. Gov. Howard Dean and House Speaker Ralph
Wright.
   Kunin said Jackson's strong showing in Vermont was ``not
unexpected,'' and pointed to Dukakis' solid victory in Tuesday's
big New York primary.
   ``I continue to be very optimistic about Dukakis,'' she said.
``I think his showing in New York is fantastic.''
   In the state's largest city of Burlington, Jackson won 60
percent of the delegates at a caucus highlighted by the appearance
of Burlington Mayor Bernard Sanders, a Jackson backer and a
socialist who has long fought the Democrats.
   ``I have no apologies to make to anybody,'' Sanders said before
the caucus, responding to Democrats who opposed his appearance at
their event.
   Sanders ran successfully as an independent for mayor and
unsuccessfully as an independent for governor. This year he is
running as an independent for the U.S. House.
   On the Republican side, some 1,000 delegates to the state GOP
convention were being chosen Tuesday night. With 33 percent of the
delegates accounted for, Vice President George Bush had 291
delegates, or 89 percent, while 34, or 10 percent, were uncommitted.
   Backers of Dukakis, who has long been favored here, were making
less upbeat statements just before Tuesday's town caucuses.
   ``I hear everything from we're dead in the water to we might
make it,'' said William Wasserman, state coordinator for Dukakis,
the governor of neighboring Massachusetts. Supporters of Jackson
said they had built a solid organization in Vermont and noted that
Jackson has done better in caucus states, with relatively small
turnouts, than in primary states.
   The 1,300 delegates elected Tuesday night will attend next
month's state convention, at which time 14 of Vermont's 19
delegates to the national convention will be chosen. The remaining
five spots belong to Gov. Kunin, a Dukakis backer, and four state
party officials.
   On the Republican side, Pat Robertson's campaign tried to turn
out supporters so that Robertson would still have a voice at the
state and national conventions.
   ``The Bush forces rallied and were able to overcome the
Robertson forces,'' said Bush's Vermont spokesman, Steve Watson.
``We had the best turnout ever in some towns.''
   Dukakis won Vermont's presidential primary March 1, with 56
percent of the vote to Jackson's 26 percent. But that primary was
non-binding and had nothing to do with the selection of actual
delegates. And recent history has shown primary winners don't fare
as well in the caucuses.
   Gary Hart won the presidential primary four years ago, but
Walter Mondale won the caucus vote. Eight years ago Jimmy Carter
won the primary, but Edward Kennedy won the caucuses.
   The primary tends to be more of a popularity contest, while the
outcome of the caucuses revolves around campaign organization.
   ``Jesse Jackson has done better in caucus states than primary
states,'' said Liz Blum, Jackson state coordinator in Vermont,
noting that his supporters are so strongly behind him that they
will attend caucuses.
   ``We have identified Jackson supporters all over the state and
have built a solid organization,'' she said.
   About 670 people attended the Burlington Democratic caucus,
compared to 435 during the 1984 contest.
   ``Most of the towns that I've talked to, have told me that
they've had the largest turnouts that they can remember,'' said
Craig Fuller, the executive director of the state's Democratic
Party. ``They are interested in who's going to be the next
president.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
