<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Resnik-Sculpture,0127</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sculpture Honoring Challenger Astronaut Dedicated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sculpture honoring Judith A. Resnik, one of
the seven astronauts killed on the shuttle Challenger, was
dedicated on the campus of her alma mater.
   Resnik, who was 36 when she was killed in the Jan. 28, 1986,
explosion, graduated from Carnegie Mellon University in 1970 with a
bachelor's degree in electrical engineering.
   The sculpture was commissioned by Tau Beta Pi, the national
engineering honor society of which Resnik was a member. The cast
metal sculpture is shaped in the society's symbol, a bent set.
   When Resnik died, Carnegie Mellon created a scholarship fund in
her memory. This year two women electrical engineering students
will receive grants from it, the school said.
</TEXT>
