<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 0423EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     04-20 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Predicts He'll Face Dukakis In The Fall _ And Win</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush predicts the winner
of the New York Democratic primary, Michael Dukakis, will go on to
win his party's nomination and face him in the fall general
election.
   At the same time, Bush rejected as ``invalid liberal trash''
suggestions that his acceptance of support from former Philadelphia
Mayor Frank Rizzo might send the wrong signal to blacks and other
minorities in November.
   ``Are you suggesting you only appear with civil rights
leaders?'' Bush asked reporters.
   He made the comments aboard Air Force Two late Tuesday as he
returned from a campaign stop in Philadelphia, where he shared the
stage at a Republican rally with Rizzo. Pennsylvania's primary is
Tuesday.
   Bush said he had no hesitation in appearing with Rizzo, a former
Democrat who is his Philadelphia campaign chairman. To not do so,
Bush said, would be ``a policy of exclusion. I don't do that.''
   The vice president, who has the Republican nomination
essentially locked up, said it was a ``good bet'' that the New York
primary victor would be the Democratic candidate.
   ``I do think that whoever wins this (New York primary) tonight,
and this is my personal opinion, will get an awful lot of delegates
and win the nomination.''
   Bush said he did not intend to criticize Dukakis right away. ``I
think I'll keep it generic until the convention,'' he said.
   But he referred to Dukakis as ``an old-world liberal Democrat.''
   Bush also defended his decision to campaign in Ohio and
Pennsylvania on Monday and Tuesday, rather than remaining in
Washington because of the Persian Gulf crisis. ``There was no
action required, no decisons on which to advise ... If there had
been an important meeting, I would have been there.''
   On the subject of Rizzo, Bush conceded that some blacks unhappy
with Rizzo's tenures as Philadelphia's police chief and then as
mayor might react negatively to his role in the Bush campaign.
   But the vice president said he intended to reach out to a
variety of ethnic groups and to speak in ``ethnic communities.''
   ``My God, to say that we've got to show that I care about civil
rights and human rights in reaching out to others, that I have to
then turn my back on ethnic neighborhoods and values and
individuals that are strong in those areas, I'm not going to do
that. That's reverse discrimination.''
   Bush said that by ``ethnic neighorhoods'' he was generally
speaking about minorities other than blacks. He cited
``Lithuanians, the Polish church we're talking about, these ethnic
wards in Chicago.
   ``And to suggest you have to write all those off to show your
civil rights (credentials), to the exclusion of other minorities, I
reject that as a liberal point of view that I just don't conceive
has any validity whatsoever.
   ``What signals have I sent? I've sent a signal that I want the
vote of people in these ethnic communities who believe in the same
things that I do and that our party does, in terms of the
importance of neighborhood, family, faith, freedom, that's the
message I'm sending.''
   Bush said that Rizzo had lost in his most recent attempt to be
re-elected mayor, as a Republican, by a slim 9,000-vote margin.
   ``And to suggest that I should not appear with him because I'm
worried that that will hurt me in some other areas, I'm sorry I
don't (buy) that. I reject it as invalid liberal trash.
   ``Are you suggesting that 49.5 percent of the people in
Philadelphia are racist because they vote for a man who had been
mayor of the city and who was campaigining on things that appealed
to them? It's unfair and it is outrageous,'' Bush told reporters.
   Earlier, with Rizzo at his side, Bush told the GOP rally in
Philadelphia: ``I want to take on whichever one of those Democrats
wins today in New York _ and whip them in the fall.''
   Bush wound up a two-day campaign swing through Ohio and
Pennsylvania. He planned to spend the rest of the week in
Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
