<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 0812EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-Governorship     04-20 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Governorship,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says He Won't Resign as Governor Until Presidential
Inaugural</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis says he will not resign as
governor of Massachusetts if he wins the Democratic presidential
nomination in July or even in November if he should win the general
election.
   ``I'll wait until I'm sworn in,'' Dukakis told reporters on
Tuesday.
   Since he formally announced his presidential candidacy a year
ago, Dukakis has insisted he could serve as governor and run a
nationwide campaign.
   Until Tuesday, he had never explained the circumstances under
which he would surrender his office.
   At a statehouse news briefing, Dukakis was asked whether he
would resign if he wins the Democratic nomination, in order to
devote his full time to the presidential campaign.
   ``We've never expected that of our candidates. Nobody asked John
Kennedy to resign from the Senate. Nobody has asked George Bush to
resign the vice presidency,'' Dukakis said.
   ``As a matter of fact, I think it's a strength of mine that I'm
an active, working governor at the same time I'm running for the
presidency. I see that every day,'' he said. ``I will not give up
the governorship. I will continue to be an active governor, as I
have in the course of the primary campaign.''
   Dukakis, who is in his tenth year as governor, rejected ``the
notion that you've got to be unemployed to run for the presidency''
and said there were no circumstances under which he would resign
before a presidential inaugural.
   His statement may come as a disappointment to Lt. Gov. Evelyn
Murphy. Under the state constitution, she would automatically
become governor if there is a vacancy in the governorship.
   If she ascends to the governorship through Dukakis' good
fortunes, Murphy could gain enough stature and political strength
to win election outright in 1990.
   Dukakis is the first sitting governor to campaign for the White
House since California Gov. Edmund Brown Jr. jumped into the 1976
primaries. The last sitting governor to win the presidency was
Democrat Franklin D. Roosevelt of New York in 1932.
   For the past year, Dukakis has generally spent about half of his
time in the state and the remainder on the campaign trail.
</TEXT>
