<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 0221EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-KennedyFiles Bjt   04-20 0793</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kennedy Files, Bjt,0814</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RFK Assassination Scholar Seeks Probe Of Destroyed Evidence</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SC1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scholar who pushed for release of
the Robert Kennedy assassination files says the newly disclosed
destruction of 2,410 evidence photographs is ``deeply suspicious''
and should be investigated.
   Greg Stone, a University of Wisconsin political scientist who
has devoted years to studying the assassination, said he was
shocked that Tuesday's opening of the files also brought word of
destroyed evidence.
   ``Far and away, the blinding central fact in this event is the
unbelievable destruction of these photographs,'' said Stone. ``That
is an outrage and an insult to the American public. ... This
performance (by the Los Angeles police) would be a disgrace in a
routine auto accident.''
   ``This is deeply suspicious,'' he added.
   Stone's comments came after California Secretary of State March
Fong Eu opened the long-secret files to the public and displayed
significant items of evidence for reporters. She held aloft a boxed
.22-caliber gun used by convicted assassin Sirhan Sirhan to kill
the U.S. senator on June 5, 1968, after his victory in the
California Democratic presidential primary.
   Among the documents displayed was a certificate showing that
2,410 police photographs in the assassination case were burned on
Aug. 21, 1968.
   The state's chief archivist, John Burns, who cataloged the
massive file for release, speculated that the destroyed photos
could have been duplicates, but said the files contain no such
statement.
   Less surprising, said Stone, was confirmation that police also
destroyed door jambs and ceiling tiles from the kitchen of the Los
Angeles Ambassador Hotel where Kennedy was gunned down. Stone and
other experts maintain those items might have shed light on how
many bullets were fired and on a theory there was a second gunman.
   ``The Los Angeles Police Commission should investigate this,''
he said, referring to a civilian oversight board appointed by the
mayor. ``Mayor (Tom) Bradley should demand it.''
   Asked why he thought the material was destroyed, Stone said,
``The most charitable interpretation is total ineptitude. ... But
you can't rule out suspicious and sinister possibilities.''
   Stone once worked for Rep. Allard Lowenstein, D-N.Y., who raised
questions about the case before he, too, was slain by a gunman in
1980.
   William Booth, a Los Angeles Police Department spokesman, said
he didn't know why the photographs and other materials were
destroyed.
   ``It was 20 years ago and I certainly don't have any independent
recollection,'' Booth said. ``I don't know whether what was done
here is routine or not because I don't know what was done here.''
   Sirhan, a Jordanian immigrant who scribbled in his diary, ``RFK
must die,'' is serving a life term at Soledad prison. Sirhan says
he was the lone assassin but can't remember shooting Kennedy. He
blames his amnesia on alcohol.
   The material released on microfilm Tuesday details interviews
with 4,000 witnesses, including dozens of eyewitnesses, and
comprises 50,000 pages.
   Eu also released a police composite videotape of the
assassination scene. Kennedy is seen entering the kitchen
surrounded by a large crowd. Screams are heard. The badly jostled
camera then shows Kennedy lying in a pool of blood while other
victims stagger about dazed and witnesses are seen weeping.
   The assassination occurred before presidential candidates were
provided with Secret Service protection.
   Also released was a tape of police calls on the night of the
assassination, showing there was a delay in sending police cars and
an ambulance to the scene because the officer on duty didn't grasp
the importance of what had happened.
   Told that there was an emergency at the Ambassador Hotel and
that Kennedy was there, the unidentified police officer responded:
``Big deal!''
   After being told by a hotel employee that Kennedy had been shot,
the officer asked her for the address, apparently unaware of the
location of the one of Los Angeles' largest hotels.
   Documents show that once Kennedy was inside an ambulance, the
senator's distressed wife, Ethel, demanded that attendants keep
their hands off Kennedy.
   One doctor who attended Kennedy in the kitchen complained about
Kennedy being taken to Good Samaritan Hospital, a central receiving
hospital, rather than a private facility with specialists in brain
injuries. But another doctor said it was wise to choose Good
Samaritan, which was only three blocks from the Ambassador.
   A large portion of the newly released police interviews focused
on the allegation that a girl in a polka dot dress was seen with
Sirhan at the hotel and ran away from the assassination scene
shouting, ``We shot him.''
   The report was never verified, but the files show that many
witnesses claimed to have seen a woman with Sirhan that night and
one described a white dress with black or deep violet dots.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880420-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 0439EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ExitPolls     04-20 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Exit Polls,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis' Weakness In New York Primary Contest: the Black Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Primary Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis won white votes across the board
in New York's presidential primary, and pollsters say a sizable
share of the one group he lost _ blacks _ likely would back him as
the Democratic nominee.
   While exit polls Tuesday found soft spots in Dukakis' support,
overall, ``They love him here,'' said CBS News pollster Kathleen A.
Frankovic. Three quarters of the state's Democrats viewed Dukakis
favorably, she noted.
   Still, ``There are weaknesses. Of course there are weaknesses,''
she said. ``This is a not a candidate who has gotten a lot of black
votes.''
   Indeed, roughly 95 percent of black voters went for Jesse
Jackson, and an NBC News exit poll said a third of the black
Democrats held an unfavorable view of Dukakis, to 27 percent
favorable and 40 percent unsure.
   Moreover, 44 percent of the blacks told NBC that Dukakis does
not care about people like them, while just 19 percent said he did
care. ``That is certainly not helpful to him,'' said NBC pollster
Mary Klett.
   But while Klett said Dukakis, if he were the nominee, may have
trouble drawing blacks to the polls, other analysts said the
problem may not be so great. In an ABC News-Washington Post poll,
65 percent of Jackson voters said they would support Dukakis
against Republican George Bush in November.
   ``Jackson voters are much more loyal Democrats,'' said ABC News
pollster Doug Muzzio. By contrast, he said, half the Dukakis voters
would favor Bush in a Jackson-Bush contest, and only 22 percent
would support Jackson.
   In both the ABC and NBC polls just over 25 percent of Jackson
voters said they would not vote in a Dukakis-Bush contest. ``But
that may not point ahead to November,'' Frankovic said, because the
single-candidate fervor of those Jackson voters may fade. Also,
Dukakis has not campaigned actively for the black vote, essentially
ceding it to Jackson in the contests thus far.
   Estimates of the black turnout varied. The ABC-Post poll put it
at 27 percent, up from 19 percent in 1984, but the CBS-Times poll
said it was 22 percent, precisely the same as that poll's 1984
figure.
   In any case, the electorate clearly was polarized. Jackson won
just about 15 percent of the white vote, and slightly more _ 22
percent in the ABC-Post poll _ of the non-Jewish white vote. About
80 percent of Jews and 70 percent of white Catholics supported
Dukakis. Each group was a quarter of the total.
   ``When you look at white voters he's got over 60 percent in all
income groups, over two-thirds in all education groups. He's got
majorities of all ages, majorities of religions,'' ABC's Muzzio
said. ``In this bifurcated electorate, he wins substantial and in
some cases overwhelming majorities.''
   But the Dukakis support was grudging in some cases. In the NBC
poll 57 percent of Dukakis' voters said they would like Gov. Mario
Cuomo to be the nominee, and more than half said they wished
someone else were running. In the CBS-Times poll, 72 percent of
Dukakis voters said they would have voted for Cuomo had he been in
the race.
   ``His support is really sort of mush,'' Klett said of Dukakis.
``It's not really a strong thing.''
   The ABC-Post poll found a measure of ``negative voting'' in the
Dukakis support. About a fifth of the Democrats said they were
voting to stop a candidate from winning rather than to help a
candidate they liked, and three-quarters of those negative voters
went for Dukakis, Muzzio said.
   The racial and religious antipathy showed in Los Angeles Times
exit poll, in which nearly two-thirds of Democrats said they
believed there was ``an element of racism involved in the vote
against Jackson,'' and about another third said they believed
Jackson is anti-Semitic.
   ``This election was very polarized,'' Klett said. ``Jackson
supporters are there; they were with him a month ago, and they're
still there. What's going to happen in the fall is something
Dukakis is going to have to face.''
</TEXT>
