<DOCNO> AP880420-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 0248EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Front-RunnerDukakis Bjt   04-20 0818</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Front-Runner Dukakis, Bjt,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Landslide Raises Prospect of Unity That Seemed Improbable Last
Month</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis' landslide in New York makes him
the undisputed front-runner in the Democratic presidential race and
raises the prospect of a unified, peaceful, broker-free nominating
convention that seemed wildly improbable a few weeks ago.
   Jesse Jackson will press on with his remarkable campaign, but
his slim chance of derailing Dukakis now grows slimmer with each
passing week, particularly if Sen. Albert Gore Jr. halts his
campaign as expected on Thursday.
   ``The Democratic Party's going to be unified and we're going to
stop George Bush this November,'' said Gore on what must have been
the most disappointing night of his campaign. Jackson has said he
wants to ``enable our party to win'' and is determined to ``play a
role in making that happen.''
   Pennsylvania votes next week, and Ohio and Indiana after that,
and none of them offers the large core of black votes that gives
Jackson a secure base from which to spring an upset.
   Gore's campaign suspension after a distant third-place finish in
New York would mean Dukakis no longer had to divide the white vote
with another white candidate.
   The District of Columbia will be Jackson's on May 3. But it
could well be his last victory, barring a late-season protest vote
against a cautious front-runner _ always a California possibility
for the Democrats.
   But the other primaries ahead offer Dukakis a chance to pad the
lead he has begun amassing in nominating delegates.
   Dukakis knows as much, too, even though he points out the
nominating campaign will be contested until the last primary on
June 7. Even as New York was according him his front-runner status
he was making a sharp attack on Bush in the manner of a candidate
who expects to be the nominee.
   ``This fall George Bush is going to be judged by a legacy of ...
pink slips for our workers, golden parachutes for high rollers, and
greenmail for sharp operators on Wall Street,'' he said in
Philadelphia.
   ``I want to make that American dream come alive again, not only
in Trump Towers, not only in fancy apartments all over this
country, not only in a few privileged neighborhoods.''
   Dukakis has managed to achieve his supremacy in the race without
relying on the traditional Democratic party power brokers. The
AFL-CIO hasn't endorsed him or any other Democrat, and Dukakis
managed to pull off his double-digit New York victory without the
endorsement of Gov. Mario Cuomo.
   Gore almost certainly will exit the campaign preaching party
unity, as he did when he congratulated Dukakis in a New York
concession speech.
   And he won't be the only one talking that way.
   Neither Dukakis nor Jackson has shown much penchant for
criticizing the other, and any campaign debate is likely to be long
on Bush-bashing and short on Democratic bickering.
   ``We respect each other. We don't attack each other,'' Dukakis
said. ``You won't see either one of us attempting to hurt or cut up
or otherwise cripple the opponent's campaign.''
   Still, Jackson has the most potential for creating mischief at
the Democratic National Convention this year, and the question most
likely to be asked from now to the opening of the convention on
July 18 is ``What does Jesse want?''
   So far, his principal answer to that question has been to stress
his determination to elect a Democrat the next president.
   When a questioner at a New York breakfast asked Jackson what he
would do if he didn't get the nomination, he replied that it was
important to ``put the nation first and party second and your role
third.''
   And so far, not one word about wanting to be vice president, a
prospect that sends terror through the Democratic party
establishment.
   That's the sort of behavior could make the Democratic convention
very peaceful indeed.
   Democrats are eager to put their nominating war behind them as
soon as reasonably possible without offending Jackson and the
millions of black voters who have joined his crusade.
   Peter D. Kelly, chairman of the California Democratic Party,
said many of the elected and party officials, designated as ``super
delegates'' to the nominating convention, may be reluctant to jump
too quickly onto the Dukakis bandwagon.
   ``They're going to want to be real careful about angering Jesse
Jackson and his supporters,'' said Kelly. ``I, for one, am very
sensitive about offending that constituency.''
   Dukakis is unlikely to put any pressure on Jackson.
   Instead, he will turn his attention to the upcoming primary
states and to the task of enlisting the uncommitted elected
officials, party leaders and uncommitted delegates to his cause.
That will enable him to arrive at the nominating convention in
Atlanta with the delegates needed to be nominated.
   ---
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: David Espo covers presidential politics for the
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
