<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MingoCorruption     04-20 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mingo Corruption,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mingo Sheriffs Sentenced For Selling, Buying Job</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former sheriffs of a mountain coal
mining county received prison terms of up to 10 years for a scheme
in which one sold his job to the other for $100,000.
   Former Mingo County Democratic chairman Johnie Owens, who has
admitted selling his job as sheriff in 1982, sentenced Tuesday to
one to five years in prison and fined $20,000 on state charges of
conspiracy and tax evasion.
   The sentences will run concurrently with a 14-year sentence
Owens received Monday on related federal charges.
   Eddie Hilbert, 45, who has said he gave Owens a $20,000 down
payment for the job, was sentenced Tuesday to one to 10 years in
prison for bribery.
   Circuit Judge Dan O'Hanlon also placed the two on five years'
probation and ordered them to pay as-yet undetermined costs of the
special grand jury investigation of their case.
   Hilbert pleaded guilty to related federal charges Monday and is
scheduled for sentencing June 16.
   West Virginia law prescribes specific sentences for each crime.
Only a parole board can shorten a sentence after a convict serves
the minimum term.
   The county, known historically as the site of the Hatfield-McCoy
feud, is at the center of a two-year political corruption and drug
trafficking investigation in which nearly 50 officials have been
charged.
</TEXT>
