<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Higher In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished lower Wednesday against the
Japanese yen in Tokyo, while stock prices posted a substantial gain.
   The dollar finished the day at 123.90 yen, down 0.47 yen from
its close of 124.37 yen Tuesday. It had opened the day at 124.08
yen and fluctuated between 123.85 yen and 124.09 yen.
   Traders said selling pressure pushed the dollar below the
124.00-yen level at one point during the trading, but the currency
later rose on modest intervention by the Bank of Japan.
   The central bank does not officially comment on its market
activity.
   An exchange dealer at a major commercial bank said some market
participants were taking a cautious attitude toward the dollar in
fear that U.S. monetary authorities would tighten credit in case of
higher-than-expected U.S. consumer price figures for March, which
were scheduled to be announced Wednesday in Washington.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average,
a modest 14.45-point loser Tuesday, gained 207.09 points, or 0.77
percent, closing the day at 26,864.09.
   ``Domestically, there is nothing to cause uneasiness among
investors, such as the possibility of restriction of margin
transactions,'' said Hiromi Yoneyama of Wako Securities.
</TEXT>
