<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ContestFraud     04-20 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contest Fraud,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds Charge Postal Workers With Fraud In Super Bowl Contest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the prize money from a Super Bowl ``Pick
the Score'' contest went to postal workers and their friends who
waited until after the game to submit their entries, using
backdated envelopes, authorities say.
   Fourteen U.S. Postal Service employees and three others were
charged Tuesday with obstructing the mail in separate schemes from
five area post offices, said U.S. Attorney Andrew J. Maloney.
   Seven defendants, including four postal workers, were among the
14 Daily News contest winners and collected $35,000 of the $100,000
in cash prizes, authorities said.
   Two other postal workers split the $50,000 grand prize with its
winner, Judith Febbraro, said U.S. Attorney Andrew J. Maloney.
   Ms. Febbraro, 42, tipped authorities to her fraudulent entry in
February after her romance with one of the postal workers ended,
Maloney said.
   She was not charged, and a portion of her prize money was
recovered, Maloney said.
   The defendants, in separate and unrelated schemes, waited until
after the 1987 Super Bowl and then used their positions or
associations with the post office to mail in numerous entries in
envelopes postmarked before the deadline, Maloney said.
   The workers, who were suspended without pay, were employed at
four post offices in New York City and one in Yonkers.
   Maloney said the first time many of them met was at a dinner for
the winners with quarterback Phil Simms, who led the New York
Giants to a 39-20 victory in the National Football League game.
   ``This newspaper had complete confidence in the integrity of
this contest,'' said Gil Spencer, editor of the Daily News. ``As we
understand it, the only way the contest could have been ripped off
was by a fraud engineered inside the post office by postal
employees, and that's exactly what the Justice Department has
charged.''
   The company that administered the contest for the Daily News _
D.L. Blair, Inc. of Garden City _ received a total of 375,000
entries, Maloney said. The winners were chosen in a random drawing
from the 206 correct responses.
   As part of the investigation, Blair recovered 167 of the entries
with correct scores. At least 107 of those entries were submitted
by postal employees or people closely associated with them,
authorities said.
   Maloney said the scheme was part of an ongoing investigation by
his office and postal inspectors.
   The defendants were charged with obstructing the mail, which
upon conviction carries a maximum five year sentence and a $250,000
fine. Fifteen were arrested Tuesday, two remain at large.
</TEXT>
