<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Koch     04-20 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koch,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor `Did My Best and Failed' In Presidential Primary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It almost seemed at times that New York's
Democratic primary had boiled down to a race between Jesse Jackson
and Mayor Edward I. Koch.
   If so, Koch was clearly the loser.
   ``Mayor Koch made hysteria, I made history,'' said Jackson after
finishing second Tuesday with 37 percent of the vote.
   Jackson lost to Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, although he
won a slim margin over Dukakis in New York City despite bitter
attacks by Koch. And the man the mayor endorsed, Tennessee Sen. Al
Gore Jr., fared miserably.
   Koch conceded Tuesday night that his attacks on Jackson were
apparently a mistake.
   ``I did my best and I failed, but the world ain't over,'' he
said.
   Polls of those who voted Tuesday indicated the primary tactics
may haunt the mayor next year, however, when Koch has said he plans
to run for re-election.
   Fifty-six percent of the voters surveyed in a CBS-New York Times
exit poll said they disagreed with Koch's criticism of Jackson. And
60 percent of those polled by NBC said they don't want Koch to run
for re-election.
   ``Ed Koch was certainly not a winner in this and he looks like a
big loser,'' said an ABC pollster, Doug Muzzio.
   Koch campaigned tirelessley alongside Gore, taking over the
headlines when he sharply criticized Jackson's positions on Israel
and said Jews would ``have to be crazy'' to vote for him.
   Asked Tuesday night if he would make the same remarks if he
could turn back the clock, Koch replied: ``Obviously, I would not
make them the way I did because, apparently, they were not helpful
to Al Gore.''
   Later, appearing on ABC's ``Nightline,'' he added: ``Apparently
the word crazy is not acceptable and I promise never to use it
again.''
   Jackson's campaign chairman, California Assembly Speaker Willie
Brown, credited Koch with improving Jackson's showing.
   ``If he had been more subtle about it, it may have been more
devastating to the Jackson campaign,'' Brown said. ``But the
flagrant display of anti-Jackson attitudes ... have embarrassed
some of the people in New York who may have been otherwise against
Jackson.''
   Democratic Party Chairman Paul Kirk praised Jackson for showing
``laudable tolerance and restraint'' in the face of ``some bitter
invectives that were visited on him, (and) not by the candidates,
who have been positive.''
</TEXT>
