<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0604</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Weather Lashes Northern California; Showers Elsewhere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm anchored off the Northern California coast brought
drenching rain and thunderstorms to much of the state and snow to
the Lake Tahoe area, but authorities anticipated little relief from
the dry winter.
   Elsewhere, a cold front resulted in showers today from central
Ontario across the northern Plains.
   Showers and thunderstorms spread across southern Florida as a
cold front sagged southward across the area. Thunderstorms were
accompanied by heavy rain across parts of southeast Florida.
   Other showers were isolated over west-central Kansas.
Snowshowers were scattered across parts of central New York.
   Nearly an inch of rain was measured at downtown Sacramento,
Calif., and street flooding was reported Tuesday evening across
northeast Sacramento County.
   Two tornados struck in Folsom, about 20 miles east of
Sacramento, on Tuesday afternoon, damaging several houses but
resulting in no injuries, police said.
   The precipitation didn't mean managers of the Northern
California watersheds were ready to call an end to the drought.
   ``It would take a tremendous amount of rain to get us into a
normal situation,'' said Bill Helms, spokesman for the state's
Flood Operations Center in Sacramento. ``Dribs and drabs won't help
us much at this point.''
   A flash flood watch issued overnight for coastal mountain and
foothill communities of southern Santa Barbara, Ventura and Los
Angeles counties.
   A snow advisory continued overnight for the Shasta Siskiyou
mountains, northeast California and the southern Sierra Nevada.
   A winter weather advisory continued for the Southern California
mountains, with up to a foot of snow reported above 7,000 feet just
west of Lake Tahoe.
   Showers were reported across southwest Oregon with snow in the
southern areas of the Cascades. Isolated showers and thunderstorms
were occurring from north central Nevada through southeast Idaho
into north central Wyoming.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
for most of the nation west of the Rockies and across eastern
Montana, eastern Wyoming and portions of Nebraska and South Dakota;
snowshowers for much of northern Nevada and the higher elevations
of eastern California. Also rain or snowshowers should be scattered
over Michigan, New York and northern New England. A few showers
should linger over southern Florida.
   High temperatures should be in the 80s for most of Florida and
from the southern Plains to southeast Arizona; in the 90s in
southwest Texas; 40s or 50s from New England across New Jersey,
Pennsylvania, the upper Ohio Valley the Great Lakes, northern
Plains, and most of Montana west to Northern California; the 60s or
70s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 20
degrees at Alpena, Mich., to 78 at Miami and Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 45 fair; Boston 41 windy; Buffalo 33 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 50 fair; Cincinnati 31 fair; Cleveland 31 fair;
Detroit 36 partly cloudy; Miami 79 partly cloudy; New York 43
partly cloudy; Philadelphia 42 fair; Pittsburgh 31 fair; Portland,
Maine 38 cloudy; Washington 40 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 48 cloudy; Chicago 41 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
55 fair; Denver 49 partly cloudy; Des Moines 46 fair; Indianapolis
35 fair; Kansas City 51 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 45 cloudy;
Nashville 37 fair; New Orleans 60 fair; St. Louis 48 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 55 fair; Anchorage 41 fair; Las Vegas 67
cloudy; Los Angeles 53 rain; Phoenix 74 fair; Salt Lake City 55
partly cloudy; San Diego 60 rain; San Francisco 53 partly cloudy;
Seattle 57 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 34 cloudy; Toronto 28 fair.
</TEXT>
