<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     04-20 0838</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers, Boaters Criticize Coast Guard's Commercial Towing
Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official of the Coast Guard says a policy
that leaves boaters in need of non-emergency help adrift and
waiting for commercial tow operators while trained Coast Guard
volunteers standby should be changed.
   The policy, adopted following 1983 instructions from Congress,
limiting Coast Guard towing to emergency situations only, has
created situations where trained and eager Coast Guard Auxiliary
crews arrive first, but are forced to simply standby and wait for
commercial towers.
   Lawmakers, recreational boaters and Commodore William C. Harr,
head of the Coast Guard Auxiliary, on Tuesday told members of the
House Merchant Marine and Fisheries Coast Guard subcommittee the
policy is creating severe morale problems among the 32,000 civilian
volunteer force, which was created in 1939 to augment the Coast
Guard in World War II..
   ``This policy has dealt the organization a body blow by
undermining the pride which members had in helping their fellow
boaters,'' Harr said. ``I am convinced that this dissatisfaction is
a leading indicator of a massive and irreplaceable loss of trained,
qualified, experienced auxiliarists.''
   However Rep. Gerry E. Studds, D-Mass., suggested that the Reagan
administration is unable to decide on a policy because the issue
pits the concept of privatization by allowing commercial operators
to handle all non-emergency towing against the concept of
volunteerism embodied by the auxiliary.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ford Recalling '84 Ranger, Bronco II Trucks, EPA Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. is recalling about 106,000 1984
Ranger and Bronco II trucks to bring their emissions control
systems into compliance with federal regulations, the government
and Ford said.
   The Environmental Protection Agency said Tuesday the recall
affects only the trucks with 2.8-liter engines and automatic
transmissions. California trucks, which are built to meet different
emissions standards, are not involved.
   The EPA said its tests had discovered the trucks' exhausts put
out hydrocarbons and carbon monoxide in excess of federal
regulations, but the agency was unable to identify a defective
component or part failure as the cause.
   ``Ford has agreed to adjust the choke and ignition timing to new
specifications and install new carburetor metering jets to bring
the trucks into compliance with the standards,'' the EPA said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>__</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Calls For Long-Term Investment In Space</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan says the United States must
make a commitment to long-term investment in space exploration in
order advance the country's leadership in that area and he is
asking Congress and the American people to join him in those
efforts.
   ``Can we afford to stop our exploration and wait for others to
pass us?'' Reagan asked on Tuesday in a speech at the annual
government-industry dinner of the Electronic Industries Association.
   ``Tonight I ask Congress and all the American people to join me
in making the long-term investment required to advance U.S.
leadership in space,'' Reagan said. ``We must begin that investment
by funding the increases I've proposed for our civil space
program.''
   Reagan has proposed $1 billion in the next fiscal year that
begins Oct. 1 for the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
to build a U.S. space station.
   The president also used the speech as an opportunity to plug the
Strategic Defense Initiative, or Star Wars, his proposal for a
space-based defense against nuclear missiles.
   ``Five years ago I proposed SDI and, much to my satisfaction, we
have made tremendous progress in that research,'' he said. ``We
must not stop dreaming because a few naysayers insist on limiting
our options for a safe and secure future.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>American Red Cross Starts Workplace AIDS Education Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Red Cross survey indicates that
employee fears about AIDS and how to deal with co-workers who have
the fatal disease are threatening a substantial disruption of the
workplace.
   The study, released Tuesday, showed that 42 percent of 2,000
workers questioned nationwide said they would not work with anyone
who has AIDS and 29 percent said they felt so strongly about it
that they would quit their jobs before working with an AIDS patient.
   AIDS is a contagious disease that destroys the immune system,
rendering the body incapable of resisting other diseases and
infections.
   Researcher David M. Herold of the Georgia Institute of
Technology, who conducted the survey, said there already have been
incidents in which work came to a standstill as a result of
unreasonable fear toward the disease.
   He cited an incident at a a state government office in Florida
which was shut down after a worker with AIDS who became ill had
vomited in his office.
   In another instance Herold said a power company was forced to
cancel a cardiopulminary resuscitation training program when
workers said they would not use the mouth-to-mouth breathing
technique on a co-worker afflicted with the disease.
   ``They (the workers) said that if anybody touched a live wire
and got electrocuted, they would just have to die because nobody
would do CPR,'' said Herold.
   He declined to identify the state government office or the
utility company.
</TEXT>
