<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--TurtleCrossing     04-20 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Turtle Crossing,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Helping Turtles Get to the Other Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYBEE ISLAND, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tybee Island residents who know turtles
have a good reason to cross the road are trying to make sure they
get to the other side.
   Every spring, female terrapins come out of the marshes, looking
for high ground to lay their eggs.
   ``Every spring, for two to three months, they get killed on the
highway looking for high nesting sites,'' Gretchen Powell,
coordinator for the Tybee Terrapin Turtle Project, said recently.
``They wander quite widely. I don't have any actual numbers, but a
large number of them are killed each year.''
   So this year, the Tybee Island Chamber of Commerce and the
turtle project are spending $1,000 for signs alsong the Islands
Expressway near the Tybee Island city limits warning motorists to
watch for turtles.
   Volunteers also will begin taking a survey of turtle sightings,
and teach students in schools here about the turtles.
   The female terrapins range from 6 to 9{ inches across their
shells. They are found in tidal waters from the Gulf of Mexico to
the mid-Atlantic.
</TEXT>
