<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 0639EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Diamond     04-20 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Diamond,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pear-Shaped Diamond Sold for a Record $9.13 Million</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE ROTHENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It took all of two minutes to complete the $9.13
million sale of the largest diamond ever to go on the block,
setting a world record for any gem sold at auction.
   The anonymous buyer bid by telephone Tuesday night for the
85.91-carat, pear-shaped diamond, described as a ``drop of frozen
light.''
   ``It represents the very essence of this planet in its simplest
and purest form,'' said Neil Letson, gemologist and jewelry
historian.
   The sale of the diamond was part of an overall jewelry auction
that included gems belonging to the late Clare Boothe Luce. The
auction brought a total of $36 million, setting another record: for
a jewelry sale in the United States.
   ``The sale was a great success,'' said John D. Block, director
of Sotheby's jewelry division.
   The nameless diamond _ whose owner was not identified _ has been
graded D color, the highest possible rating, meaning it is
perfectly cut and flawless.
   Bidding opened at $6 million. Someone in the room bid $7
million, then bids increased in increments of $100,000, according
to Diana Levitt, director of corporate affairs for Sotheby's.
   The gem sold for $8.3 million, plus a 10 percent commission.
   The sale exceeded the 1980 record at a Sotheby's auction in
Geneva where $6.6 million was bid for a pair of ear pendants with
four pear-shaped diamonds totaling 131.86 carats.
   Letson placed the diamond historically at slightly below the
Cullinan III, now in the British Crown Jewels collection, and
slightly above the Spoonmaker Diamond, now in Istanbul's Topkapi
Museum.
   Also on the block Tuesday night were jewels and other
possessions of Mrs. Luce, the former congresswoman and ambassador
to Italy.
   Her collection, which included pieces from Van Cleef & Arpels,
Tiffany, Cartier and Bulgari, sold for $2.16 million. All the
pieces in the collection were sold.
   In addition, nearly $600,000 worth of furniture and decorations
belonging to Mrs. Luce were sold.
   Proceeds of the Luce sale will go to the Clare Boothe Luce Fund,
administered by the Henry Luce Foundation. The fund supports
scholarships and fellowships for women in the applied sciences,
such as mathematics and chemistry.
   Block characterized Mrs. Luce's jewelry collection as ``a
fascinating combination of important jewelry and uncommon
historical significance which reflects the life and style of an
exceptional woman.''
   Mrs. Luce, who also was known as an author and war
correspondent, began her writing career at Vogue. In 1935, she
married Henry R. Luce, the late chairman of Time Inc.
   She served as war correspondent for Life magazine during World
War II, and then served two terms in Congress as a Republican
representing Connecticut, starting with her first victory in 1942.
   Mrs. Luce was appointed ambassador to Italy by then-President
Dwight D. Eisenhower in 1952. She remained active in GOP politics
until her death last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
