<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 0658EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Cubans-Deportation     04-20 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cubans-Deportation,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>About 1,000 Cubans Move Step Closer To Deportation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Immigration officials will inform about 1,000
imprisoned Mariel Cubans that they are considered a risk to the
public, putting them a step closer to deportation.
   Under an agreement between the U.S. government and Mariel
prisoners who rioted at a federal penitentiary in Atlanta last
year, the detainees deemed ``non-releaseable'' have 30 days to
appeal to the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service.
   Duke Austin, an INS spokesman in Washington, said the agency
would begin sending letters this week to the 1,000 prisoners who
have been considered risks to the community.
   If their appeal to the INS fails, the prisoners can appeal to a
special Justice Department panel, and get two more appeals if the
government eventually orders them deported.
   ``I think this is due process, and then some,'' said Justice
Department spokesman Patrick Korten.
   ``It's a paper review. It's a joke,'' said Rafael Penalver, a
lawyer here who is an advocate for the Cuban prisoners who object
to their detention but also fear deportation to their communist
homeland.
   Penalver says those prisoners were not allowed to present
evidence or witnesses, and also won't receive hearings if they
appeal.
   A House subcommittee heard similar arguments in February.
Federal officials responded that they were already going beyond
what was required by law because of an agreement made when riots
broke out last November among 3,800 Mariel Cubans in indefinite
detention.
   The Cubans, who had come to the United States in an illegal
boatlift from the Cuban port of Mariel, all had committed crimes in
the United States and served out their prison terms before
immigration officials detained them.
   As of April 8, about 970 detainees had been freed and 1,100
recommended for release to their families or halfway houses,
officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
