<HEAD>Bodies of Guardsmen Found After Weekend Disappearance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT CLINTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bodies of two Ohio National
Guardsmen, missing for two days in Lake Erie, were discovered after
a search for them had been called off.
   The bodies of Spec. 4 Wayne C. Wingate, 30, of Lima, and Sgt.
Melvin Wisecup, 31, of Waynesfield, were found washed ashore a
short distance from each other Tuesday morning, said Guard
spokeswoman Sonya Elam.
   The men disappeared while on one of two 27-foot Army patrol
boats dispatched from Camp Perry Sunday to clear an area of
civilian boats prior to start of the 4th U.S. Army rifle matches.
The matches were later suspended.
   The boat has not been found and authorities were still
investigating the deaths today.
   A search by the U.S. Coast Guard was canceled at sunset Monday
after units from the U.S. and Canadian coast guards found no
evidence of the men, members the 837th Engineer Co.
   Local residents found Wingate's body near the docks of Sugar
Rocks Harbor and Marina and notified authorities. Wisecup's body
was found a short time later by guardsmen after Guard helicopters
were put in the air to help with the search, Ms. Elam said.
