<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mayor'sSuicide     04-20 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mayor's Suicide,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Is Apparent Suicide Victim After Indictment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DIXMOOR, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One day after Mayor Kenneth Fisher was
charged with taking bribes to cover up an alleged gambling
conspiracy, he apparently took his own life, officials in this
Chicago suburb said.
   Dixmoor Police Chief Anton Graff, whose undercover work for the
FBI led to Fisher's indictment, said the mayor's wife, Cathy, found
his body about 4 p.m. Tuesday, slumped behind the wheel of their
pickup truck. The engine was running and the garage was filled with
exhaust, Graff said.
   Graff said he had heard of talk from Fisher, 59, that ``there's
nothing to live for.'' He called the apparent suicide ``a very
tragic end to a very long investigation.''
   A federal grand jury indicted Fisher and two other men Monday in
connection with a gambling operation that allegedly operated out of
two Dixmoor taverns for about five years.
   Fisher, mayor of the community of about 4,200 for seven years,
was accused of taking monthly bribes from mid-1982 to August 1987
to cover up the operation.
   If convicted, the mayor would have faced up to 55 years in
prison and a fine of up to $1.25 million, U.S. Attorney Anton
Valukas said.
   Fisher's attorney, David Miesmer, said Fisher had left a note
but added that neither he, Mrs. Fisher nor Graff had read it late
Tuesday.
   The mayor had ``maintained his innocence throughout,'' Miesmer
said.
   Graff said the cause of death appeared to be carbon monoxide
poisoning, but the Cook County medical examiner's office had not
identified a definite cause.
   Graff and village board members said the mayor had appeared
depressed since the FBI had interviewed him in March.Fisher, who
had diabetes, had to be hospitalized about two weeks ago because he
stopped taking his medication, Graff said.
</TEXT>
