<2ND_LINE>PM-Transvestite Thieves,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Two Men Believed Transvestite Thieves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thieves with an eye for
``top-of-the-line'' women's fashions had baffled police here for
two months, until authorities discovered they were dealing with a
ring of transvestites.
   Detectives investigating robberies of at least 10 boutiques in
affluent south Palm Beach County on Tuesday arrested two men _ one
dressed in women's clothes _ with a carload of beachwear stolen
moments earlier.
   The men are part of an organized group of 10 to 15 men who dress
as women and were responsible for thefts of at least $200,000 in
women's clothes during the past two months, said Sgt. Ken Deischer.
   ``Some are transvestites, but we can't say they all are because
we don't know who all of them are,'' Deischer said.
   The thieves who threw a rock through the plate-glass window at
Doreen's Swimwear on Tuesday cleared the racks of about $10,000 in
swimsuits, rompers, coverups, shorts and tops, officials said.
   ``The things they took were top-of-the-line,'' store manager
Michael Goldstein said. ``These swimsuits retail for $80 to $150
and coverups go for $90 to $220.''
   One of the suspects arrested Tuesday was dressed in black
women's slacks, black midriff top barely covering a black bra,
jewelry and makeup, Deischer said.
   What the thieves were doing with the stolen clothes remains a
mystery, Deischer said.
   ``I'd be curious to find out where it's going. I mean, you're
talking about $200,000 worth of clothing,'' Deischer said. ``And
that's more than they could be wearing.''
