<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Singleton     04-20 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Singleton,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Small Town Wary of Being Home To Rapist-Mutilator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AZALEA, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this community gathered to
denounce a local religious group's plans to give sanctuary to
rapist-mutilator Lawrence Singleton after his release from parole
in California.
   ``We want to do everything we can to keep him from coming
here,'' Anita Van Housen, president of the Cow Creek Homeowner's
Association, said as about 60 people who gathered at the Azalea
Grange on Tuesday night. ``But we can't tolerate lawlessness. We
aren't a lawless community.''
   Van Housen was referring to eight shotgun blasts fired last
Thursday at buildings owned by the Bride of Christ Church, whose
pastor has offered the 60-year-old Singleton a job and a home.
   The shots broke windows and damaged a tractor. Ray Duncan,
Douglas County undersheriff, said authorities also received reports
of fences being cut on church property, which he told the crowd
``does no one any good.''
   Singleton was escorted quietly off the grounds of San Quentin
Prison on Monday to avoid a mob scene when he is freed from parole
restrictions April 25, said Bob Gore, spokesman for the California
Department of Corrections.
   Singleton served most of his one-year parole in a trailer on the
prison grounds for his own protection after his release from prison
last year sparked angry protests that forced him from town to town.
   He was convicted of raping 15-year-old hitchhiker Mary Bell
Vincent and hacking off her forearms with an ax in 1978. He served
eight years in prison.
   Thomas Clyde Smith Jr., the church pastor, did not attend the
meeting in this southern Oregon community to discuss fears arising
from his plans to shelter Singleton.
   ``It would be a real real bad idea to make foolhardy mistake of
allowing him to move here without having our say ... at the
possible sacrifice of one of our children,'' said Kelly Repp, 35, a
Glendale firefighter and father of three girls.
   ``I'm just terrified of having him here,'' Repp said. ``My
daughters are terrified of him, too.''
</TEXT>
