<HEAD>Jackson Offers Dukakis Congratulations, Vows To Fight On</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 7 grafs new; picks up 7th graf pvs, The people ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson today congratulated New York
primary winner Michael Dukakis for resisting the ``temptation to
take the campaign to the gutter,'' but vowed to stay in the
Democratic race through the final round of primaries June 7.
   Jackson said it was too early to consider the vice presidency.
``Let's wait until June 8 to make that kind of judgment,'' he said
on NBC's ``Today'' show. ``We're very much in this race. We expect
great things to happen.
   Dukakis scored a decisive win over Jackson, 51 percent to 37
percent, in the New York primary Tuesday.
   ``In this case you had a mayor with a strong supporting cast who
led the drive using race and religion as a litmus test,'' Jackson
said of the New York results.
   New York Mayor Edward I. Koch harshly criticized Jackson during
the primary campaign. Koch supported Albert Gore Jr., who finished
a distant third.
   Jackson, appearing on CBS-TV, congratulated Dukakis, not only
for his win but because ``he resisted the temptation to take the
campaign to the gutter. Good for him and good for America.''
   Jackson said he had met with Gore on Tuesday night to discuss
the Tennessee senator's ``future options'' in the campaign. But he
said he didn't know whether Gore was ready to support him.
   ``The people of New York spoke loudly today and very
effectively,'' said Jackson's national campaign manager, Gerald
Austin. ``They are not going to put up with divisiveness. They are
to be commended for that.''
   The New York primary campaign proved to be a ferocious affair
that featured an almost daily tongue-lashing from Koch directed at
Jackson. Koch had said that Jews would have to be ``crazy'' to vote
for Jackson. Jackson's campaign manager said Koch was ``insane.''
   ``We're disappointed we didn't win, and we congratulate Gov.
Dukakis. We also congratulate the people of New York for pushing
aside what Mayor Koch tried to do,'' Austin said.
   Austin was optimistic about prospects in next Tuesday's
Pennsylvania primary and the Ohio primary, a week later, as well as
later big-state contests like California.
   ``We think we're still in this race,'' he said.
