<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0579,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Nearly Motionless In Thin European Trade; Gold Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf from bottom pvs ``The Hong Kong...' with 1 graf
to UPDATE with delayed closing gold.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was nearly motionless in dull European
trading late this morning. Gold prices rose.
   Dealers said they didn't expect much movement during the rest of
the session unless the report on the U.S. consumer price index
(CPI), to be released at 1:30 p.m. (8:30 a.m. EDT), contains
surprises.
   ``The dollar is incredibly stable,'' one Milan trader said.
``The market is bearish, there's no doubt about that, but the
possibility of central bank intervention and the (Persian) Gulf
situation is supporting it.''
   He predicted that ``sooner or later the market will push the
dollar lower,'' but that in the short run the dollar was likely to
remain stuck in a very tight range.
   If the price index report for March shows that U.S. inflation is
picking up, U.S. interest rates likely will rise and dollar could
move higher, traders said.
   If the index rises the expected 0.4 percent or less, the dollar
is likely to resume its decline, traders said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.47 yen to a closing 123.90 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 123.97 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.6615 West German marks, down from 1.6625
   _1.3741 Swiss francs, down from 1.3752
   _5.6440 French francs, down from 5.6465
   _1.8636 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8642
   _1,235.25 Italian lire, down from 1,235.75
   _1.2297 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2337
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.8950, stronger
than $1.8930 Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $457.30 a troy ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $456.50. At mid-morning today, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$458.00.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $457.80, up from $457.00 late
Tuesday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.35 to close at a bid $458.94.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.49 a troy
ounce, up from Tuesday's $6.46.
