<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 0829EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-NYPrimary 1stLd-Writethru a0540 04-20 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NY Primary, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0540,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Geographic and Ethnic Coalition Gives Dukakis His New York Win</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs lead to remove extraneous ``win.'' Changes delegate
figures in 10th graf, Of the</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis laced
together a broad geographic and ethnic coalition to capture the
delegate-rich New York Democratic presidential primary and solidify
his claim to front-runner status.
   Unofficial returns showed Jesse Jackson with a narrow lead over
Dukakis in New York City, a fact he said was proof that his
candidacy was still viable.
   ``We won the Big Apple,'' Jackson declared Tuesday night. But
Dukakis triumphed virtually everywhere else, drubbing Jackson in
the suburbs and upstate New York.
   ``I love New York,'' Dukakis told a boisterous New York City
victory rally.
   In winning Tuesday's New York primary decisively, Dukakis may
have knocked Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. out of the race. Gore
aides and friends said he was considering ending his cash-strapped
campaign.
   With 99 percent of New York precincts reporting, the unofficial
vote looked this way:
   _Dukakis had 783,568 votes or 51 percent.
   _Jackson had 573,112 or 37 percent.
   _Gore had 156,052 or 10 percent.
   Of the 255 delegates at stake in the Democratic primary, 164
were expected to go to Dukakis; 89 to Jackson; and two to Gore.
   The Republican primary in New York was little more than a
formality along the road to Vice President George Bush's eventual
nomination. He captured 92 of the 96 delegates at stake in a race
that saw less than 10 percent of the eligible Republicans turn out.
Four went to Rep. Jack Kemp, who abandoned his campaign some time
back.
   Turnout was much heavier in the Democratic primary, with more
than 40 percent of the eligible voters going to the polls. In 1984,
39 percent showed up.
   The unofficial returns had Jackson leading Dukakis in New York
City by about 6,500 votes out of the almost 1 million cast.
However, in the suburbs, Dukakis had an almost 90,000-vote margin
and upstate it was a more than 120,000-vote margin.
   What happened, according to exit polls, was that Jackson
collected about 95 percent of the black vote, about 15 percent of
the white vote and Dukakis won almost everything else, running
strong among Jews and pulling out other white ethnics. The
Massachusetts governor did especially well among Catholics.
   The Dukakis draw had some Democrats smiling about a possible
strong showing in November if he winds up with the nomination.
   ``If they're coming out today, that's the first indication
they'll be coming out in November,'' said John Marino, a top New
York party official and political aide to New York Gov. Mario
Cuomo, of the possible fall support for Dukakis from the white
ethnic voters, a group that has gone heavily to Republicans in
recent national elections.
   In winning New York, Dukakis easily bested Walter Mondale's 44
percent win in 1984, a victory engineered by Cuomo's political
machine. Jackson finished about 10 percentage points higher than
four years ago when he got 26 percent of the New York vote. Gary
Hart took second spot in the 1984 primary with 27 percent of the
vote.
   While Dukakis handed Jackson a considerable setback, he did it
without directly attacking him. But exit polls indicated that many
blacks didn't feel comfortable with Dukakis and said he wasn't
sensitive to their needs.
   Dukakis said he recognized the potential problem, but noted that
in his Massachusetts races he had ``always gotten strong minority
support.'' He said if he is the nominee, ``I'll be reaching out.''
   Gore, on the other hand, became the first of the Democratic
candidates to go directly after Jackson, talking about the need to
elect a ``president, not a preacher.''
   Then Gore got the Koch endorsement and the attacks, now coming
from Koch, became more strident. Jews would have to be ``crazy'' to
vote for Jackson and Jackson couldn't be trusted to tell the truth
under stress, said Koch.
   Gore eventually said Koch was ``speaking for himself.''
Jackson's campaign manager, Gerald Austin, dismissed Koch as
``Crazy Eddie.''
   After the primary results were in, Koch appeared contrite.
   ``I said what I thought was true, but obviously it did not help
Al Gore,'' said the mayor.
   With the campaign appearing to narrow to a two-man race, Dukakis
said he expected that he and Jackson would avoid strong criticisms
of each other.
   ``Neither of us believes that cutting up the other guy is the
way you win elections,'' said the governor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
