<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--TooTall     04-20 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Too Tall,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City and Developer Reach Accord on Oversized Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A developer who built a midtown skyscraper 11
feet too tall has reached a settlement with the city that allows
him to keep the extra footage if he constructs rehearsal space for
non-profit dance groups.
   The solution, announced Tuesday by both parties, will cost
developer Ian Bruce Eichner more than $2 million, said his lawyer,
Howard Hornstein.
   The city Planning Commission had refused in December to grant
retroactive approval for additions to Cityspire, a 72-story
building on West 56th Street.
   According to Hornstein, the floor slabs of the structure had to
be thickened by about 2 inches to increase the structure's
stability. As a result of this and some miscalculations, the luxury
condominium building wound up 813.53 feet high, as opposed to the
802.65 feet that had been approved.
   The settlement is subject to approval by the city's Landmarks
Preservation Commission, the city Planning Commission and the Board
of Estimate.
</TEXT>
