<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 0902EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Frats-Beer     04-20 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Frats-Beer,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beer Ban Effective Immediately To Head Off Giant Toga Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EUGENE, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   University of Oregon officials have banned
beer kegs at fraternities and sororities and made the order
effective immediately to head off a ``wild toga party,'' according
to a school official.
   Gerard Moseley, vice president for student affairs, said Tuesday
that the ban took effect when he and university President Paul Olum
issued a memo Monday.
   Moseley said the administration is trying to help university
housing organizations comply with state liquor laws.
   He said advance word about the tough new policy on alcohol
prompted some students to talk about ``closing the street ... for
one last big party,'' an event the administration wanted to avoid.
   The Oregon Liquor Control Commission has agreed to tell
distributors to notify the university any time a keg is purchased
for one of its housing organizations, Moseley said.
   ``People who buy a keg and take it someplace other than the
address they said they were going to take it are going to have
their own set of penalties to deal with, including seizure of the
vehicle used to transport it,'' he said.
   The ban prohibits bulk beer purchases, defined as ones made by
three or more students who pool their money to buy alcoholic
beverages.
   University-affiliated housing groups will also be required to
sponsor alcohol and drug educational programs at least twice each
academic year.
   Moseley said some housing groups include students over the age
of 21 but most have not reached legal drinking age. Attempts to get
the housing groups to police their parties have been unsuccessful,
he added.
   The university has an enrollment of about 17,500 students.
</TEXT>
