<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 0911EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Gang-Juveniles     04-20 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gang-Juveniles,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gang Arrests Add to Youth Overcrowding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Recent sweeps by police through gang-infested
areas have jammed juvenile detention centers, forcing hundreds of
youths to sleep on jail floors, authorities said.
   ``As we continue the sweeps, we need to take more steps to hold
these additional kids,'' Chief Probation Officer Barry J. Nidorf
told the Board of Supervisors on Tuesday.
   He urged approval of a $2 million expansion plan that would add
157 beds to the county's three juvenile detention facilities, which
currently have 1,317 beds.
   The board tentatively approved the expansion, which would be
accomplished by remodeling parts of each juvenile facility, and
asked Nidorf and Chief Administrative Officer Richard Dixon to find
a funding source.
   Nidorf said roundups of gang members and drug-related arrests
made by police officers and sheriff's deputies helped push the
juvenile jail population up to 2,006 last month, 52 percent above
capacity.
   Officials reduced that number by about 250 by suspending many
probation violations, shaving time for people in weekend work crews
and expanding home supervision programs.
   Still, as many as 450 inmates have had to sleep on mattresses on
the floor, Nidorf said. ``All the other services, such as
schooling, eating and recreation, are not impacted, and we have a
sufficient staff.''
