<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Primary-Koch 1stLd-Writethru a0528 04-20 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Primary-Koch, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0528,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koch on Presidential Primary: `I Did My Best and I Failed'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Primary Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts new grafs 5-7 with Jackson quotes today, ``In this
xxx</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At times, it almost seemed that New York's
Democratic presidential primary had been reduced to a race between
two men: Jesse Jackson and Mayor Edward I. Koch.
   If so, Koch was clearly the loser.
   ``Mayor Koch made hysteria,'' said Jackson, after a strong
second-place showing Tuesday night. ``I made history.''
   Although Jackson lost the statewide race to Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis, he won narrowly in New York City despite bitter
attacks by Koch against Jackson. And the man the mayor endorsed,
Sen. Al Gore Jr., fared miserably.
   ``In this case you had a mayor with a strong supporting cast who
led the drive, using race and relgion as a litmus test,'' Jackson
said today on NBC's ``Today'' show.'
   ``Leadership has an obligation to set the moral tone, it has an
obligation to expand and build a coalition, to relieve people of
their fears and insecurities,'' Jackson said on ABC-TV's ``Good
Morning America.''
   He said the news media did not criticize the mayor when it would
have counted.
   During the campaign, Jackson had refused to comment on Koch's
attacks except to note New York's touchy state of race relations
and compare the mayor's comments to yelling fire in a crowded
theater.
   Koch, a man hardly given to humility, conceded Tuesday night
that his attacks on Jackson were apparently a mistake, given Gore's
defeat.
   ``I did my best and I failed, but the world ain't over,'' he
said.
   The world isn't over, but it may become a more difficult place
for Koch, who reiterated his intention to run for re-election next
year. Exit polls indicated that his hardball tactics may cost him
in 1989.
   Fifty-six percent of the voters surveyed in a CBS-New York Times
exit poll said they disagreed with Koch's criticism of Jackson. And
six of 10 voters polled by NBC said they don't want Koch to run for
re-election.
   The negative poll results also could have come from such factors
as a corruption scandal that has hung over Koch's third term and
racial tensions in the city.
   ``Ed Koch was certainly not a winner in this and he looks like a
big loser,'' said Doug Muzzio, an ABC pollster.
   Koch not only endorsed Gore, he campaigned alongside the senator
from Tennessee tirelessly. And it was Koch who captured headlines
with his strident attacks on Jackson.
   But Gore captured only 10 percent of the popular vote statewide
and nine percent in the city.
   Koch criticized Jackson's positions on Israel, saying Jews would
``have to be crazy'' to vote for him. The mayor then called Jackson
arrogant for failing to march in a Salute to Israel parade. The day
of the parade, he said Jackson ``can't stand stress, and then he
lies under stress.''
   Asked Tuesday night whether he would make the same remarks if he
could turn back the clock, Koch replied, ``Obviously, I would not
make them the way I did because, apparently, they were not helpful
to Al Gore.''
   Later, appearing on ABC-TV's ``Nightline,'' he added:
``Apparently the word `crazy' is not acceptable and I promise never
to use it again.''
   Although Gore thanked Koch for his help, he also seemed to
distance himself from the mayor's tactics. After congratulating
Jackson for his showing, Gore said, ``I didn't want to stop Jesse
Jackson. I just wanted to start Al Gore.''
   Jackson's campaign chairman, California Assembly Speaker Willie
Brown, credited Koch with improving Jackson's showing.
   ``If he had been more subtle about it, it may have been more
devastating to the Jackson campaign,'' Brown said. ``But the
flagrant display of anti-Jackson attitudes ... have embarrassed
some of the people in New York who may have been otherwise against
Jackson.''
</TEXT>
