<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0497,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>After New York Win, Dukakis Starts Zeroing In On Bush</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 11 grafs with Dukakis comment today, picking
up in 6th graf pvs, ``Today was; cuts last 7 grafs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis left New York triumphant today,
cautioning that his nomination is not yet inevitable but already
focusing on George Bush and the Republicans with a promise to
``take our message, the Democratic message, to every part of the
country.''
   ``Yesterday obviously was a wonderful day in New York,'' Dukakis
said at a morning news conference. ``I also know, however, that
nothing in the world is inevitable, and we've got much to do in the
Pennsylvania primary this week and the primaries to follow.''
   Dukakis launched his campaign in the next primary state,
Pennsylvania, even before the polls here had closed.
   ``This fall George Bush is going to be judged by a legacy of ...
pink slips for our workers, golden parachutes for high rollers and
greenmail for sharp operators on Wall Street,'' he said in
Philadelphia Tuesday night..
   ``I want to make that American dream come alive again, not only
in Trump Towers, not only in fancy apartments all over this
country, not only in a few privileged neighborhoods.''
   Dukakis said he spoke by telephone with Jesse Jackson early
today but said he declined an invitation to meet with Albert Gore
Jr., who may withdraw after his dismal third-place finish in New
York.
   ``I'm sure we'll be talking. He wanted to meet this morning and
I just couldn't do it,'' the Massachusetts governor said. ``I've
got to get back to Boston. I've got a very important meeting at 10
o'clock of my anti-crime council and a very full agenda and I just
had to get back there. ... He's a good guy and I've enjoyed getting
to know him and I respect him.''
   Dukakis said Gore's withdrawal from the race is ``something he
has to decide.'' He said he would be willing to help Gore or any
other candidate pay off campaign debts.
   The governor said Jackson called him with congratulations. Asked
if he would consider Jackson as a running mate, Dukakis said, ``I
wouldn't rule anything in or out.''
   Dukakis planned to resume campaigning Thursday in Ohio, which
has its primary in two weeks.
   Celebrating Tuesday night, he predicted the battle for the
Democratic presidential nomination will continue until the last
primaries.
   ``Today was a great day, but our job has just begun,'' Dukakis
told a buoyant crowd Tuesday night in the Manhattan hotel that
served as his headquarters.
   He returned to New York from Philadelphia to claim the victory
that moved him a giant step toward the nomination and likely will
narrow the race in the remaining states to just himself and Jesse
Jackson.
   ``Tomorrow we take our message ... to Pennsylvania and Ohio and
Indiana, and after that to Oregon and California and New Jersey and
the remaining primary states,'' he said. ``And after that, we will
take our message, the Democratic message, to every part of the
country.''
   In Philadelphia he unveiled a retooled campaign speech before a
crowd of more than 1,500 Democrats at a state party dinner. He
blasted the Republican vice president and linked him to privileged
excess and corporate greed _ themes he didn't mention as he
campaigned near Wall Street a day earlier.
   The dimensions of the Massachusetts governor's victory were
enough to make it likely Albert Gore Jr. would drop out of the race
and leave Dukakis the only white Democrat in the race with Jackson.
It was a victory that pushed him far ahead in the delegate race
and, while not yet close to a majority of delegates, gave him the
look of the likely nominee.
   Dukakis didn't claim that title for himself, however. Aides said
he would compete vigorously in the Pennsylvania primary next
Tuesday and in Ohio and Indiana the week after that. His
Pennsylvania chairman, Lanny Johnson, acknowledged Dukakis is at a
large advantage in that state as the only candidate with a full
slate of delegates on the ballot.
</TEXT>
