<1ST_LINE>r a PM-UntouchableProgram     04-20 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Untouchable Program,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Controversy Surrounds Refusal To Air ``Untouchables'' On
University Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Instructors at Eastern Illinois
University are challenging a decision to ban ``The Untouchables''
from the campus television station.
   The Illinois Board of Governors of State Colleges and
Universities, which oversees the 10,000-student campus, voted 6-0
last Thursday to bar WEIU-TV from airing the series. Board member
Dominick Bufalino said ``The Untouchables'' was too violent and
created a negative stereotype of Italian-Americans.
   ``Why should we show a program that is controversial and is
offensive to a segment of our population?'' he said. ``We should be
educating, not teaching bigotry.''
   Robert Stack, who starred in the Emmy award-winning series from
1959 to 1963, called the ban ``ridiculous.''
   Stack portrayed Eliot Ness in ``The Untouchables,'' which
focused on the battles of Ness and other lawmen against Chicago
gangsters during Prohibition. A film version of the stories with
Kevin Costner as Ness just won an Academy Award for Sean Connery as
Best Supporting Actor.
   John Beabout, director of the university's Radio-TV Center, said
it was the first time the board had rejected funding for a series
on the station.
   Members of the university's Faculty Senate reacted angrily to
the ban Tuesday, calling it a violation of academic freedom, and
approved a resolution asking the board to reconsider its decision.
   Stack said he is leaving for Italy later this month to accept an
award for his role in the series, which he said is No. 1 in that
country.
   ``I find it highly ironic that the Italians are honoring `The
Untouchables' and the Americans are trying to censor it,'' he said.
   Several faculty members agreed.
   ``I could no longer teach `Romeo and Juliet' because it deals
with teen-agers and violence, according to the rationale of the
board,'' said English professor Michael Loudon.
   No state funds would have been used to buy 80 to 90 episodes for
the station. The $25,650 needed to air the program would have come
from a grant from the Corporation for Public Broadcasting, but the
board must approve all university expenditures of more than $10,000.
</TEXT>
