<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pope'sRemains     04-20 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope's Remains,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope's Remains Recovered After Theft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>L'AQUILA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today recovered a 13th century
pope's mummified remains that were stolen from a cathedral three
days earlier.
   The remains of Celestine V, who resigned in 1294 after a
five-month papacy, were found in a plywood box hidden in the hollow
of a cemetery wall, authorities reported. Police said they found
the site by following suspected thieves, who got away.
   Church officials said the remains of the Roman Catholic pope,
stolen from the cathedral in the southern city of L'Aquila on
Sunday night, had not been damaged during the theft.
   The brief papacy of Celestine, who died in 1296, was marked by
subservience to Charles II, king of Naples. Acknowledging his
incompetence, Celestine declared that a pope had the right to
resign and did so.
   Celestine was canonized by Pope Clement V in 1313.
   Church bells pealed in L'Aquila and in Celestine's hometown of
Isernia to celebrate the recovery of the remains. The Vatican
newspaper had earlier reported the ``profound indignation in
L`Aquila for the grave sacrilegious act.''
   Police said they recovered the remains in the cemetery at
Amatrice, 40 miles south of L'Aquila, after following an
undisclosed number of suspects. The Italian news agency ANSA said
the suspects escaped as police concentrated on recovering the
remains.
   Authorities were looking for the suspects today.
   The thieves took the remains after forcing open a chapel door in
the Cathedral of Santa Maria di Collemaggio. Investigators
theorized they may have been planning to ask for a ransom, although
no demand had been reported.
   The L'Aquila archbishop's office said the remains would be
returned Monday to the cathedral, where they had been held since
1327, after an alarm system is installed.
</TEXT>
