<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Gulf-PoolReport 1stLd-Writethru a0549 04-20 0884</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Pool Report, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0549,0909</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missing Helicopter On Night Mission After U.S.-Iran Battle Ended</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 9-11, `In the...officers here' to recast, Pentagon
has not determined that missiles were Silkworms. Pick up 12th pvs,
`Van Dyke...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD THE USS JACK WILLIAMS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The missing U.S. Marine
helicopter that Iran claims to have shot down was on a night
mission in the Persian Gulf following day-long clashes between U.S.
and Iranian forces, U.S. officers said.
   The AH-1 Cobra gunship and its two-man crew failed to return to
the guided missile cruiser Wainwright from the Monday night flight.
The search continued today.
   A Navy spokesman, Lt. Cmdr. Mark Van Dyke, said there was no
evidence the helicopter was shot down.
   The gunship, regularly based aboard the dock landing ship
Trenton, flew support missions earlier Monday as U.S. forces
attacked two Iranian oil platforms in what the Reagan
administration called a measured response to Iran's mining of gulf
sea lanes and other hostile acts.
   Senior U.S. officers said Tuesday that the battle was over as
far as the United States was concerned, but there was no assurance
Iran felt the same way.
   Capt. Donald Dyer, who commands a U.S. destroyer group in the
gulf, said the situation remained tense, ``but I think it's
beginning to back off a little bit.'' He said the Iranians took
some heavy losses.
   Cmdr. Edward Mann, skipper of this frigate that flies the flag
of Dyer's command, said he was surprised by Iran's response Monday.
Mann said he did not believe Iran would cease its attacks on
neutral commercial shipping.
   U.S. officers appeared satisfied with the outcome of the series
of clashes Monday that began with the platform attacks about 8 a.m.
   In the course of it, Iran fired five missiles at the Jack
Williams and two destroyers sailing with it. Navy officers aboard
ship said they were Chinese-made Silkworm missiles fired from
anti-ship batteries along the Strait of Hormuz for the first time,
but the Pentagon said it has not determined what type of missile
was fired.
   All five missiles went awry, their guidance systems confused by
aluminum chaff fired into the air by the U.S. ships.
   A sixth missile was reported fired from the Faw Peninsula of
southern Iraq, but the result was not known to officers here.
   Van Dyke said there were no American casualties in Monday's
warfare and Iranian casualties were not known.
   The United States claimed one Iranian patrol boat sunk, three
speedboats sunk or damaged, and two frigates disabled. In addition,
Van Dyke said, the two oil platforms at Sirri and Sassan, in the
south-central gulf, were neutralized.
   Both platforms had been used for military purposes, including
support for speedboats that attack neutral shipping, the United
States said. Iran has justified its attacks on merchant shipping
saying they are in retaliation for Iraqi attacks on its own oil
tankers.
   Iran and Iraq have been at war for 7{ years.
   U.S. officials said the Iranians were advised by radio of U.S.
intentions before they were attacked.
   Iranians at Sirri and Sassan were given five minutes to evacuate
before the shellings began. Both platforms were bombarded before
Marines from the Trenton went aboard Sassan and destroyed it with
demolition charges.
   When an Iranian tugboat at Sirri radioed the Wainwright for
permission to pick up survivors in the water, Capt. James.
Chandler, who commands the cruiser, agreed and also dropped
lifeboats.
   Minutes later, the Joshan, one of Iran's fast, Seakiller
missile-equipped patrol boats, raced toward the Wainwright and was
warned by its skipper that if it approached any closer, ``It is my
intention to sink you.''
   The Iranian boat then fired a missile at the Wainwright, which
launched chaff. The Simpson fired an SM-1 missile that blew the
patrol boat apart.
   U.S. officiers said the two Iranian frigates, Sahand and
Sabalan, also fired on U.S. aircraft after ignoring warnings
against taking hostile action.
   Also, Iranian speedboats and a helicopter attacked an
American-run oil rig in the Mubarak oil field off the United Arab
Emirates and damaged the American resupply vessel Willie Tide.
   An A-6 Intruder fighter jet from the carrier Enterprise attacked
the speedboats and at least one was sunk, the others damaged.
   The Jack Williams and two destroyers were speeding back into the
gulf from the Strait of Hormuz when they received word the Sahand
and at least eight speedboats were approaching from Iran's naval
base at Bandar Abbas, 30 miles to the north.
   ``The Sahand is in your vicinity. Take him,'' was the terse
message from Rear. Adm. Anthony Less, commander of the Joint Task
Force Middle East.
   U.S. officers said two A-6s drew missile fire from the Sahand
and retaliated with Harpoon missiles that damaged the 12-year-old,
British-built frigate.
   Then the USS Joseph Strauss, sailing just ahead of the Jack
Williams, fired another Harpoon, blasting the ship from 20 miles
away. When last seen, it was listing badly with a hole in its hull
and its superstructure ablaze. Whether it sank was not known, Van
Dyke said.
   The Sabalan was hit by F-14 Tomcats, also flying off the
Enterprise in the Arabian Sea. It was hit by a laser-guided skipper
bomb and left dead in the water. Its fate also was unknown.
</TEXT>
