<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-USSailors     04-20 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-US Sailors,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Injured U.S. Sailors Leave For United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN FISCHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three of four U.S. sailors
injured when a frigate hit a mine in the Persian Gulf last week
left today for further treatment in the United States, military
officials said.
   The sailors, two of them in serious condition, were flown by
helicopter from the U.S. Army Medical Center in Landstuhl to
Frankfurt's Rhein Main Air Base, said U.S. Air Force spokesmen
Capt. Dave Shaw.
   They then boarded a C-141 aircraft that left for the United
States at 12:30 p.m. (5:30 a.m. EDT), Shaw said.
   The men were to be flown to Andrews Air Force Base in Maryland
and then on to Brooke Army Medical Center in San Antonio, Texas.
   They were identified as Seaman Apprentice Wayne Smith, 18, of
Clearview, Pa., Petty Officer 3.C. David Burbine, 23, of Ashaway,
R.I., and Petty Officer 2.C. Larry Welch, 26, of Ohio, said Marie
Shaw, a spokeswoman for Landstuhl Army hospital.
   Smith is in stable condition and recovering well, she said.
Burbine and Welch are in serious but stable condition.
   The spokeswoman said Chief Petty Officer Alex Perez, 38, of
Ports Breath, R.I., was being kept at the hopital in Landstuhl
``because he is very tired.''
   Perez suffered serious back injuries, Mrs. Shaw said, but was in
stable condition.
   The men, who arrived at the hospital Sunday, were among ten U.S.
military personnel injured when the U.S. Navy frigate Samuel B.
Roberts struck a mine in the Persian Gulf last Thursday.
   U.S. officials have said the mines in the gulf were laid by Iran.
   Smith, who had been on the frigate for less than a month,
described the blast in an interview that appeared in today's
editions of the unofficial U.S. Armed Forces newspaper, Stars and
Stripes.
   When the captain announced that three mines had been spotted,
Smith said he wondered if there were more that had gone undetected,
the newspaper reported.
   ``I was kind of thinking how it would be if they could miss one
if it was underneath the water,'' the newspaper quoted him as
saying.
   Smith and Burbine were at their stations in the engine room,
which turned into an inferno when the mine exploded, the newspaper
said.
   ``I tried to close my eyes and tried to hit the ground to keep
the fire from burning me,'' Smith was quoted as saying. ``I was
afraid of a lot of things, you know, if the ship went down, having
to swim while being burned like I was.''
</TEXT>
