<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0594 04-20 0768</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0594,0785</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Calls Up Volunteers; Kuwait Says Iran Fires Missile Into Its
Territory</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-6 ``Kuwait's Defense...Saudi border'' with 4
grafs to UPDATE with Kuwaiti and Iranian comment, convoys
reportedly suspended. Pickup 7th graf pvs ``The Scud...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran today told all volunteers to report
for duty and put its bases on alert to face what it called
``bestial aggression'' from the United States and Iraq. Kuwait said
Iran fired a missile into its territory before dawn.
   Iran said it launched a new thrust into northeastern Iraq, and
both Iran and Iraq reported exchanging air strikes.
   Shipping executives said commercial vessels were avoiding the
Persian Gulf and Iranian warships were reportedly staying in port.
   The U.S. Navy sank or damaged six Iranian vessels and destroyed
two offshore oil platforms Monday in the heaviest fighting with the
Iranians since the U.S. Navy began escorting Kuwaiti ships in the
gulf last July.
   Kuwait's Defense Ministry gave no details of where the
``Scud-type'' missile exploded today or whether it caused
casualties or damage, but said: ``Kuwait has the full right to take
what it sees as appropriate measures toward this new aggression,
directed against its territories.''
   A source who spoke on condition of anonymity said the missile
fell near desert oilfield operated by Getty Oil in the vicinity of
Wafra, on the Saudi border.
   Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati of Iran, in a message
reported on Tehran Radio today, said: ``The government of Kuwait is
responsible for all the consequences of its support for the
aggressive Iraqi regime'' in the gulf war.
   Velayati's statement was in a message to the Organization of the
Islamic Conference accusing Kuwait of giving financial and other
support to Iraq. The radio, monitored in Cyprus, did not say when
the message was sent.
   The Scud is a Soviet-designed surface-to-surface missile with a
range of about 180 miles. Iran has used such missiles against Iraq
in the 7{-year-old gulf war.
   Iran last year fired several Chinese-made Silkworm missiles into
Kuwait's coastal waters from the Faw peninsula.
   Tehran Radio, announcing the nationwide mobilization, declared:
``Today our revolution and our heroic nation is faced with the
onslaught of the evil triangle of America, Iraq and the
reactionaries.''
   It said all volunteers should report to their bases throughout
the country ``and get ready for departure'' to the battlefront. The
broadcast did not mention numbers, but Iranian leaders have claimed
more than 3 million Iranians have undergone military training in
the last six months.
   The radio added: ``At this critical juncture, in order to
respond to the bestial aggression of America and regional
reactionaries, all basij (volunteer) forces'' should immediately
report for duty.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Cyprus, said Iranian forces killed or wounded 300 Iraqis and
captured more than 250 in the Shemiran mountain region of Kurdistan
in the new offensive.
   The agency said Iranian warplanes bombed ``military and economic
targets'' in the northern Iraqi city of Erbil soon after dawn
today, causing ``heavy'' damage and casualties. The Iraqis reported
civilian casualties but gave no numbers.
   IRNA said Iraqi warplanes bombed residential areas of the
western cities of Dezful, Hamedan and Boroujerd, causing civilian
casualties.
   Iraq claimed its forces were mopping up Iranian pockets of
resistance in the Faw peninsula, which it recaptured this week.
Iran seized control of the strategic peninsula two years ago.
   The search continued today for a U.S. Marine attack helicopter
and its two-man crew, missing since going out on a night mission
following Monday's fighting.
   There was no estimate of Iranian casualties Monday, but Navy
officers said they presumed them to be heavy.
   Iran has maintained the U.S. attacks on Iranian oil platforms
were planned in concert with Iraq.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, denying that assertion,
insisted the United States is neutral in the gulf war and said the
American presence in the gulf is ``non-confrontational.''
   The Reagan adminstration said it attacked the Iranian oil
platforms in retaliation for the mine that damaged the USS Samuel
B. Roberts last week, wounding 10 crewmen. The Navy said other
Iranian targets were fired on only after they threatened U.S.
forces.
   President Reagan said there was no doubt Iran planted the mine
that damaged the Roberts. He said it was quieter in the gulf
Tuesday and ``we hope it continues that way.''
   One gulf-based marine salvage executive said the gulf appeared
``ghostly'' today from lack of shipping. He and others, who spoke
on condition of anonymity, said commercial vessels were avoiding
the waterway.
</TEXT>
