<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites SUB a0428 04-20 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites, SUB, a0428,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st item in PM-Lites, a0428, to CORRECT year of Vermont
moose-cow romance in 6th graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LACONIA, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It can get mighty lonely in the New
Hampshire woods, as an 18-year-old female pony named Princess has
discovered.
   For the last five months, Princess has been the object of
affection of a 900-pound bull moose nearly twice her size. However,
a man photographing the unlikely pair believes the relationship is
maternal.
   ``He even tries to follow the pony into the barn. He thinks she
is his mother,'' said Herbie Ainsworth of Gilmanton, who refuses to
disclose the farm's location for fear that someone might shoot the
moose.
   The moose, nicknamed Prince, stays in the pasture all day
watching the pony and then returns the next morning, he said
recently. The farm's owners don't feed the moose, though it often
tries to enter the barn for a bite of hay.
   It's rare for a moose to be attracted to domestic livestock, but
not unheard of.
   In 1986, a Vermont heifer named Jessica attracted the affections
of a bull moose for a 76-day romance that sparked interest
nationwide before he resumed his life in the wild.
   Kristine Klein, a state biologist, said that a cow moose drives
away its calf when the youngster is about a year old, and that
after being abandoned, a young moose occasionally will attach
itself to another moose or to domestic livestock.
</TEXT>
