<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 0951EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Stroke-Laser     04-20 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stroke-Laser,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Use Of Laser To Clear Blocked Neck Artery Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deadly complications of stroke-prevention
surgery could be reduced by a new method using a laser beam to
clear blocked neck arteries, says a doctor who reported performing
the procedure for the first time.
   The surgery, performed last Friday on a 72-year-old California
man, ``represents the first time laser light has been applied to
the treatment of carotid artery disease,'' said Dr. John Eugene,
who worked with cardiovascular surgeon Richard Ott.
   ``I feel excellent, and I think the operation was quite a
success,'' the patient, Kenneth B. Smith, said Tuesday by telephone
from his San Clemente home. ``The neck is a little sore from the
incision, but otherwise I'm fine.''
   Smith was discharged Monday from the University of California
Irvine Medical Center in Orange.
   For more than two weeks before the operation, Smith suffered up
to a dozen ``transient ischemic attacks,'' nicknamed
``mini-strokes,'' because his left carotid artery _ one of two main
neck arteries supplying blood to the brain _ was 85 percent to 90
percent blocked by fatty deposits called plaque.
   Because the blockage impeded blood flow to Smith's brain, he
suffered repeated, temporary paralysis of his right arm, leg and
hand and the right side of his face, and faced the possibility of a
massive, possibly deadly stroke, caused either by the blockage or a
loosened piece of plaque, Eugene said.
   Surgery to clear such blockages is called carotid
endarterectomy. In conventional surgery, the neck is cut open, the
artery is exposed and a knife is used to remove the plaque, then
the artery and neck are closed.
   But in the operation performed by Eugene and Ott, a low-power
beam from an argon ion laser was aimed between the plaque and
underlying artery wall to remove the plaque cleanly, Eugene said.
   ``We feel it offers a substantial advantage over the knife
technique because we leave a smooth artery surface with the layers
of the artery welded together by the laser beam,'' he said.
   Rand Corp. researchers reported last month in the New England
Journal of Medicine that 10 percent of elderly Americans who
undergo conventional carotid endarterectomy die or suffer strokes
as a direct result of the surgery, which has been criticized as
being overused.
   Eugene said the laser approach should reduce such fatal
complications because it repairs the artery wall and reduces the
odds that debris will break off from it to cause a stroke.
   However, Dr. Sam Ahn, a vascular surgeon at the University of
California, Los Angeles, said the success of such surgery depends
more on the surgeon than the equipment used, so he was skeptical if
complication rates really would be reduced, since they already are
quite low at major medical centers.
   He said the laser surgery ``is the first reported, as far as I
know.''
   The new method has been under development since 1982 at
UC-Irvine, and doctors hope to use it by year's end to clear
blocked heart arteries, Eugene said, adding he previously used it
to clear blocked leg and arm arteries.
   The method differs from another technique in which a
laser-tipped catheter is inserted into an artery to clear
blockages. That technique hasn't been used on carotid arteries
because it poses a higher risk of causing a piece of plaque to
break off and trigger a stroke, Eugene said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
