<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SmithMinorities     04-20 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Smith Minorities,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>College President Issues Response To List of Minority Grievances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTHAMPTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smith College student activists say
that the college president's response to their grievances is
inadequate, and they are planning to meet with a federal official
about campus racism.
   ``We've heard a lot of talk. We need to see something solid,''
Jennifer Fleming, a member of Concerned Students of All Colors,
said Tuesday.
   President Mary Maple Dunn released her response to the 18
grievances that dozens of members of the ad hoc student group had
delivered to her in a protest march on her house Sunday.
   The students, in their list, decried the dearth of minorities
among faculty, staff and administrators and complained that
students had been excluded from the search for an affirmative
action officer, among other things.
   The group threatened to file a civil rights complaint with the
Hampshire County district attorney and a discrimination complaint
with the Massachusetts Commission Against Discrimination if nothing
was done about their grievances.
   Wambui Mwangi, a sophomore who is among the students who helped
draw up the grievances, said Tuesday that Ms. Dunn's response was
inadequate.
   The students said they intended to keep their scheduled meeting
today with a community relations specialist from the Justice
Department and to hold a general meeting at 4:30 p.m. Friday to
discuss Ms. Dunn's response.
   In a statement prefacing her point-by-point response, Ms. Dunn
described the grievances as ``long-standing complaints which have
been brought to the attention of the administration before.''
   She added, however, ``we think it only fair that students
acknowledge that some steps to redress these grievances have been
taken.'' She said Tuesdy she planned to meet with students in the
near future.
   Among her responses, she:
   _Acknowledged ``the faculty is nearly all-white, that no people
of color hold top administrative posts, that minorities are
underrepresented at all levels of influence.'' She said, however,
that the college would follow minority hiring goals set by a
still-to-be-hired affirmative action officer.
   _Countered students' claims of exclusion from the search for the
officer by saying student leaders had been invited to interview
finalists and students had never before expressed interest in
serving on search committees.
   _Announced she would create the post of ombudsperson to serve as
an advocate against discrimination.
   Ms. Fleming said students have met often with Ms. Dunn about
minority concerns.
   ``The point of the protest was to get reaction, not to get Mary
to talk to us again,'' she said. ``It was a show of strength, of
frustration.''
   She said the group consisted of an ``indefinite'' number of
students and was ``formed simply to protest. Whoever wants to can
join.''
   A report issued last month by a faculty group called Committee
on Community Policy recommended that the college try to make the
faculty 20 percent minority within five years. Currently, 5 percent
of employees are members of minority groups.
   The study also said that minority recruitment and enrollment as
a whole is increasing, but black enrollments have been declining at
a significant rate for years.
</TEXT>
