<2ND_LINE>PM-Cardinal-Cuba, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0577,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>O'Connor Calls Visit Possible Bridge for U.S.-Cuban Relations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf ``O'Connor is...'' with one graf to CORRECT
that Cuba 90 miles from Florida, sted Miami.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TINA SUSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John O'Connor of New York met with
government and church leaders on the first day of his visit to this
Communist nation, with all sides expressing hope his visit will
help improve U.S-Cuban relations.
   O'Connor is spending four days in Cuba as a guest of the Roman
Catholic Church to celebrate the 200th anniversary of the birth of
the Rev. Felix Varela. The priest, who served in New York City from
1823 to 1853, is considered a Cuban hero in the struggle against
Spanish colonial rule.
   ``It is my hope that Felix Varela will form a bridge _ a bridge
between the church in Cuba and the church in New York,'' O'Connor
told reporters when he arrived in Havana Tuesday, after stops in
the Dominican Republic and the Cuban city of Santiago.
   ``And who knows, when there is a strong bridge between the two
churches, then perhaps many others can go back and forth across
that bridge,'' O'Connor added.
   ``And other kinds of peaceful reunions may take place between
two people who are separated by such a small body of water and who
together dream of peace.''
   O'Connor is the first American cardinal to visit this Caribbean
island nation, just 90 miles from Florida, since Fidel Castro came
to power in 1959.
   The Roman Catholic prelate was to say Mass tonight after a day
of meetings with church leaders and U.S. officials in Havana. The
nature of those talks has not been announced. O'Connor said earlier
he could not presume that Castro will see him, but he would accept
such an invitation.
   At a Vatican Embassy reception Tuesday night, O'Connor mingled
with Cuban Vice President Carlos Rafael Rodriguez, Archbishop Jaime
Ortega and officials of the U.S. Interest Section, a diplomatic
post set up in Havana because there are no formal U.S.-Cuban
relations.
   Rodriguez, a member of the Communist Party Politburo, echoed
O'Connor's comments.
   ``This bridge is necessary not because there are hostile
relations, (but) because there are none,'' said Rodriguez.
   He said Americans have a false image of Cuba and ``it's
necessary to rectify it. I think that the cardinal's visit
contributes to rectifying that image.''
   O'Connor hugged Ortega when he got off a plane that carried him
to the capital from Santiago, the coastal city in southeastern Cuba
where he began his visit Monday.
   The cardinal said the thunderous applause he received in
Santiago convinced him that years of religious restrictions in Cuba
had not dampened the spirit of believers in this officially atheist
nation.
</TEXT>
