<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Dartmouth Recruiting,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dartmouth Offers Free Air Fare For Top Student Recruits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Following the lead of its athletic
department, Dartmouth College is offering free air fare to top
freshmen applicants still undecided about whether to attend the Ivy
League school.
   ``We have actively recruited athletes for years,'' said
Dartmouth President James Freedman. ``Now we want to invest the
same energy in bringing intellectually ambitious students to the
college.''
   The Presidential Scholars program offers the top 187 accepted
freshmen free air fare to visit the campus this month before
deciding whether to enroll. Faculty members are personally inviting
each of the students.
   A faculty committee chose the top students and established the
program.
   The college this year received 10,200 applications for a 1988
freshman class of about 1,100.
   Dartmouth also is targeting women and minorities who have been
accepted but still are making up their minds. This year, the
admissions office organized a telethon to contact women who had
been accepted.
   Women now account for about 39 percent of the student body at
Dartmouth, and Freedman and trustees have called for a significant
increase.
</TEXT>
