<2ND_LINE>PM-Kuwait-Hijack Reax, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0613,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kuwaitis Celebrate `Triumph' Over Hijackers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS graf after 7th pvs, `An official...' to incorporate
a0613, a0616, updating with hijackers reported leaving Algiers,
Kuwait saying no deal except safe passage to Iran or Lebanon. Pick
up 8th pvs, `The government...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kuwaitis hailed the release of 31 hostages and the
end of the 16-day hijacking of a Kuwaiti jumbo jet in Algeria today
as a victory for their government's firm stand against terrorism.
   The Kuwaiti government had steadfastly refused to meet the
gunmen's demand it free 17 convicted pro-Iranian extremists.
   The state radio broke into its regular programs to announce the
release.
   Ali Khaled Al-Sabah, a member of Kuwait's ruling family and the
brother of three royal family members among the freed captives,
told The Associated Press: ``My happiness in indescribable. I feel
as if my brother and two sisters have been resurrected from an
inevitable doom.
   ``We feel deeply indebted to the Kuwaiti leadership and the
government of Algeria,'' he said in a telephone interview.
   Algerian officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
hijackers left the Kuwait Airways Boeing 747 about 20 minutes
before the hostages were freed. They said the gunmen were taken by
unmarked cars to an undisclosed location.
   An official source in Kuwait, also speaking privately, said the
hijackers were promised safe passage to an undisclosed location.
   The gunmen left Algiers for an unknown destination, sources in
the Persian Gulf told The Associated Press. The Kuwait News Agency
said no deal was struck with the hijackers except for safe conduct
to Iran or Lebanon.
   The government thanked Algeria for its help and but condemned
the hijackers' ``cowardly'' operation as part of a plot to distract
the Arab world.
   The radio broadcast a special song glorifying the emir of
Kuwait, Sheik Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah, and his government for their
``triumph'' over terrorism.
   People telephoned the radio and state-run television network to
ask for news of the hostages.
   Many people called in to congratulate the government on its firm
stand against the hijackers, who had killed two Kuwaiti passengers.
The plane was seized April 5 on a flight from Bangkok to Kuwait
with 112 people aboard.
   ``This is a happy moment for the nation,'' a radio announcer
declared. ``We congratulate ourselves, our government and our emir,
and we offer the leadership garlands of roses and jasmine.''
   Television technicians and announcers were summoned to broadcast
live satellite coverage of the release of the 24 passengers and
seven crew members in Algiers.
   A special Kuwait Airways jet was expected to fly to Algiers and
bring back the freed passengers and crew members later today or
Thursday.
   The 17 men whose freedom the hijackers sought were convicted and
imprisoned for the December 1983 bombings of the French and U.S.
embassies in Kuwait.
   The Cabinet, meeting in emergency session shortly after the
ordeal ended, told Kuwaitis that their ``courageous stand and
solidarity with the leadership ... provides a striking example to
people of the world in steadfastness versus terrorism and the firm
rejection of blackmail.''
   Minister of State for Cabinet Affairs Rashed Abdel-Aziz
al-Rashed said the government ``expressed deep gratitude for the
efforts made by Algerian officials, foremostly president Chadli
Bendjedid and officials of the Palestine Liberation Organization,
including chairman Yasser Arafat.''
   Arafat and the PLO began their mediation effort when the
commandeered plane landed at Larnaca, Cyprus, on April 8.
   Kuwait also thanked ``all sister and friendly states'' for their
support during the ordeal.
   `While the Cabinet praises the Almighty for the ending of the
ordeal, it emphasizes that this cowardly operation and the series
of criminal acts of terrorism witnessed by the Arab world are but
part of a blueprint that seeks to undermine the security of the
Arab nation and preoccupy it with such acts to distract its
attention from its issues of destiny,'' al-Rashed said. He did not
elaborate.
</TEXT>
