<1ST_LINE>u p PM-CongressionalCaucus 1stLd-Writethru a0456 04-20 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congressional Caucus, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0456,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis In Line To Pick Up More House Delegates</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 6 grafs with House caucus, picking up in 4th
graf pvs, Twenty-six</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional Democrats today met behind the
closed doors of the House to make final decisions on sending 250
delegates from Capitol Hill to their party's national convention.
   Before the opening of today's House Democratic Caucus, which was
considered largely a formality, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
already was in line to receive 26 of the House delegates.
   The Dukakis campaign was predicting no flood of endorsements
following Tuesday's New York primary victory.
   ``I don't see a deluge,'' said Susan Brophy, who handles
delegate selection for the campaign.
   Rep. Norman Mineta, D-Calif., a Dukakis supporter, said today
that Dukakis had scored ``a decisive win in New York but we still
have major states in Pennsylvania and Ohio.''
   In all, 205 of the 207 House delegates were nominated last week.
The remaining two were picked today.
   Twenty-six of the House members nominated last week said they
were backing Dukakis for the Democratic presidential nomination,
while 15 were supporting Jesse Jackson, 11 were for Tennessee Sen.
Albert Gore Jr., and 10 were for Illinois Sen. Paul Simon. Another
143 were uncommitted.
   On Tuesday, Democrats in the Senate held a ceremonial vote to
pick their 43 national convention delegates. The real decisions
were made last week and were based in many cases on seniority.
   The 250 delegates from Capitol Hill will be among 643 ``super
delegates'' to attend the Democratic National Convention in
Atlanta. These delegates, who include governors and members of the
Democratic National Committee, receive their convention credentials
based on offices they now hold or used to have.
   Only New York's primary on Tuesday and California's on June 7
offer more delegates than the behind-the-scenes ``primary'' on
Capitol Hill.
   Dukakis is working hard to swing those unpledged _ and mostly
uncommitted _ delegates into his camp as he seeks the 2,081 votes
needed to win in Atlanta.
   Dukakis has the backing of 13 senators, while Gore won seven
votes on the Senate list, including his own.
   Simon, whose campaign is on hold, managed to win only a seat for
himself and the backing of fellow Illinois Sen. Alan Dixon.
Twenty-one senator-delegates were uncommitted.
   Jesse Jackson had no announced supporters among the senators
chosen Tuesday.
   ``We were pleased that we were able to accommodate almost every
Democratic member who requested to be an unpledged delegate,'' said
Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia. He said
only two who wanted to go did not get seats, but he did not name
them.
   In addition to the 250 congressional slots, 362 votes will be
cast by members of the Democratic National Committee and 26 by
Democratic governors. Five former party leaders also have automatic
seats at the convention.
   Dukakis, who leads in the overall delegate count, also leads
among super delegates interviewed by The Associated Press, 103.65
to 46.55 for Gore, 45.1 for Jackson and 28.5 for Simon. A total of
416.25 are uncommitted and three delegate slots were vacant.
</TEXT>
