<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MoonGroup     04-20 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Moon Group,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Documents Show FBI Got Reports From Moon Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI collected information about a group
critical of U.S. policy in Central America that was provided by an
affiliate of the Rev. Sun Myung Moon's Unification Church, The
Boston Globe reported today.
   Members of the Collegiate Association for the Resarch of
Principles, which is affiliated with Moon's church, sent the FBI
reports about the Committee in Solidarity with the People of El
Salvador, according to documents released by the FBI in response to
a Freedom of Information request.
   FBI agent Ray McIllhaney said he could not comment on how the
information was used or why it was kept in FBI files, the newspaper
said.
   The documents deal only with the Moon affiliate's communications
to the FBI in 1981 and indicate that members on at least 10
campuses sent material to the FBI.
   The identities of those who sent the information were blacked
out of the released documents, the newspaper said.
   Congressional testimony and published reports indicated that
another group, also sponsored by the Moon organization, was
involved in fund-raising and training for Nicaraguan Contra rebels
through Lt. Col. Oliver North's private aid network, the Globe said.
   One report to the FBI from a Collegiate Association member in
Santa Barbara, Calif., said a supporter of the anti-Reagan policy
group ``tried to convince me that the Soviet Union is not involved
in El Salvador, yet he freely admits the role of Cuba,'' the
released documents show.
   A spokesman at Collegiate Association headquarters in New York,
who did not identify himself, told the Globe that allegations that
members worked with the FBI are ``junk. If you write that, I will
tell my friends in Boston not to buy your newspaper.''
   McIlhaney said the FBI's use of unsolicited material from
outside sources depends on its relevance and appropriateness to the
agency. He said the agency regularly receives unsolicited material
from various people and organizations about various things.
</TEXT>
