<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CyanideDeaths     04-20 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cyanide Deaths,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Selection Completed in Drug-Tampering Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection has been completed in the federal
trial of a woman accused of lacing over-the-counter drug capsules
with cyanide that killed two people, including her husband.
   Stella Nickell, 44, is charged with two counts of causing a
death by product tampering.
   Bruce Nickell, 52, and Susan Katherine Snow, 40, both of Auburn,
died after taking poisoned capsules of Extra-Strength Excedrin in
June 1986. Authorities have suggested no other link between the
victims.
   Lawyers said the trial is the first under federal law for
tampering with over-the-counter drug capsules.
   Mrs. Nickell also is charged with three counts of tampering with
a product involved in interstate commerce in the tainting of
capsules in two Extra-Strength Excedrin bottles and an Anacin-3
bottle that were recovered in stores in Kent and Auburn, suburbs
between Seattle and Tacoma.
   The deaths resulted in a nationwide tampering scare, and
Excedrin manufacturer Bristol-Myers recalled all its
non-prescription medicine sold in capsule form.
   The government alleges Mrs. Nickell killed her husband to
collect $176,000 in life insurance benefits, then put tainted
pain-relief capsules in stores to draw suspicion away from herself.
   Attorneys for both sides said pre-trial news coverage of the
case didn't seem to have influenced the jury pool. Selection was
completed Tuesday.
</TEXT>
