<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SovietVisit     04-20 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Visit,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Visit Resort in Preparation for Basing Treaty Inspectors
in Utah</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARK CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group Soviet officials visited this ski
resort community to inspect some of the recreational facilities
that will be available to Soviet inspectors stationed in Utah as
part of an arms limitation agreement.
   The Soviet group spent a relaxed afternoon Tuesday, looking at
storefront windows and eating lunch at a Mexican restaurant.
   Igor Khripunov, first secretary at the Soviet Embassy in
Washington, said the proposed treaty indicates a growing confidence
and trust in the relationship between the two superpowers
   The Intermediate Nuclear Forces agreement ``demonstrates the
bilateral relationship between our two countries is moving into a
new stage, leaving behind a prolonged period of confrontation,''
Khripunov said.
   The Soviet team will be stationed at the Hercules Inc. Bacchus
East Plant in West Valley City, southwest of Salt Lake City. A U.S.
team will be stationed at Votkinsk in the Soviet Union.
   The Soviets would verify that Pershing 2 missiles were no longer
being produced at Hercules, while the U.S. team would make sure
SS-20 missiles no longer were being assembled.
   The Soviets were particularly amused by a window display of a
stuffed rattlesnake next to a pair of rattlesnake cowboy boots. A
U.S. official said that when the Soviets toured the grassy
perimeter of the Hercules plant Monday, they were warned about
rattlesnakes.
   Asked if U.S. inspectors would face similar dangers at Votkinsk,
near the Ural Mountains, Khripunov said: ``We can't offer anything
as exciting as rattlesnakes. Just cold and snow, I guess.''
</TEXT>
