<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 1116EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Refugee'sDeath     04-20 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Refugee's Death,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethiopian Refugee Slain in West Philly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Ethiopian refugee who said she came to
the United States to escape political persecution and a
shoot-on-sight order in her homeland was stabbed to death in her
apartment, authorities said.
   Homicide detectives said today they had few clues to who killed
Mezgebnesh Abayu or why. She had been stabbed several times, and
the apartment showed signs of a brief struggle. But the place had
not been ransacked and the door had not been forced open, they said.
   Nothing they found indicated or ruled out a political motive,
police said.
   In an interview with the Philadelphia Inquirer in November, Mrs.
Abayu said she had worked for a news magazine in the Ethiopian
capital of Addis Ababa.
   When Ethiopian Emperor Haile Selasie was deposed in a
Marxist-backed military coup in 1974, she said she and her husband
joined a student-led opposition group.
   Her husband was killed, she said, and ``there were orders to
shoot me on sight.''
   She fled to the neighboring nation of Sudan in 1980, leaving her
daughter, and then entered the United States as a refugee, one of
18,000 Ethiopians who have come here since 1980.
   Friends said Mrs. Abayu was not very happy in the United States,
where she was cut off from her parents and daughter with no chance
of returning home. She threw herself into community work, serving
on the board of directors of the Ethiopian Community Association.
   She also worked as a job counselor for the defunct Philadelphia
Area Refugee Consortium, a support group.
   She earned an undergraduate degree at the University of
Pennsylvania, studying social sciences and journalism. She would
have received a master's degree in social work from Temple
University this spring.
   Mrs. Abayu, 33, was about to start a job as a caseworker for the
city Department of Human Services after completing a 10-week
training program. Her sister, Tenagne Workeshatu, 26, last saw her
alive about 7 a.m. Monday when the younger woman left for classes
at Philadelphia Community College.
   When Mrs. Workeshatu returned from school at 12:30 p.m., she
found her sister's body just inside the door of the third-floor
apartment they shared, police said.
   Her friends said they were shocked by her death.
   ``When we came to this country as refugees, our expectations
were so high,'' said Harry Massele, director of the Ethiopian
Community Association. ``What we found was a difficult life. When
somebody is killed, we are so in shock because it does not happen
very often in Ethiopia.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
