<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Hostages, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0583,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Captors of 2 Americans Vow Retaliatiation; Frenchmen To Be Freed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with U.S. Ambassador unable to
confirm reported killing of American hostage. Two Frenchmen may be
freed before Saturday. CORRECTS spelling of An-Nahar newspaper.
Pickup 3rd graf pvs ```there will...'''; INSERTS 7 grafs after 8th
graf pvs ``On Monday...'' with detail. Pickup last graf ``There
are...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pro-Iranian group holding two Americans
said early today it will retaliate against ``America's
aggressions'' in the Persian Gulf, where U.S. and Iranian forces
clashed this week.
   In other developments, U.S. Ambassador John Kelly said he could
not confirm reports that U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins
was killed by his pro-Iranian captors. And a newspaper said two
French hostages may be freed before Saturday.
   ``We will not sit back and watch America's aggressions in the
gulf,'' the Revolutionary Justice Organization said in a
handwritten statement delivered shortly after midnight to the
independent daily newspaper An-Nahar.
   ``There will be retaliations and retaliations to punish the
aggressors and make them understand they will regret their
actions,'' said the statement, written in Arabic.
   The statement did not specify what measures the group would take
but included a photograph of Joseph James Cicippio, one of the two
Americans the group is holding.
   Cicippio, 57, of Valley Forge, Pa., was acting comptroller of
the American University of Beirut. He was kidnapped in the Lebanese
capital on Sept. 12, 1986.
   Edward Austin Tracy of Burlington, Vt., a writer who was
abducted in west Beirut on Oct. 21, 1986, is the other American
whose kidnapping was claimed by Revolutionary Justice Organization.
   In the photograph, Cicippio was clean shaven and wearing a navy
blue track suit with white stripes on the shoulder. He appeared
thinner than he did in the last picture released by the
organization, on Jan. 17, 1987.
   On Monday, the U.S. Navy attacked two Iranian oil platforms in
the Persian Gulf and sank or damaged six Iranian ships in
retaliation for a mine explosion last week that damaged the USS
Samuel B. Roberts and wounded 10 crewmen.
   Ambassador Kelly said his embassy had no information supporting
reports Higgins was killed by his captors.
   ``We have no information that would confirm those reports. We
cannot deny those reports, but no one knows the truth,'' he said.
   The Christian-controlled Voice of Lebanon radio station said
Monday that Higgins was killed before the Syrian-backed Shiite
Moslem Amal militia captured the south Lebanon hamlet of Siddiqine
from the Iranian-backed Hezbollah early this month.
   In another report today, An-Nahar said two Frenchmen also held
by pro-Iranian kidnappers may be released within three days.
   The newspaper quoted unidentified sources as saying Arab
businessmen Omran Adham and Mahdi al-Tajer were in Beirut and have
had ``contacts ... with the kidnappers.''
   ``Two French hostages may be released before April 23,'' the
report said.
   Adham and al-Tajer ``expect a positive outcome of their
contacts,'' the paper added. It did not elaborate.
   There are 22 foreigners missing and believed kidnapped in
Lebanon, including nine Americans. The longest held is Terry
Anderson, 40, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, who was seized March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
