<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WomenKilled     04-20 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Women Killed,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Women Killed in Freeway Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A frantic woman drove the wrong way up a freeway
exit ramp while trying to flee her former boyfriend, but her car
crashed into oncoming traffic and she was shot to death along with
her mother, police said.
   Barbara Jean Johnson, 36, and her mother, Jessie Mae Norman, 63,
were shot dead Tuesday, police said.
   Cleophus Jones Ethridge, 51, was charged with capital murder
after he surrendered to police two hours after the incident. He is
being held without bond.
   Homicide Sgt. Ronnie Doyle said the incident stemmed from a
domestic dispute. Doyle said Ms. Johnson had gone to her
boyfriend's home on Tuesday to collect items for her move to a new
apartment.
   During the chase the women drove the wrong way up a ramp to get
on the freeway, hit a pickup as they traveled west on an eastbound
road and were finally stopped by oncoming traffic.
   Ms. Johnson's two daughters, aged 16 and 10, were also in the
car but escaped without injury. No one was injured in the accident
with the pickup.
   Carl Dubone, an eastbound motorist, said he came over a rise and
saw a man standing in traffic holding a rifle.
   ``He was stepping away from the (Johnson) white car,'' Dubone
said. ``He was aiming at the lady (older daughter) who was running.
He stepped in front of the car and shot at the lady, but she ducked
down behind a car. The traffic was almost at a standstill by then.''
   Police said the man briefly chased the older girl, then went
back to his car and drove away.
   Ms. Johnson, a licensed vocational nurse, was shot through the
chest as she sat in the driver's seat of her car. Ms. Norman was
shot in the jaw while sitting in the back seat behind her daughter.
</TEXT>
