<1ST_LINE>u p PM-VermontCaucuses 1stLd-Writethru a0504 04-20 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vermont Caucuses, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0504,700</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with updated vote and delegate totals; pick
up pvs bgng ``It's a tremendous...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANICA KIRKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson reclaimed a razor-thin lead
today in Vermont's see-saw Democratic caucuses, a stunning comeback
from his 2-to-1 loss to Michael Dukakis in the state's ``beauty
contest'' primary last month.
   Tuesday night's caucus contest was a tight battle throughout the
night, and at times an emotional one. Burlington Mayor Bernard
Sanders, a Jackson supporter, was slapped by an irate citizen after
he cast his vote.
   With 97 percent of the votes counted today, Jackson held an
ever-so-thin lead over Dukakis. Of 1,300 state convention
delegates, Jackson had 575 delegates, or 46 percent, and Dukakis
had 572, or 45 percent. Albert Gore Jr. had 4, or 0 percent; 112
delegates, or 9 percent, were uncommitted.
   Dukakis would win 7 national convention delegates and Jackson 7,
if those results held up at the state convention next month.
   Though his lead was tenuous, Jackson's supporters hailed his
showing as a triumph. He won the state's largest city, Burlington,
and won many of the state's smallest, most rural communities as
well.
   ``It's a tremendous victory for us,'' said Liz Blum, the Jackson
state coordinator.
   The delegates elected Tuesday night will attend next month's
state convention, where 14 of Vermont's 19 delegates to the
national convention will be chosen. The remaining five spots belong
to Gov. Madeleine Kunin, a Dukakis backer, and four state party
officials.
   Jackson's strong showing in the caucuses was a disappointment
for the Dukakis campaign, which has most every prominent Democrat
in the state behind it, including Kunin, Sen. Patrick Leahy, Lt.
Gov. Howard Dean and House Speaker Ralph Wright.
   Kunin said the Jackson showing was ``not unexpected'' and added
she continues to be ``very optimistic about Dukakis.''
   ``I think think his showing in New York is fantastic,'' she
added. Dukakis won the big New York contest Tuesday by a solid
margin.
   Dukakis had won Vermont's presidential primary March 1, winning
56 percent of the vote, while Jackson gained 26 percent. The
primary was non-binding and had nothing to do with the selection of
actual delegates.
   Based on that showing, the Dukakis campaign had expected to win
the caucuses, but in recent days his supporters had backed off such
predictions.
   At the end of the night, with the tally showing a slight Dukakis
lead, William Wasserman, Dukakis' state coordinator, said: ``I'm
delighted that we're even one delegate ahead. We already knew the
Jackson campaign was well organized.''
   On the Republican side, some 1,000 delegates to the state GOP
convention were chosen Tuesday night. With 39 percent of the
delegates reported, George Bush had 332 delegates, or 89 percent,
with 52 uncommitted delegates, and five for Pat Robertson.
   Robertson's campaign had hoped to elect enough delegates to give
them a voice at the state and national conventions. But Bush's
Vermont spokesman, Steve Watson, said the Bush forces ``rallied and
were able to overcome the Robertson forces.''
   The turnout statewide was extremely high. About 670 people
attended the Burlington Democratic caucus, compared to 435 during
the 1984 presidential contest.
   The Burlington caucus provided a fair share of drama and
tension, as many party regulars protested the appearance of Mayor
Bernard Sanders, a socialist who ran for mayor as an independent.
Sanders backs Jackson.
   Lyman Hunt of Burlington, who took the podium to speak in
support of Gore, said, ``I resent intruders who would undermine and
destroy the Democratic Party.'' And voter Helen Malloy yelled from
the back of the auditorium, ``We want unity among ourselves, not
with a group of outsiders.''
   Several minutes later, she approached Sanders as he was
returning to his seat after casting his vote and slapped him on the
cheek. Sanders, who at first appeared to think the woman was about
to greet him, looked stunned.
   ``I don't think that was very nice,'' he told her.
   Malloy later said in a telephone interview that she ``lost my
footing ... I didn't hit (him) in the face on purpose.''
   Jackson had no paid staff in Vermont for either the primary or
the caucuses, but the volunteer staff for the primary was estimated
at 50 or more.
   The Dukakis campaign had two professional staffers in Vermont
for the caucuses, down from 15 paid staffers and 60 volunteers for
the preferential primary.
</TEXT>
