<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Shultz 1stLd-Writethru   04-20 0668</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0541,0690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Condemns Hijackers</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Shultz comments on hijacking.
Edits to trim. No pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Hijack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz
today denounced the hijackers of a Kuwaiti jumbo jet as murderers
and said freeing them would violate international standards.
   The hijackers left Algeria for an unknown destination today
after their 31 hostages were freed, said sources in the Persian
Gulf who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``They are not only hijackers but murderers,'' Shultz said at a
news conference in Helsinki, where he stopped en route to Moscow to
prepare for the May 29-June 2 summit.
   The Kuwait News Agency said the gunmen, who seized the plane
April 5, were promised safe passage to Iran or Lebanon.
   Shultz said his reports from Algiers were fragmentary and he did
not want to second-guess the Algerian government, which negotiated
with the gunmen.
   But he said the hijackers committed two distinct crimes: seizing
the airplane and killing the two Kuwaitis whose bodies were dumped
from the jetliner in Cyprus last week.
   ``From the standpoint of the international community we don't
like to see hijackers go off free,'' Shultz said. ``I don't think
that's a proper thing to do.''
   Kuwait thanked Algeria for its intercession. In the past, the
United States also has expressed gratitude to governments that
assist in ending hostage crises, but Shultz did not do so.
   Shultz said the United States would not seek to extradite the
hijackers if none of the hostages was American.
   But Charles E. Redman, the State Department spokesman, said one
passenger might have held dual citizenship, and Shultz said one of
the gunmen may have been involved in the hijacking of a TWA
jetliner in 1985 in which a U.S. Navy diver was killed.
   Shultz will open three days of talks in Moscow on Thursday with
Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze and meet with Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   On Shultz's agenda are the Iran-Iraq war, which threatens
shipping in the Persian Gulf, and U.S.-Soviet negotiations to
conclude a treaty to cut strategic nuclear weapons arsenals by 30
to 50 percent.
   Shultz said he would appeal anew to the Soviets to agree to
impose an arms embargo against Iran through the U.N. Security
Council.
   With Soviet support, the council called for a cease-fire in the
war in the gulf last July. But U.S. efforts to overcome Iranian
resistance with sanctions have been stymied by Moscow.
   A U.S. official, who briefed reporters on condition of
anonymity, said the Soviets might change their minds. He said
Shevardnadze had discussed the issue Tuesday with Jack Matlock, the
U.S. ambassador, and ``his attitude was barely negative.''
   Shultz said Tuesday the United States does not intend to be
drawn into the Persian Gulf war but is determined to defend its
ships against Iranian attack.
   He said it was difficult to analyze Iran's motives in attacking
ships in the Persian Gulf and firing on U.S. vessels and aircraft
on Monday, given vastly superior U.S. firepower.
   Shultz said the Iranian mine that damaged the U.S. frigate
Samuel B. Roberts in the gulf last week, prompting the Navy's
retaliatory raid on two Iranian oil platforms Monday, may have been
laid ``carelessly.''
   The navy sank or damaged six Iranian warships Monday.
   Shultz said he had no information to link Israel to the
assassination of Khalil al-Wazir, a top official of the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   He said the killing did not appear to be an act of terrorism,
which he said has ``a random characteristic'' with the attackers
striking at innocent civilians.
   ``This was a different kind of action, which doesn't mean we
don't condemn it,'' he said.
   Al-Wazir, military commander of the PLO, was killed Saturday in
his home in Tunisia by masked commandos. A Tunisian inquiry
concluded Israel conducted the attack.
   Israeli sources confirmed privately to The Associated Press that
Israeli forces killed al-Wazir. The Israeli government has not
confirmed this.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
