<DOCNO> AP880420-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 1211EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-PTL-IRS     04-20 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL-IRS,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Panel Upholds IRS Lifting of Ministry's Tax-Exempt Status</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court today cleared the
way for the Internal Revenue Service to revoke the PTL television
ministry's tax-exempt status.
   The IRS wants to revoke PTL's exempt status in part because PTL
had used contributions to fund the lavish lifestyles of Jim Bakker
and his wife Tammy, said IRS lawyer Francis Allegra.
   Officials of the ministry Bakker founded had argued that loss of
tax-exempt status could scuttle efforts to reorganize the ministry
by a federal bankruptcy court's May 1 deadline.
   Bakker resigned from PTL after a scandal over a sexual encounter
with former church secretary Jessica Hahn.
   Attorneys for the IRS, seeking to make the revocation
retroactive to May 31, 1981, said PTL owes the government from $55
million to $82 million in back taxes.
   Today's unanimous ruling from a three-judge panel of the 4th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed a decision by U.S. District
Judge Karen L. Henderson of Columbia, S.C..
   Henderson had found that the bankruptcy court handling the PTL
reorganization did not have the authority to prevent the IRS from
lifting the ministry's tax-exempt status.
   ``Although a revocation may potentially obstruct the orderly
administration in bankruptcy, we decline to create and exception
... in the absence of expressed congressional intent,'' the panel
said.
   R. Bradford Leggett, a PTL attorney, had argued before the
appeals panel on March 31 that loss of tax-exempt status would
jeopardize the ministry's ability to reorganize by the bankruptcy
court's May 1 deadline.
   The ministry, based in Fort Mill, S.C., is engaged in a ``March
to Victory'' telethon to raise $4.2 million by May 1. PTL has debts
estimated at $60 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
