<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   04-20 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0686</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: to ratification.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   April 16
   Lawrence (Kan.) Journal-World on Larry Speakes and presidential
quotes:
   So, a former White House press secretary has been caught in the
act.
   Scandalous! Other press secretaries, past and present, have
decried (Larry) Speakes' actions and stated flatly that they would
have nothing to do with such behavior. The vehemence of their
protest almost makes one wonder if they might have something to
hide.
   Speakes was merely telling the press what the president thought
in a way that the president never objected to.
   He probably was wrong to represent some of those views as
verbatim quotes, but it wasn't as if he was misrepresenting the
president's opinion on the issues.
   It's doubtful that Speakes was the first press secretary to
fabricate some golden quotations for the president.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 13
   The Commercial Appeal, Memphis, Tenn., on the foreign trade bill:
   To the surprise of no one who keeps tabs on Congress, the
1,000-page foreign trade bill now nearing completion is riddled
with favors for special interests, some at the expense of
consumers. ...
   Perhaps the most flagrant giveaway _ worth about $100 million _
was slipped in for the Warner-Lambert Co. Its patent on Lopid, a
cholesterol-reducing drug, is due to expire in July 1989, when
generic drug firms could crank it out at lower prices.
   The bill would extend Warner-Lambert's patent for 3{ years. With
a month's supply of Lopid costing between $40 and $70, that would
be dandy for the company's bottom line.
   But the provision would gouge patients and taxpayers, who pay
for the drug through Medicare and Medicaid.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 15
   The Post-Crescent, Appleton-Neenah-Menasha, Wis., on income tax
forms:
   A word to the wise ought to be sufficient. Unfortunately, many
of us aren't very wise.
   Otherwise, we wouldn't have waited until April 15 to file our
federal and state income-tax returns.
   For some of us, that annual decision to procrastinate will mean
a deadline missed and a penalty still to be paid. For others, it
will mean a vow to do it on time next year. ...
   But while we profess empathy for procrastinators, we cannot help
but wonder how many of us would have beaten the deadline if only
those infernal Internal Revenue Service forms had been
decipherable, if only the tax simplification we've been hearing so
much about in recent years really meant tax simplification. ...
   For most of us, even those with higher educations and accounting
experience, those tax forms are perfect examples of government
bureaucratese at its worst.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 15
   The Seattle Times on Contra drug dealing:
   A political time bomb ticks away as a Senate subcommittee
investigating narcotics and terrorism raises unavoidable questions
about Reagan administration knowledge of Contra drug dealing. ...
   Former diplomats, senior military commanders, ex-Contra
chieftains, and convicted drug dealers paint an ugly picture of a
pretend war against the cocaine lords.
   In many cases, a veneer of anti-communism was reason enough to
tolerate affiliations with drug traffickers.
   In short, maintaining support for the anti-Sandinista Contras
was more important to the administration than resolutely saying no
to drugs.
   How these compromises will play out in 1988 presidential
politics is unknown, but the testimony and evidence presented to
the committee should sicken North Americans whose daily lives are
tormented by drugs in their homes or neighborhoods.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 14
   The Honolulu Star-Bulletin on Larry Speakes and presidential
quotes:
   There would be no harm in composing statements and issuing them
in the president's name provided they were first cleared with him.
   But issuing statements without prior clearance crosses the line
between the permissible and the impermissible, and (Larry) Speakes
should have had enough sense to realize it.
   (President) Reagan has done a lot to hurt his credibility by
making unfounded and sometimes contradictory statements.
   He didn't need his press secretary making matters worse.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
