<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BusWreck 2ndLd-Writethru a0662 04-20 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Wreck, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0662,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>14 Still Hospitalized After Bus Carrying Children Wrecks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Restores time element, graf 2</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ROCK HILL, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state highway patrol has charged a
bus driver with driving too fast after a chartered bus carrying
Pinecrest Elementary School students crashed, leaving 14 people
hospitalized today.
   The bus, with 48 people students and adults aboard, rolled over
twice on Interstate 77 south of Rock Hill on Tuesday, authorities
said. Everyone aboard was injured, although most of the injuries
were not serious.
   One of the students, a girl, was in critical condition with a
head injury at Charlotte Memorial Hospital, hospital spokeswoman
Amy Farugia said today. Four other victims were also at the
hospital.
   Carolyn Carpenter, a spokeswoman at Piedmont Medical Center in
Rock Hill, said nine people were hospitalized there today.
   The highway patrol has charged the driver, Howard D. Boles, 31,
of Greenwood with driving too fast for conditions, even though he
was observing the speed limit and road conditions were good, said
department spokesman Frank Braddock.
   State Trooper Jerry Farrell said Boles' ``attention was
distracted'' when he reached down to get a soft drink and the bus
left the road.
   The bus is owned by Boles Bus Service of Greenwood, troopers
said. Boles was cut on the head but was not hospitalized.
   A caravan of three buses _ the school's entire fourth grade _
was returning from Discovery Place in Charlotte to Greenwood. The
students were among about 2,000 school children visiting Discovery
Place, said Executive Director Freda Nicholson.
   Nine people were admitted to Piedmont Medical Center in Rock
Hill, according to spokeswoman Carolyn Carpenter. Seven are in good
condition, while one is in satisfactory condition and one is in
stable condition in the intensive care unit, Ms. Carpenter said.
   Ms. Farugia said that in addition to the critically injured
girl, three other students were in good condition at Charlotte
Hospital with cuts and bruises and one adult was in serious
condition with head injuries and a broken leg.
   David Tipps, a construction worker from McAllister, Okla., was
driving behind the bus on his way to Columbia when he saw the bus
swerve off the road and flip over.
   ``There was nothing to make him crash. He just went over,''
Tipps said.
   He said the first drivers on the scene felt helpless because of
the magnitude of the accident.
   ``We just helped who we could,'' Tipps said. ``We grabbed them
and started pulling them out of the bus.''
</TEXT>
