<1ST_LINE>r a PM-IntruderShot     04-20 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Intruder Shot,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Murder Charge Dropped Against Teen Who Shot Intruder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPARTANBURG, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A magistrate has dismissed a murder
charge against a teen-ager who shot and killed a man as he was
trying to break into the youth's house.
   Solicitor Holman Gossett, who requested the charge be dropped
Tuesday, said a 65-year-old state law gave Ronald James Sutton the
right to use deadly force to protect his home.
   Sutton, 17, was charged with murder after he shot Freddie
Edwards Dawkins Jr., 22, on Easter night. Police found Dawkins'
body outside Sutton's bedroom window, the window screen resting on
his legs.
   The murder charge against the black youth sparked protests from
people who said the case was no different from that of a
11-year-old white boy, Todd Knight, who only days earlier shot and
killed two intruders into his home in Switzer and earned widespread
praise for justifiable homicide.
   Sutton's mother, Irene Jones, said her son was overjoyed with
the news that the charge was dropped. ``I believe he can get back
to a normal life. He was under a lot of pressure,'' she said.
   Spartanburg City Police Capt. John Lee said the charges were
filed because Sutton did not give Dawkins a warning to leave, did
not attempt to escape and did not call police before firing the
shots.
   Lee said the charges were dismissed by Magistrate Georgia
Anderson at Gossett's request and in concert with police
investigators.
   The 1923 law Gossett cited applies to deaths in which ``the
occupant is the slayer and stands on the right to protect
habitation, if he is in his own house and he determines a
trespasser is committing a felonious act.''
   Sutton, a Spartanburg High School sophomore, told police that
someone rang the doorbell at his home four times several hours
after his mother had left for work.
   He was too frightened to answer, but fired the fatal shot
through his blind-covered bedroom window when he heard someone
trying to remove the screen, the teen-ager told police.
   Sutton was charged with murder and spent one-and-a-half days in
jail before his $2,500 bond was set by a circuit court judge.
   ``It was unfortunate that this young man had to go through what
he went through,'' Lee added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
