<HEAD>Bank, Health Workers Strike over Fuel Prices in Nigeria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking workers paralyzed banks and
curtailed health care in a northern city, joining nationwide
protests over increased fuel prices, newspapers said Wednesday.
   Government hospital patients were left abandoned, and bank
workers refused to help customers rushing to withdraw money in the
northern city of Kano, according to the reports in Lagos, the
capital.
   The strike was called Tuesday by 19 industrial trade unions
protesting the higher petroleum prices.
   Meanwhile, police used tear gas to break up demonstrating
students Tuesday in the northwestern part of the country, the News
Agency of Nigeria reported. Their college was closed after the
incident, the report said.
   Six students were killed last week during protests, which began
in the northern city of Jos. More than 20 universities have been
closed.
