<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Philippines-Bases,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philippines Chief of Staff Relieved as US Base Commander</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino on Wednesday
relieved the Philippine commander of her country's U.S. military
bases, which are the subject of ongoing joint talks.
   Mrs. Aquino ordered armed forces chief Gen. Renato de Villa to
step down from his post as commander of U.S. bases in the
Philippines, the presidential palace announced.
   Although the Philippine government technically commands the six
U.S. installations, they are controlled by the United States.
   It was not clear how the move might affect negotiations on
renewing the agreement allowing the United States to operate the
bases. Philippine officials said it would have no bearing.
   Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos said he recommended the chief of
staff be relieved as commander of U.S. bases because the position
entails additional responsibilities for an already busy man and can
be filled by an officer with a much lower rank. Ramos said the
Philippine commander of the bases should be an officer with a rank
not higher than the commanders of the U.S. facilities.
   No replacement was named.
</TEXT>
