<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Old Bones,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Finds Century-Old Bones While Unclogging Pipe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Human bones unearthed while a man was
unclogging a drainage pipe may be 100 years old, an anthropolgist
says.
   ``We're going back out there to see if we can't find more of
that individual,'' said William Bass of the University of
Tennessee. ``We think the feet are on one side of the trench and
the arms are on the other side of it.''
   A week ago Harry Kennedy was trying to unstop the drainage line
from his washing machine when a helper unearthed the bones.
   ``I was sitting here in the house and went out there to see how
he was doing and he pitched a bone up on the bank,'' said Kennedy,
73. ``I said we ought to stop right here and call the police; I
believe this is a human bone.''
   A sheriff's deputy brought bones from a thigh, pelvis and lower
arm to the county coroner's office, which turned them over to Bass.
   Bass, also a forensic pathologist for the state, said a
preliminary review indicates the bones are from an adult male.
</TEXT>
