<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0580,0833</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinians Barred From Israel, One Arab Slain</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with clashes, one Arab killed.
Picks up 5th graf pvs `In a Memorial Day...'. SUBS 1 graf,
beginning `Palestinian leaders... ' for grafs 15-18 pvs to remove
redundant material. Edits elsewhere to trim. </NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers today fought Palestinians protesting
the assassination of a PLO leader, and one Arab was killed. Other
troops blocked Palestinians in the occupied lands from entering
Israel.
   Hundreds of thousands of Israelis gathered in cemeteries
throughout Israel today to remember the 16,450 troops who died
fighting for the nation. In the occupied territories, Arabs hung
black banners and mourned PLO military commander Khalil al-Wazir.
   An army spokesman said Israel would be closed to Arab residents
of the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip through the weekend in an
effort to prevent terrorist attacks during Memorial Day and
Independence Day commemorations, which started Tuesday night.
   Israeli troops also maintained a curfew for a fourth day on 17
refugee camps and towns in the West Bank and six camps and towns in
Gaza to prevent further riots over the death of al-Wazir, who was
killed in Tunis on Saturday.
   Israeli sources have said Israeli commandos killed al-Wazir, who
was buried in Damascus today. The government has not confirmed
Israeli involvement.
   Since the assassination, 21 Palestinians have died in clashes
with Israeli troops.
   According to U.N. figures, 169 Palestinians have been killed
since anti-occupation unrest began Dec. 8. Two Israelis also have
died.
   In Gaza's Nusseirat refugee camp, troops opened fire on
stone-throwing Arabs today, killing 21-year-old Mohammed Hassan
Massar, hospital officials said. Ten Arabs were wounded in clashes
around the occupied lands.
   In a Memorial Day speech, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir told
American Jewish fund-raisers in Jerusalem that what they were
seeing in the 4{-month Arab uprising was ``not demonstrations or
sit-ins. It is war.''
   He also said a public controversy over soldiers' duties in the
West Bank and Gaza would not affect their resolve.
   ``I can tell that they know that what they are doing now is just
as important for the country's future as anything they have done in
the past and we're just as proud of them now as we were then,''
Shamir said.
   Shortly after the speech, sirens sounded throughout the country
for two minutes marking the start of ceremonies at military
cemeteries to honor the 40-year-old nation's war dead.
   Memorials also were held at thousands of elementary and high
schools around Israel, where teachers held special classes and
pupils laid wreaths and recited poems in honor of those who fell in
battle and training accidents.
   At Denmark High School, one of Jerusalem's largest Jewish
secondary schools, bereaved parents and teachers urged pupils to
learn from the patriotism of peers who gave their lives for their
country.
   ``Everyone has to defend our homeland,'' Russian-born Moses
Cyrus Weiler, 81, who lost two sons in Israeli wars, told 11th
graders in one classroom. ``If you continue in this path, there
will be value to your life.''
   The Memorial Day observance ends tonight with a torch-lighting
ceremony at Mount Herzl that starts the Independence Day
celebration.
   Security was intense, with military barricades blocking roads in
the occupied lands. Officials said only Arabs with special permits
would be allowed into Israel until the Independence Day
celebrations end Thursday night.
   Places of entertainment, including movie theaters and
restaurants, were ordered closed for the day.
   Palestinians leaders urged Arabs to protest the deportations
Tuesday of eight more Arabs from the occupied lands to Lebanon.
They include six accused of the April 6 stoning attack on Jewish
hikers in the West Bank village of Beita, where a 15-year-old
Israeli girl, Tirza Porat, was killed.
   The United States condemned the expulsions, saying they would
exacerbate tensions in the territories Israel seized in the 1967
Middle East war.
   Police Commissioner David Krauss said extra police were posted
throughout the country and about 1,000 officers would patrol
Jerusalem until the Moslem sabbath ends Friday.
   ``There is information that terror organizations will try to
carry out attacks,'' he told Israel radio.
   The deportations brought to 16 the number of Palestinians
expelled from Israel this month.
   The Israeli army Tuesday said some of the Beita deportees had
planned the attack on the Israeli hikers and hoped to hold some of
the teen-agers hostage. It was the first time the army had
suggested the attack was premeditated. Two Palestinians also were
killed in the clash.
   A police report said investigators could not determine if the
bullet that killed Miss Porat had been fired from the gun of one of
the Israeli guards accompanying the group or from another weapon.
   An army spokesman said Tuesday that separate investigations by
the army and Israel's Shin Bet security service had not been
completed.
</TEXT>
