<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House today expressed concern over
delays in ratifying a U.S.-Soviet nuclear-arms treaty and said it
would be ``most unfortunate'' if the agreement were not approved by
the time President Reagan goes to Moscow for summit talks.
   The treaty, which requires the elimination of medium-range
nuclear weapons, has been stalled by a number of issues, most
recently the question of whether futuristic weapons are banned by
the pact.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said a failure to ratify
the treaty by the time Reagan meets with Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev May 29-June 2 would be a setback to ongoing negotiations
to curb strategic nuclear weapons under a so-called START treaty.
   Fitzwater said that to have the medium-range weapon treaty
ratified before the summit ``would be an important boost to our
negotiations on the START treaty.
   ``Similarly, if it's not (ratified) it would tend to dampen, I
think, the prospects for serious START progress. It would not be
helpful and we would hope that the Ccongress would be able to
ratify it before we go.''
   The treaty is not expected to come to the Senate floor until May
9 at the earliest, leaving only 2{ weeks before Reagan's departure.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., said Tuesday that the question about
futuristic weapons is still unanswered despite a statement by a top
Soviet official.
   ``I think the question still needs clarification and there's got
to be some more work done on this issue,'' he said.
   Fitzwater said the issues raised in the Senate ``are all
important and they certainly deserve clarification. We believe they
have received it.''
   The administration argues that the treaty will not affect
development of futuristic weapons.
   As Nunn expressed his reservations, the House was voting 393-7
in favor of a non-binding resolution approving the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty.
   The vote has no effect on the Senate, which has exclusive
constitutional authority to ratify treaties.
   Nunn commented a day after the State Department forwarded to the
Senate the transcipt of a letter by Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
A. Shevardnadze to Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   In the letter, Shevardnadze said the Soviets agree with the
United States that the INF treaty signed last Dec. 8 bans
``futuristic weapons'' such as lasers or beam weapons.
   The treaty eliminates existing missiles with a range of 300 to
3,400 miles, but Nunn and other senators have questioned how the
pact0would affect weapons in that range0dlatcoumd be1d
