<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 1254EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iraq-Faw Bjt   04-20 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Faw, Bjt,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqis Dig in On Recaptured Faw Peninsula</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   An Associated Press reporter was taken on a tour
of the Faw Peninsula by the Iraqi military, and filed the following
report:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FAW PENINSULA, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi troops who recaptured this
strategic peninsula from Iran found heavily shelled buildings
plastered with pictures of Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini and anti-Iraqi slogans.
   They also discovered piles of Islamic religious books, many
written by Khomeini, that Iranian soldiers left behind in an
apparently hasty retreat.
   An Iraqi general told reporters here Tuesday that Iraqi forces
had completely dislodged Iranian troops from the Faw peninsula,
recapturing territory seized by Iran 26 months ago. Hundreds of
Iranian prisoners were shown to reporters.
   Other Iraqi reports on Wednesday acknowledged that pockets of
Iranian resistance remained on the peninsula.
   The general, speaking at his command post near the oil refinery
city of Faw, identified himself only as a representative of the
Iraqi high command. The reporters were the first to reach the Faw
peninsula since it was recaptured.
   The general spoke as Iraqis were building new fortifications
after recapturing the triangle of land at the southern tip of their
country. It was the first major Iraqi offensive since 1986 in the
7{-year-old Persian Gulf war.
   Hundreds of military vehicles headed toward Faw on Tuesday to
reinforce elite presidential guard units that spearheaded the
36-hour assault Sunday and Monday.
   The city of Faw, which reporters visited 15 hours after the
Iranians were driven out, was quiet. There were, however, sporadic
shellings which Iraqis said came from new Iranian positions in
thick palm groves on the eastern bank of the Shatt Al-Arab
waterway, the southern border between Iran and Iraq.
   Ration storage areas had been left intact, suggesting a speedy
Iranian retreat.
   Iraqi military officials said many weapons were seized, without
giving numbers. Reporters saw ammunition left intact in storage
depots.
   About 250 Iranian prisoners-of-war were shown to reporters, and
many of them talked about being surprised by the Iraqi offensive.
   One Iranian prisoner, Mohammed Idage, 49, said he was in a
bunker, which provided shelter from Iraqi shells, when he was
caught by Iraqi soldiers.
   ``I thought the Iraqis were too far away, and nobody told us
that they were approaching so rapidly,'' he said. ``It was a real
surprise to see Iraqis all around the bunker.''
   The general said the offensive was launched to regain control of
the 35 square-mile triangle of territory occupied by Iran in
February 1986. He said the Iraqi air force and navy joined ground
forces in the operation.
   He also denied Iranian charges that Iraq used the nearby Kuwaiti
island of Bubiyan as a staging position for part of the offensive.
   ``The Iranians are trying to conceal their crimes against our
brothers in Kuwait and their hijacking of the Kuwait aircraft,'' he
said.
   He referred to claims that Iran was behind the hijacking of a
Kuwait Airways jumbo jet which took the plane to Iran, Cyprus and
Algeria before it ended Wednesday.
   As the general spoke, a powerful explosion rocked the ground
nearby.
   ``Not to worry, it's outgoing,'' said an Iraqi captain. ``The
Iranians are there,'' he said, pointing to the date palms across
the waterway.
   He said Iraqi troops continued to shell those positions in a bid
to prevent any reorganization of Iranian troops.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880420-0139 </DOCNO>
