<DOCNO> AP880420-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 1259EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-UN     04-20 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-UN,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US-Iran Confrontation Dims Outlook for UN Peace Effort</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. efforts to end the Iran-Iraq war,
already near collapse, suffered another setback from this week's
Persian Gulf military confrontation between the United States and
Iran.
   The Security Council passed a resolution July 20 demanding an
immediate cease-fire in the 7{-year-old war, but Iran has accepted
it only with reservations.
   Since the resolution was passed, the war has intensified with
missile attacks on cities by both sides that have killed hundreds
of people, a new Iranian push into Iraqi territory on the northern
front and reports that Iraq has used chemical weapons.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar gave the council a
gloomy picture last week of his four rounds of talks with Iranian
and Iraqi envoys, concluding that their positions were
``insufficient'' for a cease-fire.
   On Tuesday, he expressed grave concern about further escalation
of the war. The 15-member council has been deliberating informally
on how or whether its resolution can be enforced.
   Diplomats said privately the U.S. campaign for a council arms
embargo on Iran was undermined by U.S. Navy attacks on two Iranian
oil platforms Monday and ensuing operations in which six Iranian
naval vessels were sunk or disabled.
   They said the confrontation made it less likely that governments
would take sides with Washington to punish Iran for what now
appears to be a conflict with a superpower.
   The Soviet Union, which has delayed action on an embargo,
condemned the U.S. attacks and the diplomats said Soviet suport for
a ban on arms sales to Iran had become unlikely.
   U.S. officials said, however, that they hope the clash between
the U.S. and Iranian navies will help break a Security Council
impasse.
   ``We think this proves more strongly than ever the need for an
enforcement resolution'' imposing a weapons ban on Iran, U.S.
Ambassador Herbert S. Okun said Monday after briefing the council
on events in the gulf.
   Washington said its actions were ``necessary and proportionate''
response to an Iranian threat, and legitmate self-defense. The oil
platforms were attacked as retaliation for a mine that damaged a
U.S. Navy frigate last week and wounded 10 sailors.
   Iran vowed retaliation against the United States and Ambassador
Mohammad Mahallati said Tuesday:
   ``The American aggression has strongly and substantially
weakened the Security Council resolution and violated its call for
restraint by all states.''
   Resolution 598 demands an immediate cease-fire and troop
withdrawal, outlines a peace plan and calls for enforcement
measures. It was seen in July as a rare example of U.N. toughness
and a test of its ability to put teeth in demands for an end to the
war.
   Iraq has said it accepts the resolution, but Iran wants the
cease-fire linked to identification of Iraq as the aggressor. Iraq
invaded Iran in September 1980 after several border skirmishes.
</TEXT>
