<DATELINE>PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Restaurateur Sonny Bono has taken
the oath of office as mayor of this desert resort and gotten a hug
from one of his major campaign critics.
   Bono, 53, joined the ranks of celebrity mayors on Tuesday.
   He won his seat April 12 just as another well-known small city
mayor, actor-director Clint Eastwood, was easing out of his job as
mayor of Carmel on California's rugged coast near Big Sur.
   A celebratory barbecue before the swearing-in, Bono buried the
hatchet with one of his chief detractors, outgoing Mayor Frank
Bogert.
   During the campaign, Bogert, 76, acidly observed that the
difference between Bono's mayoral bid and that of Eastwood was
comparable to the difference between chicken manure and chicken
salad.
   But all was friendship and enthusiasm Tuesday, as Bogert gave
Bono a hug.
   ``That's the way they do it in Mexico,'' Bogert said, squeezing
the incoming mayor. ``That's called an `abrazo.' Here's a big
abrazo for Sonny Bono.''
   Bono responded graciously, saying ``Muchas Gracias.''
   Cher's ex-husband won his new post a day after the actress he
crooned ``I've Got You, Babe'' with during the 1960s won the 1988
best actress Oscar for her performance in ``Moonstruck.''
   Bono was swept into office, winning over a field of six
lesser-known candidates, promising to revive some of the tourist
splendor Palm Springs has surrendered in recent years to
neighboring desert communities where celebrities like former
President Gerald Ford and Frank Sinatra have chosen to live.
