<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Jobless     04-20 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Jobless,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unemployment at 30,000 & Rising, Official Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hungary-Romanians, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unemployment in Hungary has risen from
10,000 jobless last year to 30,000, and is expected to go up by
another 19,000 yet this year, a labor official was quoted as saying
Wednesday.
   Csaba Halmos, president of the National Office for Wages and
Labor, also said 10,000 jobs will be created this year.
   According to the Communist Party daily Nepszabadsag, which
carried Halmos' remarks, the labor official said about 700,000
people change jobs each year out of Hungary's work force of 5
million.
   Rising unemployment in Hungary is largely a consequence of
austerity measures introduced by the government that include
streamlining or closing companies that chronically lose money.
   Halmos was quoted as saying 19,000 jobs probably would be
eliminated this year.
   He said unemployment was likely to increase, but called for
caution in claiming it could rise to 100,000 to 150,000. According
to official estimates, there could be as many as 200,000 jobless by
1990.
   Halmos, however, predicted 100,000 to 150,000 new jobs could be
created in restructured factories or in private enterprise and
cooperatives. He gave no timetable for such a development.
   About 10,000 workers received retraining last year, and found
new jobs, Nepszabadsag quoted Halmos as saying.
   According to statistics published in January, 70 percent of
Hungary's jobless are unskilled workers who find it harder to find
employment.
</TEXT>
