<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Rock     04-20 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Rock,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Preceded Tipper Gore in Music Lyrics Fight</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of presidential candidate Albert Gore
Jr. raised controversy when she spearheaded a campaign to put
warning labels on rock music albums with sexually explicit lyrics.
   But another presidential contender _ Jesse Jackson _ was
treading the same ground long before Tipper Gore made headlines.
   Jackson in 1977 put on a ``Music and Morality Conference'' at
his Operation PUSH in Chicago, urging that voluntary standards be
drawn up by the record industry and radio stations, newspaper
clippings show.
   ``We hope this conference will send a message to the industry
because Chicago is such a major market,'' Jackson was quoted as
telling the Chicago Tribune. Like Mrs. Gore, Jackson said he was
not advocating censorship. He said he wanted ``voluntary standards
by the radio stations and by the record companies themselves.''
   ``Love and romance are part of life and we are not suggesting
that these subjects should be censored in record lyrics,'' Jackson
wrote in a letter published in the newspaper on May 28, 1977.
   ``Our appeal has been directed toward pornographic lyrics that
degrade human sexuality rather than uplifting the human spirit.''
   Jackson said a recording at the time, ``Let's Make a Baby,'' was
``one in a whole series, increasingly explicit and dominant in a
market almost exclusively directed at children.''
   He called on the record industry to ``assess the state of the
art.''
   Mrs. Gore created an uproar in the music industry, and cost her
husband some support among the Hollywood set, with her crusade
against sex, drugs and violence in music over the past few years.
   Tipper Gore, a co-founder of the Parents Music Resource Center,
testified before the Senate Commerce Committee, of which her
husband was a member, in 1985 about what the group felt was the
danger of explicit lyrics.
   The Recording Industry Association of America later reached an
uneasy agreement with the center, stating its members would place
warning labels on records,such as: ``Explicit Lyrics _ parental
advisory.''
   Mrs. Gore 's leadership brought opposition from such
entertainers as Frank Zappa. He disagreed with Mrs. Gore's
assertion that lyrics could promote deviant behavior, saying, ``I
wrote a song aboiut dental floss but anyone's teeth get cleaner?''
   Jackson has not made rock music a part of his campaign or
speeches. But he frequently speaks against ``babies making babies''
and urges young people not to waste their minds with drugs.
   In his 1977 letter to the Tribune, he said the crusade against
``sex-rock'' was part of Operation PUSH's educational arm,
PUSH-Excel which was aimed at motivating young people to study.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880420-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 1319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis     04-20 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis: `Nothing is Inevitable'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, the undisputed front-runner at
last in a two-man race for the Democratic presidential nomination,
remained ever cautious on Wednesday and said ``nothing in this
world'' is certain.
   Dukakis met with rival Jesse Jackson early Wednesday to receive
congratulations on a sweeping New York primary victory, but the
Massachusetts governor declined to meet with loser Albert Gore Jr.,
citing the press of state business in Boston.
   Dukakis flew back to Boston after an early morning meeting with
reporters and was taking a day's respite from campaigning. He
resumes the Democratic campaign Thursday in Ohio and Pennsylvania.
   Although his victory was broad and impressive, Dukakis faced
repeated questions about his dispassionate campaign style and polls
showing that large numbers of Democrats longed for some other
candidate to be in the race despite his convincing victory here.
   ``I'm somebody who I think tends to grow on people as they get
to know me,'' Dukakis responded.
   ``As it continues to go on, we'll see stronger and stronger and
more intense support. But obviously for many people I'm a
relatively new acquaintance, and it's going to take a while to
build that kind of support,'' he said.
   Dukakis' big victory and Gore's failure left the governor with a
strong lead in delegates, although he acknowledged a delegate
majority was not yet within his reach. But New York pared Gore from
the field, making it hard to envision Dukakis failing to win the
nomination.
   Campaign manager Paul Brountas said New York's returns would
encourage uncommitted delegates and those still backing losers to
move toward Dukakis, but he said the campaign was not trying to
produce a visible stampede of support within the party. Such a big
move too soon could risk alienating Jackson supporters that the
nominee needs in November.
   Dukakis said a one-on-one race with Jackson will be conducted
without division or attacks. He predicted that by the end of the
primaries in June ``I doubt either one of us will have a numerical
majority'' of delegates.
   ``But I hope I have a substantial lead and the kind of lead that
will then make it possible for me to unite the party, to produce a
clear majority,'' he said.
   Dukakis said he was unable to meet with Gore, who was poised to
withdraw at an announcement Thursday in Washington.
   He called a Gore withdrawal ``something he has to decide,'' but
said he would help Gore raise money to eliminate a campaign debt
that approaches $2 million.
   He said Gore, who launched strong attacks on Dukakis as naive
and inexperienced in foreign policy, ``wanted to meet this morning
and I just couldn't do it.''
   ``I've got to get back to Boston. I've got to get a very
important meeting ... of my anti-crime council and a very full
agenda, and I just had to get back there. But I'm sure we'll be
talking. He's a good guy and I've enjoyed getting to know him and I
respect him.''
   He did meet with Jackson and later said it was ``too early to
say'' what role he sees for Jackson. Asked if he would consider
Jackson as his running mate, Dukakis said, ``I wouldn't rule
anything in or out at this point.''
   ``He's obviously an important leader in our party and in our
country. We respect each other,'' he said.
   Dukakis refused to claim the role as likely nominee, saying
``nothing in this world is inevitable and we've got much to do.''
</TEXT>
