<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ShuttleTest 1stLd-Writethru a0548 04-20 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle Test, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0548,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Full-Scale Test Conducted Of Redesigned Shuttle Booster Rocket</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with test completed, raising reference to what
test is about</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morton Thiokol conducted a full-scale
test of a space shuttle booster rocket with deliberately flawed
seals today to see whether hot gases would penetrate the joints as
they did when the Challenger exploded.
   ``It looked good. We've got to wait and see the data, but you
always like to see it go off on time and see it run 120 seconds,''
said J..R. Thompson, director of NASA's Marshall Space Flight
Center in Huntsville, Ala.
   ``If we get good results, then we'll press on at the Cape,'' he
said, referring to preparations for a mid-August launch of the
shuttle Discovery at Cape Canaveral.
   The two-minute firing of the 126-foot-long, 1.2 million-pound
booster at 11 a.m. was the third in a series of five full-scale
tests scheduled before the shuttle returns to space.
   The test was designed to reveal any weaknesses in the new
booster, which was redesigned following the Jan. 28, 1986,
explosion of the shuttle Challenger that killed seven astronauts.
   For the test, the rocket was assembled with deliberate flaws in
the sealing material of two joints to see if hot gases would
penetrate them. Flawed seals have been tested previously in
short-duration tests, but never in a full-scale firing, Raab said.
   A plume of bright yellow flame erupted from the rocket, sending
a cloud of grayish-brown smoke and dust billowing hundreds of feet
in the air. Cattle grazing nearby bolted at the roar and hundreds
of company workers and school children cheered and applauded.
   Company engineers and NASA officials planned a briefing after
they conduct a preliminary inspection of the prone rocket. A
detailed analysis of the results was several days away.
   The Challenger disaster was blamed on a booster rocket joint
improperly sealed by a rubber O-ring, which allowed hot gases to
escape and ignite the shuttle's external fuel tank.
   The redesigned joint has a third O-ring to protect the primary
O-ring from hot gases. The old joint had two rings. A gap between
sections of insulation in the old joint is now filled with putty.
   Engineers also have added a metal lip, called the capture
feature, that rests between the insulation and the O-rings. The lip
is designed to prevent the joint from bulging under the pressure of
burning gases during launch.
   
   The remaining full-scale tests are scheduled for June and July.
If all goes well, the shuttle's first post-Challenger launch is set
for sometime in mid-August.
   The test comes at a critical time for Thiokol. The company is
NASA's sole supplier of booster rockets, and views a successful
launch as a sign that the stigma of the Challenger tragedy can be
set aside.
   While praising Thiokol's work in the redesign effort, NASA also
has asked Congress for a $1.2 million government plant to build
advanced space shuttle booster rockets. The space agency wants the
proposed plant to be accessible by rail and water, which would
exclude Thiokol's plant in land-locked Utah.
</TEXT>
