<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Arms Dealer,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses Indictment Against Arms Dealer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today dismissed an indictment for
possession of illegal rocket launchers and machine guns against an
international arms merchant.
   U.S. District Judge Edward B. Davis also dismissed a charge of
possession of weapons by a convicted felon against Sarkis
Soghanalian.
   The 57-year-old Soghanalian, a Lebanese national who lives in
Miami, had been scheduled to go on trial on the charges Thursday.
He is still scheduled for trial May 16 in another arms case.
   Davis granted a motion for dismissal filed by attorney Neal
Sonnett on grounds that Soghanalian never had ``constructive
possession'' of arms mounted on a Bell helicopter at a hangar at
Miami international airport.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Robert O'Neill told Davis that after
interviewing witnesses he could not oppose the defense motion for
dismissal.
   But O'Neill said the government is proceeding in the second
case, in which Soghanalian is charged with violating the Arms
Export Control Act by conspiring to smuggle to Iraq combat
helicopters worth $200 million and other arms counts.
   Soghanalian has charged the indictments were returned at the
instigation of Iran.
