<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson'sObstacles Bjt   04-20 0792</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson's Obstacles, Bjt,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Road is Long With Many a Winding Turn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The road from here to California for Jesse
Jackson is a rough one, strewn with ballot problems, unfavorable
rules, small numbers of black voters, and big leads for Michael
Dukakis in states from Pennsylvania to Ohio and beyond.
   Eleven primaries remain before the Democratic National
Convention in Atlanta, and only one _ the District of Columbia _
offers Jackson a solid shot  The landscape is particularly difficult now
that Dukakis has
opened a lead in the delegate count and is even winning the
cumulative popular vote _ which Jackson had claimed at victory.
  was the most
important battle. Jackson needs at least two big-state victories in
the next seven weeks to have a hope of pulling back even with the
Massachusetts governor.
   Jackson had a chance in Tuesday's New York primary, where his
base of support was large and the potential for expanding his share
of the white vote seemed substantial. But he fell short, taking
only 37 percent of the vote as Dukakis won half the ballots.
   ``The challenge between Pennsylvania and California and New
Jersey is to keep asserting presidential leadership, keep giving
the nation a real live alternative,'' Jackson said Wednesday. ``I
want to give the nation a real live option between now and June 7,
and I'm going to do that.''
    VA policy that regards alcoholism as misconduct was
challenged by Eugene Traynor, 46, a supervisor in a photography
laboratory in New York City, and James P. McKelvey, 42, an
alcoholism counselor in Washington, D.C.
   Both men, who began drinking when they were children, received
honorable discharges from the Army in the late 1960s. They said
they have abstained from drinking alcohol since the early 1970s,
when they were hospitalized and treated for the condition.
   The VA authorizes payment of education benefits to veterans
within 10 years of their discharge. No benefits are paid after 10
years unless a veteran can show he or she was unable to pursue an
education ``because of a physical or mental disability which was
not the result of such veteran's own willful misconduct.''
   The VA provides an exemption from the 10-year time limit for
alocholism only when it is a secondary sympton of other
psychological problems.
   Traynor and McKelvey filed federal lawsuits claiming the
Veterans Administration was discriminating illlegaly against the
handicapped.
   Federal appeals courts ruled against them in separate cases.
   McKelvey said the high court's decision gives a message ``to
other recovering alcoholics, or more importantly, people that are
out there struggling, trying to get sober, and dying from this
disease. ... I believe that the justices who ruled in favor of the
Veteran's Administration is giving them a license to kill, more or
less. They're saying that the Veteran's Administration can violate
existing federal statutes and get away with it.''
   A VA spokesman, John Scholzen, said the agency would have no
comment until its attorneys have examined the ruling.
   The cases attracted widespread attention with the current
renewed debate over the nature of alcoholism.
   Many programs have developed in recent years that treat
alcoholics as victims of a disease rather than as social deviants
or criminals.
   The psychiatrists' catalogue of diseases, called the Diagnostic
and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, calls alcohol abuse and
dependence a disease and says about 13 percent of all Americans
suffer from it at some point in their lives.
   Dr. David Goldman, a researcher at the National Institute on
Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism, said the medical community ``has gone
far beyond'' the debate about whether alcoholism is a disease. Now,
he said, researchers are trying to identify the specific gene that
they believe makes a person ``vulnerable'' to alcoholism.
   Some critics fear the recent trend treating alcoholism as a
disease dangerously removes individual responsibility for such
behavior as drunken driving and spouse and child abuse.
   Norma Phillips, the national president of Mothers Against Drunk
Driving, said her organization welcomes the decision because she
believes it will encourage judges to give tougher sentences in
drunken driving cases.
   ``There are some judges who feel people are not able to make a
decision after they drink,'' said Mrs. Phillips, of Escondido,
Calif. ``They feel they have an alcohol problem so they give
lighter sentences.''
   A spokesman for Alcoholocs Anonymous who asked not to be named
said the question of whether or not alcohol abuse is a disease does
not matter in AA treatment, which calls for group support in
staying sober.
   ``We've never taken any position as to whether or not it is an
illness because it doesn't really matter with our treatment
system,'' the spokesman said.
   There are an estimated 10 million alcoholics in the United
States, including about one million who seek treatment annually in
one form or another.
   In other action, the court:
   _ Ruled that unions may distribute handbills urging consumers to
boycott ``neutral employers'' against whom the unions have no
grievance.
   Voting 8-0 in a case from Florida, the justices said that
although federal labor law generally prohibits unions from engaging
in ``secondary boycott'' picketing of neutral employers it does not
ban non-picketing activities aimed at such businesses.
   In a separate decision, the court ruled by a 6-2 vote in a
California case that employers may be forced to provide free,
internal mail delivery for labor union literature aimed at
organizing employees.
   _ Upheld a law requiring munijcipal or state bonds issued after
June 30, 1983, to be registered before they can be tax-exempt.
   The justices, by a 7-1 vote, ruled that the federal law enacted
to discourage tax evasion in the trading of municipal bonds does
not violate any state's sovereign immunity.
   The alcoholism case is Traynor vs. Turnage, 86-622.
   The psychiatrists' catalogue of diseases, called the Diagnostic
and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, calls alcohol abuse and
dependence a disease and says about 13 percent of all Americans
suffer from it at some point in their lives.
</TEXT>
