<HEAD>Gore Campaign Coming To An End</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB 21st graf bgng ``Of those'' to update Gore's NY delegates
to 2 sted 15</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. is ending his campaign for
the 1988 Democratic presidential nomination after a weak
third-place showing in the New York primary, sources said today.
   The word from back home in Tennessee was that Gore should
``gracefully get out.'' Sources close to his campaign, speaking
only on condition of anonymity, said the candidate was grappling
with whether to hold his delegates until the convention.
   Gore, winless since Super Tuesday six weeks ago, scheduled an
announcement for Thursday in Washington.
   He told supporters in New York that he would be consulting with
advisers ``over the next few days ... and we're going to decide
among ourselves how best we can carry on the cause that we have
been advancing.''
   Campaign manager Fred Martin said Gore had not decided whether
to drop out.
   As the New York votes were tallied and the scope of Gore's loss
became clear, he congratulated Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis,
calling it ``somebody else's super Tuesday.''
   ``I want to congratulate Mike Dukakis for a really impressive
victory. New York is a real marathon and he beat us by a mile,'' he
said.
   Gore talked about the prospects of Democrats in the fall, rather
than his own uncertain future.
   ``I believe that together we are going to teach the Republicans
a lesson they won't soon forget in November,'' the Tennessee
senator told supporters gathered at a midtown hotel.
   Meanwhile, Tennessee Gov. Ned McWherter, a key Gore adviser,
said the senator was considering quitting the race.
   ``I told him he should gracefully get out and let this one
conclude,'' McWherter said from Nashville, Tenn. He said Gore had
called him from New York while awaiting primary results.
   ``The options are to continue campaigning and affect the
dialogue with the party, to suspend the candidacy but remain a
candidate or to withdraw,'' Martin said.
   Gore congratulated the second-place finisher in New York, Jesse
Jackson, praising his ``tremendous showing.''
   Early today, Gore paid a ``courtesy call'' on Jackson to tell
him of his plans for the next several days, said Gerald Austin,
Jackson's national campaign manager.
   Gore said his wife, Tipper, had gone on to Texas for a
fund-raiser set for tonight ``because we need the money.'' Gore
said he planned to meet her there.
   Gore's campaign is reported to be $1.6 million in debt, and he
had needed to win 20 percent of the vote in New York to be eligible
for federal matching funds.
   Martin discounted reports Tuesday that Gore had begun recalling
campaign workers from Pennsylvania, the next primary state. He
blamed Gore's poor showing in New York on lack of money and name
recognition and the perception by some that it was a two-person
race.
   Gore, at 40 the youngest candidate, joined the race June 29 at
the urging of a group of wealthy Democrats convinced that only a
Southerner could win in 1988.
   He made some early forays into Iowa, but when the waters proved
chilly, he declared Iowans had too much influence on the process
and said he would risk skipping the crucial caucus state. When
polls indicated a weak showing in New Hampshire, he left the North
altogether and headed to his native South to make a stand on Super
Tuesday.
   For one day, his strategy looked brilliant. He won six states on
March 8 and jumped immediately into the front tier with Dukakis and
Jackson. But the Gore campaign apparently had not looked beyond
Super Tuesday. With no one except the candidate apparently in
charge, the Gore campaign lurched into Illinois, Michigan and then
Wisconsin, gathering a total of 435 convention delegates along the
way.
   Of those delegates, only two came from the huge New York bloc of
255 up for grabs Tuesday. Gore pulled only 10 percent of the vote
here, far behind Dukakis' 51 percent and Jackson's 37 percent.
   The only consistent theme of Gore's campaign of late had been
attack. He launched regular salvos at Dukakis and Jackson, saying
it was ``nothing personal'' but the voters deserved to know the
differences among the candidates.
   In New York, Gore opened with a strategy centered on criticism
of the other two candidates, but when supporter Koch picked up the
theme with a vengeance, even Gore seemed to cringe.
   ``I never wanted to stop Mike Dukakis or stop Jesse Jackson,''
Gore said Tuesday night. ``I just wanted to start Al Gore.''
   Gore resisted criticizing Koch, but made it clear the mayor
spoke only for himself. After the polls closed, he thanked Koch for
his support, but noted, ``he ignored a lot of advice that he got
from people around him.''
</TEXT>
