<DOCNO> AP880420-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 1406EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-MaulingTrial     04-20 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mauling Trial,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Animal Trainer Gets Probation, Fine in Lion Mauling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury today sentenced the owner of a
lion that attacked a young girl to 10 years probation and a $5,000
fine, and a judge ordered the man to sell his exotic animals and
stay away from children.
   The jury had convicted Gary Durkovitz, 35, of injury to a child
last week, but deliberated on the sentence for another 2{ days.
   Durkovitz's pet lion ``Samson'' attacked Roxanne Hernandez, 8,
at the Texas Flea Market on Oct. 10, 1987, in Houston.
   State District Judge Ted Poe imposed additional terms of
probation that included 20 hours per month of community service
work.
   Durkovitz, who is from Houston, must dispose of all of his
exotic animals, must stay away from children and also serve 30 days
in Harris County jail, ordered the judge.
   Jurors took about five hours to convict Durkovitz, but
deliberated for more than 15 hours over the penalty.
   Harris County prosecutors had asked for the maximum punishment
of 10 years in prison and a $5,000 fine, but defense attorneys
requested probation.
   Durkovitz, who had taken his 350-pound lion to previous shows at
the flea market, was walking his lion out of the building when the
attack occurred.
   Samson attacked the little girl when she walked in front of him
and tore off part of her skull. The girl, whose brain was exposed
after the attack, was hospitalized for a month and was unable to
return to school until February.
   She has undergone reconstructive surgery and faces more surgery
to restore part of her missing skull and a bald spot on her head.
   Her mother, Roxanne Hernandez, testified the girl wears a wig or
cap in public and that she has trouble concentrating.
   Durkovitz said that he had taken all the precautions he knew of
to prevent an attack.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
