<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rocker Eddie Van Halen, stricken with a
tropical virus while vacationing in Fiji, left Cedars-Sinai Medical
Center today after two days of treatment.
   ``The doctor gave him a clean bill of health. He is getting
ready for rehearsals of `Van Halen's Monsters of Rock Tour,'''
publicist Maureen O'Connor said shortly after Van Halen, 33, went
home to Malibu.
   Three other entertainers _ actor James Garner, comic Sid Caesar
and ex-TV star Morey Amsterdam _ remain hospitalized at
Cedars-Sinai.
   ``Yes, we're down to three now,'' said medical center spokesman
Ron Wise.
   Garner, 60, entered the hospital on Monday, while Caesar, 66,
and Amsterdam, 76, have been confined to the medical center for
several days.
   Amsterdam, best remembered as Buddy on ``The Dick Van Dyke
Show,'' had blood clots removed from each leg and ``he's doing very
well,'' said Wise. It wasn't known when Amsterdam would be released.
   Caesar, who had hernia surgery two weeks ago, was being treated
for an infection, the spokesman said.
   ``He's doing quite well and should be in the medical center
through rest of the week,'' said Wise.
   Garner was undergoing a series of tests prior to surgery
Thursday on his aorta, which carries blood away from the heart.
   ``It's major surgery and they are going to operate and take care
of it,'' Garner's assistant Maryann Rea said.
   Garner, best remembered by television viewers of the old
``Maverick'' and ``Rockford Files'' series, was nominated for an
Oscar for his starring role in the movie ``Murphy's Romance'' and
he starred in ``Victor Victoria.''
</TEXT>
