<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 1447EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MilitarySupplies     04-20 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Military Supplies,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GAO Faults Army On Contractor Supplies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army does not have the required systems in
place to adequately control government-furnished parts and supplies
provided to military contractors, according to a congressional
study released Wednesday.
   The General Accounting Office report, released by Sen. John
Glenn, D-Ohio, also said Army contractors are being permitted to
requisition material from Pentagon supplies without being
identified as contractors, as required by regulations.
   Glenn said the Defense Department estimated that Army
contractors held about $2.8 billion in government-furnished
material as of the end of fiscal 1987.
   ``We have created a large potential problem by giving
contractors ready access to billions of dollars' worth of
government property,'' said Glenn. ``Fiscal restraint should not be
AWOL at the Army.''
   Government-furnished material, or GFM, includes parts,
assemblies and other materials used in the production of tanks,
aircraft and ships.
   The Pentagon provides the material to contractors when it is
determined to be in the government's best interest. And the Army
allows contractors to obtain the material through direct access to
the defense supply system.
   ``The Army does not have in place the management control and
reporting systems that DOD requires to adequately control GFM
provided to contractors,'' the GAO concluded.
   The GAO, an investigative arm of Congress, said the Army expects
to have a new management-control system in place by June 1989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880420-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 1447EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeSillers     04-20 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DeSillers,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill Would Regulate Charitable Donations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANA SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The furor over $980,310 donated to help
a 7-year-old boy get a liver transplant prompted a Senate committee
Wednesday to approve a bill to establish stricter regulations of
charitable contributions.
   Ronnie DeSillers of Miami died last April while awaiting his
fourth liver transplant at Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh.
   Earlier this year, that state filed an administrative complaint
against his mother, accusing her of violating the state's charity
law by using some of the funds for personal expenses, including
rent and a car telephone.
   She was fined $1,000, but may contest that at a May 10 hearing,
said David Adams, spokesman for the Department of State.
   Current state law says a charitable account opened for a
beneficiary should be used only for that person.
   Maria DeSillers has denied wrongdoing, saying she doubted the
accuracy of a state audit that showed she had received $980,310 in
donations for her son's liver transplant and related medical
expenses. The donations included $1,000 from President Reagan and
$32,000 from sailors aboard the USS John F. Kennedy.
   The bill approved unanimously by the Senate Appropriations
Committee would apply to people who collect $10,000 or more in
donations. It specifies that no more than 20 percent of the
donations can be used for administrative costs and living expenses
and says unused portions should be returned to donors on a pro rata
basis.
   A first-time violation would be punishable by 60 days in jail, a
$500 fine or both. Subsequent violations are punishable by a year
in jail, a $1,000 fine or both.
   The legislation now goes to full Senate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
