<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Puppy Saved,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teacher Revives Student's Puppy Mouth-to-Mouth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAU CLAIRE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teacher used mouth-to-mouth
resuscitation Wednesday to revive a pupil's 2-week-old puppy.
   ``I haven't done that since I grew up on the farm, which was a
long time ago. About 30 years ago,'' said Alice Meyer, a
third-grade teacher at Pedersen Elementary School in Altoona.
   Meyer said she occasionally revived newborn calves on her
family's farm.
   First-grader Jessica Ellison brought her puppy to show
classmates, but when she looked in her book bag, the black,
huskie-malamute mix appeared lifeless.
   ``By the time we opened it, the little puppy was suffocated. We
thought it was dead for sure,'' Meyer said.
   Mary Ellison said she was unaware that her daughter had taken
the puppy to school until school officials called her. When she
arrived at school, the puppy had already been revived and Jessica
``didn't seem upset,'' her mother said.
   ``She was saying, `This is my pup,''' Mrs. Ellison said. ``She
was real excited about it.''
   ``The lesson for the day,'' Meyer said, ``is all living things
need air.''
