<HEAD>White House Spokesman Savors Danish Question</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Poul correct in penultimate graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater didn't
immediately react Wednesday to pending elections in Denmark, but he
did serve up a tongue-in-cheek, mealtime quip.
   When asked if the administration had any comment on new
elections being called because of a ban on visits by nuclear-armed
warships, he replied, ``Danish means breakfast to me.''
   When reporters assembled in the White House briefing room broke
up in laughter, the spokesman repeated the line.
   Then Fitzwater, his face reddening, said, ``My heart is pure on
that one, folks. Give me a break.'' He promised, ``We'll check it
out for you.''
   Last week, the Danish Parliament passed a resolution, 75-58,
requiring the government to inform visiting naval vessels of
Denmark's anti-nuclear policy. Prime Minister Poul Schlueter, who
opposed the measure, on Tuesday called an election for May 10 over
the issue.
   State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said last week that
the United States was ``deeply distressed'' by the resolution.
