<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CNWStrike     04-20 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CNW Strike,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Intervenes to Avert Chicago Rail Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan intervened Wednesday to avert
a threatened strike against the Chicago and North Western
Transportation Co. by creating an emergency board to investigate
the railroad's contract dispute with the United Transportation
Union.
   In addition to being a major freight hauler of the Chicago and
North Western provides the principal rail service for suburbanites
commuting to work in Chicago.
   Under the Railway Labor Act, the board will report to the
president in 30 days with its recommendations for settlement. The
parties are then required to try to resolve their differences
without a strike during the succeeding 30 days.
   CNW officials maintain they could realize annual savings of more
than $50 million by cutting the two brakemen from current four or
five-man crews, which also include engineers and conductors. The
union has threatened to strike Friday over the issue.
   The White House said the National Mediation Board found that the
threatened strike threatens to deprive several Midwestern states of
essential transportation services.
   The railroad employs more than 8,000 people and is the eighth
largest rail carrier in the United States as measured by revenue
generated. It handled nearly 1.5 million carloads and more than 80
million tons of traffic in 1986.
   ``In addition to its freight-handling activities, the railroad
is the major rail passenger provider for the city of Chicago,
handling approximately 40,000 passengers daily,'' the White House
announcement said.
   ``Alternatives to this commuter rail service are limited. As a
result, the Chicago area would suffer a substantial disruption of
normal business activities, in the event of a strike.''
</TEXT>
