<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     04-20 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUMPERTOWN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rural high school science students who
sent Mississippi bugs to the Soviet Union are anxiously awaiting a
return shipment of insects from the Moscow Zoo.
   Science teacher Doug Fleury said the work started after students
wanted to recognize Soviet scientific achievements and he began
corresponding with the Soviets for them. Samples of unicorn
beetles, about the size of hen eggs, and velvet ants, a type of
wingless wasp, were sent to Moscow in 1985.
   Now two kinds of giant walking sticks and a giant roach are en
route to this rural area of northeast Mississippi.
   Fleury is pleased.
   ``It's just not done _ a country school swapping bugs with a
major international zoo,'' he said recently.
   On May 2 and 3, Jumpertown High pupils, with former pupils at
Thrasher High School where the work began, will celebrate the
project.
   Brad Fugitt, 18, of Booneville, who graduated from Thrasher last
year, said he had been collecting insects for Fleury for five years
and some of his insects have been sent as far as Moscow.
   ``It kind of feels like an honor,'' he said.
   Fugitt is waiting for a response to a letter he wrote recently
to the Moscow Zoo to invite Russian scientists to participate in an
insect-collecting expedition in Mississippi in June or July.
   Fleury said he has two hopes for the bug exchanges: to send some
of the pupils to the Soviet Union with a shipment of live insects
and to bring someone from Moscow to northeast Mississippi.
   ``It's not unusual for zoo people to have a bigger view of the
world than just geographical boundaries,'' Fleury said. ``The
scientific discipline doesn't have geographical boundaries. It has
biological boundaries.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GREAT FALLS, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 275-foot river will be listed in the
1989 edition of the Guinness Book of World Records as the world's
shortest river, thanks to the efforts of fifth-graders at Lincoln
Elementary School.
   Teacher Susie Nardinger and her students received a letter
recently from Guinness officials saying their documentation had
been accepted for the Roe River, northeast of Great Falls.
   The short stretch of water flows past a fish hatchery and is
named for fish eggs.
   The Roe will replace in Guinness the 440-foot-long D River at
Lincoln City, Ore.
   Students launched their efforts in October, and the class
learned how complicated a project can become during the ensuing six
months, Nardinger said.
   ``They learned that they had to work through channels,'' she
said.
   Before Guinness editors would even consider listing it, the Roe
had to be an official river in the eyes of U.S. government
officials.
   Much of the time was spent trying to gain an official blessing
for the river from the Domestic Names Committee of the U.S. Board
on Geographic Names. The committee approved the name of Roe River
on March 10.
</TEXT>
