<2ND_LINE>AM-Sinner Background,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Finds Discrepancies In Woman's Background
^With AM-Justice Posts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman whose accusations marred John C.
Shepherd's candidacy for deputy attorney general made up nearly
every portion of her background, the St. Louis Post-Dispatch
reported Wednesday.
   Denise Sinner told investigators and employers about attending
college, having terminal cancer and performing well in past jobs.
But people interviewed by the newspaper, including Sinner's former
husband, said she had lied.
   Sinner was convicted in March of stealing nearly $147,000 from
Shepherd's St. Louis law firm while she worked there as a
bookkeeper. Sinner claimed she had had an affair with Shepherd,
that he was responsible for having hired her and that he had told
her to write checks on the firm's account for her personal use.
   Shepherd testified during the trial that all her accusations
were lies.
   The government lawyer who prosecuted Sinner's case has said she
and her lawyer never presented ``one shred of evidence'' to support
her claims.
   Shepherd said Wednesday that he was withdrawing as Attorney
General Edwin Meese's choice to fill the No. 2 spot in the Justice
Department. Shepherd cited the personal and financial toll that
intensive scrutiny had taken on him and his family.
   The Post-Dispatch said its investigation had revealed no
evidence that Shepherd had an affair with Sinner.
   Sinner has no comment on the newspaper's story and has stopped
talking to reporters, a receptionist in the law office where she
works in nearby St. Charles told The Associated Press on Wednesday.
   The Post-Dispatch said it investigated several claims Sinner,
29, had made in the course of a four-hour interview with a reporter
and found numerous discrepancies:
   _Sinner's employment history on the resume she submitted to
Shepherd, Sandberg & Phoenix listed a degree in education from the
Universitat Kaiserslautern in West Germany. But a spokesman for
that school told the newspaper that no record of Sinner's
attendance could be found. Sinner's attorney in St. Louis said he
had been told that her degree was in music from the University of
Heidelberg. Sinner's ex-husband, Michael Sinner, a supervisor at
the jail in Stearns County, Minn., said his former wife dropped out
of high school.
   _She had been fired from her last two jobs _ both times amid
allegations that she stole money from the companies.
   _She fabricated stories about having cancer. One of those
claims, which was accompanied by forged medical records, was the
reason for Sinner's conviction on a charge of making false
statements in her trial in March. Investigators have traced to a
genuine cancer patient the records she submitted as hers.
   _Michael Sinner said his ex-wife was never a music instructor
for the U.S. Army in Germany as she claimed in her resume. Sinner,
who took his wife to Germany while he was in the Army, said her
only formal music training was with ``Miss Henderson'' in
Paynesville, Minn., their hometown.
</TEXT>
