<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 1617EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-ResidentialPicketing     04-20 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Residential Picketing,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer Argues That Picketing of Private Homes Should Be Allowed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Wisconsin lawyer trying to convince the
Supreme Court that communities violate free-speech rights when they
ban picketing at private homes ran into a buzzsaw of hostile
comments Wednesday.
   ``We don't claim a right to harass,'' Steven F. McDowell of
Milwaukee said in behalf of two anti-abortion activists who want to
picket a doctor's home. But several justices seemed dubious.
   ``You want to hassle this doctor,'' Justice Antonin Scalia said.
``You want to stick your thumb in his eye. Isn't that what this is
all about?''
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justice Thurgood Marshall
repeatedly asked McDowell why his clients' freedom of speech could
not be served by picketing Dr. Benjamin Victoria's places of
business rather than his home.
   At one point, Rehnquist suggested that a ban on residential
picketing could become more acceptable if there exists ``an
opportunity to bring the message home someplace else'' such as
Victoria's offices.
   And Justice Anthony M. Kennedy pressed questions about ``a right
to a quiet street.''
   Anti-abortion activists in the spring of 1985 demonstrated in
front of Victoria's home in Brookfield, Wis., denouncing him as an
abortionist and a ``baby killer.''
   Victoria practices medicine at offices in Milwaukee and
Appleton, Wis.
   The demonstrators picketed Victoria's home on at least six
different occasions, with the groups ranging in size from 11 to
more than 40 people.
   During the month the picketing occurred, the Brookfield Town
Board enacted an ordinance outlawing ``picketing before or about
the residence or dwelling of any individual.''
   Harold H. Fuhrman of Milwaukee, the town's lawyer, told the
justices Wednesday the town council was ``appalled at this invasion
of privacy.''
   He said the ordinance was aimed only at pickets who concentrated
on one particular home, and not those who chose to parade through a
neighborhood with their messages.
   Fuhrman also said the ordinance allowed picketing in the town's
two commercial areas.
   The anti-abortion groups stopped the picketing, but two of the
demonstrators, Sandra C. Schultz and Robert L. Braun, challenged
the ordinance in court.
   A federal trial judge barred Brookfield from enforcing the
ordinance, and an evenly divided 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
upheld the judge's ruling.
   The justices' decision is expected by July.
   The case is Frisby vs. Schultz, 87-168.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880420-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 1529EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-ArmsTreaty     04-20 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arms Treaty,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Prods Senate to Ratify INF Treaty Before Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House prodded the Senate on
Wednesday to approve a nuclear-arms treaty with the Soviet Union,
saying it would be ``most unfortunate'' if the agreement is not
ratified by the time President Reagan goes to Moscow for summit
talks in late May.
   The treaty, banning all U.S. and Soviet intermediate-range
missiles, is not expected to come to the Senate floor until May 9
at the earliest, leaving only 2{ weeks for debate before Reagan
leaves for Moscow.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said ``we're very
concerned'' the treaty might not be approved in time. ``I think it
would be most unfortunate'' if that happened, he said.
   Fitzwater said ratification of the Intermediate-range Nuclear
Forces, or INF, treaty would have an effect on negotiations to curb
the deadliest class of nuclear weapons _ strategic arms.
   To have the INF treaty signed before the summit ``would be an
important boost to our negotiations'' on strategic weapons, the
spokesman said.
   ``Similarly, if it's not signed, it would tend to dampen, I
think, the prospects for serious ... progress'' on a strategic
weapons treaty, he added. ``It would not be helpful and we would
hope that the Congress would be able to ratify it before we go.''
   Even if the INF treaty is ratified, administration officials
doubt that a strategic arms agreement will be ready for signing at
the summit.
   After a three-night rest stop in Helsinki, Finland, Reagan will
arrive in Moscow on May 29 for his fourth meeting with Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The two leaders will see each on each of the five days Reagan is
in Moscow. The president also will have separate schedule of his
own.
   For example, he will hold a meeting with Soviet writers, artists
and film makers, visit a monastery and also confer with Soviet
refuseniks _ Jews denied permission to emigrate.
   White House planners expect that a highlight will be a
presidential address to Soviet students, followed by a
question-and-answer session with the audience. The event is
expected to be broadcast on live television in the United States.
   Reagan also plans to end the visit with a news conference.
   ``The INF ratification is important for what it says about the
United States' commitment to arms control and therefore helping
make progress in the START (strategic arms reduction) talks,''
Fitzwater said.
   ``All of our discussions with the Congress had indicated that
they would be able to ratify the treaty before we go to Moscow,''
Fitzwater said. ``That has been our expectation ... We still think
that is possible and we hope that the Congress will stick to that
schedule.''
   The latest snag in the ratification process is the question of
whether the treaty bans futuristic weapons such as lasers, particle
beams and other devices, as well as existing weapons.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze, in a letter to
Secretary of State George P. Shultz, said the Soviets agree with
the United States that the treaty bans futuristic weapons.
   The treaty eliminates existing missiles with a range of 300 to
3,400 miles, but some senators have questioned how the pact would
affect weapons in that range that could be developed in the future.
   Once the treaty is on the Senate floor, the agreement likely
will encounter stalling tactics from Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., and
other foes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
