<TEXT>
   Some Associated Press reports on Tuesday's New
York presidential primary carried incorrect totals for delegates
won by the Democratic candidates.
   The erroneous figures, which were unofficial calculations, had
Sen. Albert Gore Jr. winning as many as 17 delegates, Gov. Michael
Dukakis winning 152 and Jesse Jackson winning 88.
   Gore actually won two delegates, Dukakis 164 and Jackson 89,
according to a recalculation of the unofficial results.
   The error was the result of a computer problem at News Election
Service, a pool that tabulates unofficial returns for major news
organizations.
