<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Engen-DOT     04-20 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Engen-DOT,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former FAA Chief Calls DOT `Bureaucratic Nightmare'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald D. Engen, the former Federal Aviation
Administration chief, accused the Department of Transportation on
Wednesday of having a plodding rule-making process that he likened
to ``a maddening shell and pea game.''
   Engen told the Senate Commerce aviation subcommittee that while
he headed FAA, the Transportation Department sometimes added months
to the time his agency needed to implement new air safety
regulations. The FAA is a branch of the department.
   ``There were times as administrator that I viewed this as a
maddening shell and pea game effort on the part of some'' on the
transportation secretary's staff, Engen said in written testimony.
``This seemed particularly true where ... (the secretary's office)
viewed a rule as contentious or politically unpalatable despite its
validity from an aviation technical viewpoint.''
   Transportation Department officials rejected Engen's
contentions, and distributed documents that they said challenged
some of the claims he made.
   Engen left his job July 2, saying he had resigned for personal
reasons. He has declined to discuss his departure further.
   Asked Wednesday whether the complaints he aired to the
subcommittee had prompted his departure, Engen said, ``You'll have
to draw that conclusion, not me.''
   The former administrator has been critical before of the time
the Transportation Department takes to approve FAA proposals.
   But Engen's comments this time were in greater detail, and
followed by a month a scathing critique of FAA that Transportation
Secretary James H. Burnley IV delivered to the same subcommittee.
   On March 23, Burnley said that FAA is often reluctant to write
regulations that would impose additional costs on the nation's
aviation industry. He said that to spur the FAA to take safety
actions, ``it has been necessary to use the bureaucratic equivalent
of a cattle prod.''
   Engen cited one instance in which he said he blocked The Boeing
Co. from removing two of the 10 emergency exits on its 747
jetliners to add extra seats. The former administrator said he
rejected the manufacturer's request because it would have been less
safe for passengers. He also said that the Transportation
Department ``was strangely silent'' while the matter was decided.
   ``There was no waffling, no coziness between government and
industry,'' he said.
   But Transportation Department spokesman Bob Marx gave a reporter
a copy of an Aug. 6, 1985, letter from then-Transportation
Secretary Elizabeth H. Dole to Rep. Major Owens, D-N.Y., stating
that ``at my request'' Engen was pursuing the issue.
   A June 10, 1985 letter to Mrs. Dole from Henry A. Duffy,
president of the Air Line Pilots Association, expressed ``our
disappointment and concern regarding Admiral Engen's endorsement of
the overwing emergency exit deactivation on Boeing 747 aircraft.''
The letter asked Mrs. Dole to block FAA approval of the plan.
   In another instance, Engen said Boeing offered in the spring of
1985 to develop a device for training pilots to deal with wind
shear _ sudden, powerful gusts that imperil take-offs and landings.
   He said he pressed the Transportation Department to quickly
accept Boeing's $1.3 million offer, arguing that the issue needed
to be addressed as soon as possible. Using the usual bidding
process, he said, ``could consume many months, if not years.''
   He said that Transportation Department officials questioned the
contract, and the proposal was bounced between the department and
the FAA ``like a ping pong ball.'' It was not approved until
October, two months after a Delta Airlines jet crashed at
Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport because of wind shear.
   But after Engen spoke Wednesday, the Transportation Department
distributed an Aug. 20, 1985, letter to Engen from Burnley, who was
deputy transportation secretary at the time. In the memo, Burnley
objected to the proposed $2.1 million contract, arguing that it
contained excessive profit for Boeing.
   In a letter from Engen to Mrs. Dole dated Sept. 24, 1985, Engen
said the contract price had been reduced to $1.8 million.
   Engen, who took over the FAA on April 10, 1984, is now president
of the Air Safety Foundation, an organization connected to the
Aircraft Owners and Pilots Association. The association represents
owners and pilots of private planes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
