<DOCNO> AP880420-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 1623EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Shultz     04-20 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Criticizes Safe Passage For Hijackers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz
said Wednesday that it was wrong to allow the hijackers of a
Kuwaiti jetliner to get away.
   The Algerian government negotiated the release Wednesday of 31
hostages, ending the 16-day ordeal in which two Kuwaiti passengers
were slain. The whereabouts of the gunmen was not known.
   ``They are not only hijackers but murderers,'' Shultz told a
news conference during a stopover on a trip to Moscow for
pre-summit talks.
   Asked if the hijackers should have been allowed to go free,
Shultz said: ``No, I don't think that's a proper thing to do.''
   Kuwait thanked Algeria for mediating. In the past, the United
States also expressed gratitude to governments that assisted in
ending hostage-takings but Shultz pointedly did not.
   And yet, Shultz indicated the United States might not have legal
rights to pursue the hijackers, who demanded the release of 17
prisoners held in Kuwait in an assault on the U.S. and French
embassies in the Persian Gulf country.
   Only one of the passengers might have held U.S. citizenship,
which would give the Justice Department a possible course of
action. But Shultz said he did not know if the passenger's dual
nationality had been ``pinned down.''
   Extradition also might be possible if reports are confirmed that
one of the gunmen was involved in the hijacking of a TWA jetliner
in 1985 in which one of the passengers, a U.S. Navy diver, was
killed.
   ``Don't misunderstand me,'' Shultz said. ``I`m not
second-guessing the Algerian government. What I'm saying is these
people were hijackers ... and clearly murderers. From the
standpoint of the international community we don't like to see
hijackers go off free.''
   Shultz stopped in Helsinki on his way to Moscow to resume
preparations for the May 29-June 2 summit meeting in the Soviet
capital, where he is to hold talks with Mikhail S. Gorbachev and
Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   On Shultz's agenda are the Iran-Iraq war, which threatens
shipping in the Persian Gulf, and U.S.-Soviet negotiations to
conclude a treaty to cut strategic nuclear weapons arsenals as much
as 50 percent.
   Shultz said he will again appeal to the Soviets to help get the
United Nations Security Council to impose an arms embargo against
Iran.
   On arms control, Shultz said ``we'll keep working for a good
agreement,'' But he said it would be hard to accomplish in time for
a summit signing by Gorbachev and President Reagan.
   U.S. and Soviet drafts of the accord have 1,200 distinct points
of disagreement with the summit meeting only five weeks away. About
half are technical, but the others touch on the difficult problem
of verifying weapons reductions are carried out.
</TEXT>
