<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StealthSecrets     04-20 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stealth Secrets,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Magazine Defends Stealth Article</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN L. HERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Editors of an engineering magazine
Wednesday defended publication of an article containing details of
stealth aviation research against criticism, including a caller who
said the writer ``should be shot.''
   The article, ``How to design an `invisible' aircraft,'' appears
in this month's edition of IEEE Spectrum, published by The
Institute of Electrical and Electronic Engineers.
   Pentagon officials requested copies of the magazine after the
article was published, institute officials said. However, the
Defense Department would not comment publicly.
   ``It's DOD policy not to comment on whether published
information is classified,'' said Pentagon spokeswoman Jan Bodanyi.
   Still, according to the magazine's editors, military officials
were disturbed.
   ``We've had a few DOD calls saying the person who wrote this
should be shot,'' said West Coast field editor Tekla Perry in Palo
Alto, Calif.
   The magazine article says dozens of delta-shaped Stealth
fighters, built by Lockheed Aeronautical Systems Co. in Burbank,
Calif., are being flown by pilots of the elite 4450th Tactical
Group at Nevada's Nellis Air Force Base, one of the nation's most
classified military reservations.
   The article, which says that ``stealth techniques are some of
the best-kept secrets in the government,'' goes on to detail the
latest research.
   Some of the secrecy around the Stealth bomber, known as the B-2,
was dropped Wednesday when the Air Force released a picture of that
new craft and announced it would make its maiden flight this fall.
   Executive Editor Edward A. Torrero said Wednesday that the
magazine ``absolutely'' would not have deliberately published
anything that it was told was classified.
   ``We're not in the business to publish classified information,''
he said. ``Nothing was not obtained from open literature and
sources that were knowledgeable about security requirements.''
   A reported goal of the stealth project is to make a fighter
plane's head-on radar signature resemble that of a bird, according
to the technical journal.
   Research to accomplish that is being conducted at many sites,
including Ohio State University, the University of Pennsylvania and
Georgia Tech, according to the magazine article.
   Ohio State is building computer simulation models of stealth
aircraft to fine-tune the shape of planes to make them as invisible
to radar as possible.
   Commercial airline passengers who fly into Philadelphia
International Airport are unknowingly contributing to stealth
research, the article said.
   The University of Pennsylvania's Valley Forge Research Center
has set up a large radar array that creates two-dimensional images
of planes flying into the airport, according to the journal.
   ``As they come in, we just use them as targets,'' research
center technician Walter Borders told The Associated Press on
Wednesday.
   Researchers at Georgia Tech are using U.S. intelligence data to
build and test sensors for detecting stealth-modified aircraft, the
magazine said. The sensors are then delivered to the government,
according to the magazine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
