<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MissingCopter     04-20 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missing Copter,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Probing Radio Clallenge Before Copter Vanished</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon said Wednesday it had called off
the search for a Marine helicopter and its two crewmen missing in
the Persian Gulf and disclosed it was investigating a radio
challenge to the aircraft heard before it disappeared.
   Iran has claimed it shot down the missing helicopter on Monday
as Iranian and U.S. forces clashed in the gulf. With the exception
of the two missing Marines, no Americans were injured or killed in
those battles.
   Dan Howard, the Defense Department's chief spokesman, responded
to the Iranian statements Tuesday by noting Iran didn't begin
making the claim until after the Pentagon itself announced the
Cobra was overdue from a routine surveillance mission.
   In a written statement Wednesday, the Pentagon said:
   ``The Joint Task Force Middle East continues to review the
events surrounding the disappearance of the AH-1T Cobra helicopter
in the Persian Gulf. Our analysis to date reveals that an unknown
party was heard challenging an ``American aircraft'' about the time
of the last transmission from the missing Cobra.
   ``However, there have been no reports of weapons fire or
explosions in the area in which the aircraft was last known to be
operating. There is no positive evidence at this time to determine
the cause of the helicopter's disappearance.''
   A Pentagon source who requested anonymity said the cruiser USS
Wainwright _ from which the copter departed on its patrol _ had
picked up three different radio calls _ or challenges _ to the
Cobra in quick succession.
   ``The calls advised an American aircraft to reverse course
because it wasn't in international waters,'' said the source. ``Of
course, both the Wainwright and the copter were in international
waters, so who knows what was going on?''
   The Wainwright was one of three ships that attacked the Sirri
oil platform in the southern Persian Gulf on Monday morning. U.S.
forces destroyed the Sirri platform and another one in retaliation
for last week's mining of the frigate Samuel B. Roberts, which
injured 10 sailors.
   The decision to call off the search operation for the missing
men was first announced Wednesday at the White House by spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater.
   ``The search and rescue effort was terminated ... with negative
results,'' Fitzwater said. ``The pilot and copilot have been
declared missing.''
   The missing crewmen were identified as Capt. Stephen C. Leslie,
30, and Capt. Kenneth W. Hill, 33, assigned to Squadron HMLA-167
based at the New River, N.C., Marine Corps Air Station.
</TEXT>
