^By GUY DARST</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Preliminary results from new tests show that a
controversial chemical used to regulate the growth of apples does
cause tumors in mice, the Environmental Protection Agency has told
apple growers.
   But EPA says it does not yet have enough information for a
decision on what to do. The manufacturer, Uniroyal Chemical Co. of
Middlebury, Conn., has told the growers it remains confident that
the chemical, sold under the trade name Alar, eventually will be
cleared.
   EPA could announce a decision as early as this fall on whether
tr, which has the scientific name daminozide, wroo ban use of Alate
EPA Assistant Administrator John A. Moore to the International
Apple Institute.
   The agency began studying daminozide in 1980 and proposed to ban
it in 1985, but decided to order new studies when its own
scientific advisers said it had not proved its case. It did lower
the permissible residues in apples and the amount that may be used
in orchards.
   Daminozide had been used on about 40 percent of the nation's
apple crop. Applied in the summer, it slows growth, the state-run Banca
Commerciale _
Italy's second largest bank _ would pay $75 a share for 8.5 million
shares, or 45 percent of Irving's outstanding common stock. Banca
Commerciale also would have the right to buy an additional 10
percent of Irving stock on the open market after the deal was
consummated.
   The original bid, announced along with the restructuring plan
Monday, was for $65 a share for 9.5 million shares, or 51 percent.
   The new plan, like the original, gives the Italian bank four
seats on the Irving board.
   Bank of New York, meanwhile, is offering $15 in cash and 1.575
of its common shares for the approximately 95 percent of Irving it
doesn't already own. The tender offer, set to expire Friday, began
last month after regulatory approval.
   Bank of New York also is running a slate of 16 nominees to
Irving's board of directors.
   Irving Chairman Joseph A. Rice said Banca Commerciale's offer
would provide shareholders with ``substantially more value than the
offer by the Bank of New York Co., and we urge our shareholders to
reject the BNY offer'' at Saturday's annual shareholders' meeting.
   Irving said it believes the Banca Commerciale deal would have an
indicated per-share value of between $64 and $72.25, figures Bank
of New York has disputed.
   Bank of New York and a number of analysts say Bank of New York's
offer of about $64 a share appeared better partly because of the
timing and regulatory reasons. The reason why Banca Commerciale
revised its offer in the first place was because ``they had a
loser,'' said H. Rodgin Cohen, an attorney for Bank of New York.
   Analysts have differed in their characterizations of Banca
Commerciale, some calling it a friendly ``white knight'' that would
help Irving preserve its independence, with others labeling it a
``white serf'' that pales in comparison to the hostile bidder, Bank
of New York.
   ``I think they (Irving shareholders) will vote for the Bank of
New York offer,'' said James J. McDermott, a banking analyst with
Keefe, Bruyette & Woods. ``The sophisticated investor is going to
see the time value.''
   In a separate news conference, Bank of New York pointed out that
not only will the Irving-Banca Commerciale deal need approval from
the Federal Reserve and the New York State Banking Board but also
the go-ahead from Italian regulators. And that, it said, could take
more than a year to achieve.
   Bank of New York Chairman J. Carter Bacot also questioned
whether Banca Commerciale had the necessary capital requirements to
win regulatory approval. To win the support of shareholders, Irving
also has proposed in its restructuring plan to raise net income by
about $1.60 a share in 1988 and $2.75 next year through
cost-cutting measures that include a hiring freeze.
   Irving reported a $193.27 million loss in 1987 after raising by
$450 million its loan-loss reserves to cover shaky Third World debt.
   The restructuring plan includes the sale of some assets, such as
its 50-story Wall Street headquarters and Irving's 39 percent stake
in the Swiss bank Banca della Svizzera. Irving said it planned to
pay a $10-a-share special cash dividend from the gains on the asset
sales.
   In addition, Irving proposed boosting its annual dividend to
$4.50 a share from $2.42 next month, but the Fed has objected to an
increase to that level, leaving that portion of the plan in doubt.
   Bank of New York maintained that with the loss of the dividend
the Banca-Commerciale deal was worth less.
   Of the revised deal, Cohen said, ``They gave on the front end
and took away on the back; it's that simple.''
   Banca Commerciale, based in Milan, has assets of around $60
bilion and is Italy's second largest bank, behind Banca Nazionale
del Lavoro. About 64 percent of Banca Commerciale is owned by the
giant state holding company Istituto per la Ricostruzione
Industriale.
   Irving's assets total about $24 billion.
