<1ST_LINE>u i AM-PLO-Funeral 1stLd-Writethru a0771 04-20 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO-Funeral, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0771,0762</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Military Chief Buried in Syria's Largest Refugee Camp</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDS: CORRECTS spelling to Wazir throughout, dropping al- to
conform with AP style</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of thousands of mourners
followed a gun carriage carrying the flag-draped coffin of a slain
PLO military commander Wednesday, and they vowed that his martyrdom
would fuel the fight with Israel.
   ``In blood, in soul, we shall be loyal to our martyr!'' they
shouted at the funeral for Khalil Wazir, better known by his alias,
Abu Jihad.
   The 52-year-old veteran of the Palestine Liberation Organization
was assassinated Saturday by commandos who burst into his home in
suburban Tunis.
   The Tunisian government and Israeli sources have said Israel
carried out the attack, but the Israeli government has not
confirmed it.
   Wazir was buried in the Martyrs Cemetery at Syria's largest
refugee camp after his coffin was brought from Mouwasat Hospital.
   His mother, wife and five children followed as the coffin,
draped in a red, white, green and black Palestinian flag, was
brought to Yarmouk camp, home to 300,000 refugees.
   Palestinian officials said PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat and Libyan
leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi were on their way to Damascus to attend
the funeral, but they did not show up. The officials said they
expected Arafat and Gadhafi to arrive later, but did not elaborate.
   Hundreds of thousands of Palestinians, many carrying large
photographs of al-Wazir, marched behind the gun carriage as it left
the hospital under heavy Syrian protection for the seven-mile
journey to Yarmouk.
   ``We shall carry on with the uprising as you told us,'' read
placards referring to 4{ months of Palestinian riots against
Israel's occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Thousands of other mourners, chanting slogans and flashing ``V''
for victory, stood on both sides of the road as the convoy drove
through Damascus. Others watched from balconies and rooftops and
showered the procession with flowers.
   When the mourners reached the camp south of Damascus, a group of
mourners rushed to the gun carriage, lifted the coffin out and
insisted on carrying it to the cemetery.
   Women in black dresses and scarves emblazoned with the
Palestinian flag wept.
   Syrian soldiers fired about 60 rounds into the air from
Soviet-made Kalashnikov assault rifles as the coffin was lowered
into the grave.
   Wazir, born in Ramleh in what is now Israel, became a key aide
to Arafat and was considered his heir apparent.
   A close aide to al-Wazir, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said he was the leader of the Palestinian uprising in the occupied
territories.
   ``The loss of our great hero Abu Jihad will not put an end to
the uprising. Abu Jihad left a school behind,'' the aide said in an
interview.
   ``Abu Jihad had been recruiting young men and women since the
PLO left Beirut in the 1982 Israeli invasion. These cadres have
been tried out in several operations, where they proved to be
capable inside and outside Palestine.''
   Among the PLO personalities who attended the funeral were George
Habash, leader of the Marxist Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine, and Nayef Hawatmeh, secretary-general of the
Moscow-oriented Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine.
   Arafat has been at odds with Syrian President Hafez Assad since
1983, and if he came to the Syrian capital, it would be at a time
when Arab leaders are seeking to reconcile them.
   The PLO chairman had not been expected to attend the Wazir's
funeral because of the feud with Assad.
   Gadhafi, who only recently reconciled with Arafat after a split,
is a close ally of Assad, who did not attend the funeral.
   Wazir's body arrived in Syria from Tunisia on Tuesday aboard a
PLO-chartered plane.
   At the United Nations, Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
said in a statement that he is ``very concerned at what appears to
be evidence of a further infringement by Israel of the sovereignty
and territorial integrity of Tunisia.''
   He recalled the October 1985 Security Council vote condemning
Israel for an air raid on a Tunis suburb. Israel said it was
striking at a PLO target.
   The United States abstained on the 1985 resolution instead of
using its veto to protect Israel as it usually does.
   Foreign Minister Mahmoud Mestiri will present evidence to the
Security Council on Thursday that Israeli commandos gunned down
Wazir, said Nouredine Kacem, first secretary at the Tunisian
mission.
</TEXT>
