<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd_Writethru a0756 04-20 0870</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld _ Writethru, a0756,0888</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinians Barred Entry to Israel, One Arab Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV2</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 2 grafs to CORRECT last name to Wazir, dropping
al- to conform with style; picks up 4th graf pvs, ``At least ...;
Also SUBS 17th `At Beit' and 20th `In the' to CORRECT Wazir; SUBS
12th `Israel's Memorial' to CORRECT period covered by Memorial Day,
which ended at sundown Wednesday</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israelis honored their independence and war
dead Wednesday, but it was another day of street battles in the
occupied lands, where soldiers shot one Arab to death and wounded
10.
   Arabs hung black banners and held mock funerals for PLO military
commander Khalil Wazir, who was assassinated last week at his home
in Tunis and buried Wednesday in Damascus, Syria.
   At least 169 Palestinians have been killed since riots began
Dec. 8 in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, which Israel has occupied
since capturing them from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East
war. An Israeli soldier and civilian also have been slain.
   All 1.5 million Palestinians in the territories were barred from
Israel for the rest of this week as a security measure during the
nation's 40th anniversary celebration.
   Hadashot, an Israeli daily newspaper, said an investigation by
the military found 240 Arab women in Gaza had miscarried during
more than four months of rebellion.
   It said as many as half the miscarriages were caused by tear gas
inhalation. The army said it would not comment immediately.
   Army spokesmen said a new prison had been established north of
Jerusalem to hold some of the 5,000 Palestinians reported arrested.
It was the fifth new prison set up since December, according to Law
in the Service of Man, a human rights organization of Palestinian
lawyers.
   Curfews were in effect for the fourth day on 17 refugee camps
and towns in the West Bank and six of eight refugee camps in Gaza,
affecting more than 400,000 Arabs. Army roadblocks barred
journalists from some parts of the occupied lands.
   The longest curfew is at the Jelazoun camp near Ramallah in the
West Bank, under restrictions for 34 days.
   Even U.N. relief officials had been barred from delivering food
to the 5,000 residents, but three trucks were allowed in Tuesday
with sardines, corned beef, beans, cooking oil, powdered milk and
rice, said Bill Lee of the U.N. Relief and Works Agency, which
serves Palestinian refugees.
   Israel's Memorial Day, on which the nation honors the 16,450
soldiers killed in seven wars and in clashes with Arab guerrillas,
ran from sundown Tuesday until sundown Wednesday, followed by the
24-hour Independence Day celebration.
   Mourning and celebration are coupled each year ``so that our
children are aware of the sacrifice that went behind the joy of our
independence,'' teacher Ruth Dafnai told a reporter as her sixth
graders put flowers on graves at the Mount Herzl cemetery in
Jerusalem.
   Israeli poets withdrew their support of an international poetry
festival for the 40th anniversary, as a protest of government
policy in the occupied lands, and organizers said they were
canceling it.
   ``Our conscience did not allow us to invite other poets to take
part in a government-sponsored festival,'' said Natan Zach, a
leader in modern Hebrew poetry.
   Allen Ginsberg of the United States, Guenter Grass of West
Germany and Yevgeny Yevtushenko of the Soviet Union had beem
expected to attend the festival in June.
   At Beit Sahur near Bethlehem, about 350 mourners of Wazir waved
black banners and carried a wooden coffin draped with the outlawed
Palestinian flag from the Greek Orthodox church into the center of
town.
   A Tunisian government report said the Palestine Liberation
Organization leader was killed by Israeli commandos. Israeli
sources confirmed it but the government has not acknowledged
responsibility.
   Mourners walked silently as church bells rang, then five
jeeploads of Israeli soldiers fired tear gas to disperse the crowd,
said an Associated Press reporter at the scene. Another mock
funeral was held in Ramallah, north of Jerusalem.
   In the Gaza Strip, where Wazir grew up, pictures of him were
posted on walls and Palestinian flags and black banners hung from
power lines. Shops were closed in a protest strike.
   Soldiers opened fire on stone-throwing Arabs in Gaza's Nusseirat
refugee camp, the army said. Hospital officials reported one Arab
killed and seven wounded.
   Mohammed Hassan Massar, 21, died of a bullet wound to the chest
and another 21-year-old was in serious condition with a leg wound,
said Ilana Ziv of Barzilai Hospital in Israel.
   Two Arabs tried to seize a soldier's gun at Anabta, 10 miles
north of Nablus in the West Bank, and members of the patrol opened
fire, wounding one Arab in the right thigh and the second in the
left arm, Israel radio and hospital officials reported.
   Officials at Jenin hospital said an Arab was wounded in the left
leg at Tubas, an Arab village 15 miles north of Nablus.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said the army might fine parents
of children under 12 who throw firebombs and rocks, according to
Hadashot. ``This is the best way to confront violence among
children in the territories,'' it quoted him as saying.
</TEXT>
