<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SEC-ProgramTrading     04-20 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SEC-Program Trading,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SEC Adopts Six-Month Experiment To Limit Trading During Volatile
Periods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission on
Wednesday approved a six-month experiment limiting program trading
on the New York Stock Exchange on days when the market takes a big
swing either up or down.
   The SEC ordered that use of the exchange's computerized SuperDOT
system be suspended for the practice called ``index arbitrage''
when the Dow Jones Industrial Average rises or falls by 50 points.
   Traders use index arbitrage to make money by taking advantage of
momentary price discrepancies between stock index futures and the
underlying stocks. They transmit massive buy and sell orders to the
Chicago futures exchanges or the New York stock exchanges,
depending on whether stocks or stock futures appear undervalued.
   Under normal circumstances, this trading ensures that the two
markets track each other, but an SEC study of the October stock
market crash, when the Dow fell a record 508 points, found that
index arbitrage accelerated the crash. It found that when the
market is surging up or down program trading can overwhelm the
stock and futures exchanges.
   The six-month restriction of index arbitrage, which the Big
Board has been observing voluntarily since Jan. 14, is intended to
dampen the market on its most volatile days.
   The SEC, in a written statement, said it was reserving the right
to remove the restriction ``whenever such a waiver appears
justified to foster or maintain the efficiency, fairness or
orderliness of the market.''
   It said program trading serves a useful purpose and that, in
general, the agency's primary focus is on expanding market capacity
to handle high volumes of trading.
   But, the statement said, ``in light of the uncertain market
environment and the need to increase investor confidence in the
stability of the markets, it is appropriate for the exchanges to
develop experimental initiatives.''
   The SEC said it expects the stock exchange to report back on the
effectiveness of the restrictions before the six-month trial ends.
   Meanwhile, John Phelan, the chairman of the New York Stock
Exchange, and Leo Melamed, the chairman of the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, the largest financial futures exchange, have been
discussing a plan to coordinate closing the markets completely on
days when the Dow swings 200 to 300 points.
   They told a House subcommittee last week that they expect to
reach agreement on the plan within 30 days.
</TEXT>
