<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--DairyOutlook     04-20 0141</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Dairy Outlook,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Milk Production May Hit Another Record This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Milk production may climb 2 percent to 3
percent this year after edging lower in 1987, the Agriculture
Department said Wednesday.
   The increase will reflect ``stable cow numbers and increasing
output per cow,'' the department's Economic Research Service said
in an outlook report.
   Milk production dropped 1 percent last year to 142.5 billion
pounds from a record of 144.1 billion pounds in 1986. The new
forecast means 1988 production could surpass the old record.
   ``Generally favorable price and income conditions may raise
commercial use (of milk) as much as 2 perent from a year earlier,''
the report said. ``Net removals (purchases of surplus) under the
price support program are expected to total 7 billion to 9 billion
pounds, milk equivalent, up from 6.7 billion in 1987.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880420-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 1736EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Koch Bjt   04-20 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Koch, Bjt,0702</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>For Koch, Primary Sets Stage for Next Year's Re-Election Bid</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY21</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch campaigned like a candidate
in the New York Democratic primary _ and lost. Some say the effort
may have damaged his ambitions to become the city's first four-term
mayor.
   ``I have to work a little harder,'' Koch conceded Wednesday as
he looked back at the previous day's voting and ahead to his 1989
re-election campaign. He admitted he may be vulnerable.
   Koch had worked hard on behalf of Sen. Al Gore Jr. of Tennessee,
but Gore's poor showing _ 10 percent statewide, 9 percent in New
York City _ raised the question of whether the mayor had done more
harm than good.
   Beyond that, Koch's stinging attacks on the Rev. Jesse Jackson
left many observers wondering if he had finally severed the last
frayed cords between himself and New York's large black community.
   Jackson lost the state but carried New York City, a performance
that raised the hopes of some black political figures who have been
frustrated in the past by their inability to elect a black mayor.
   ``There will be a black candidate against Ed Koch in '89,'' the
Rev. Al Sharpton said at a news conference with other black
political activists Wednesday.
   The group suggested several possibilities, including Manhattan
Borough President David Dinkins, former Borough President Percy
Sutton, attorney Alton Maddox Jr. and Sharpton himself.
   Dinkins, the city's highest elected black official, said at a
separate news conference that he had no plan to run for mayor.
However, he agreed that the events of the primary would have ``an
adverse impact'' on Koch's re-election chances.
   Others, such as Democratic Party activist Mark Green, used
stronger words. ``Ed Koch has to worry that he's lit a long fuse
that could go off in his face in '89,'' Green told The New York
Times.
   Exit polls indicated that voters disagreed by nearly 2-to-1 with
Koch's attacks on Jackson and by a margin of 3-to-2 did not want
him to run for re-election.
   Koch, as always, was unrepentant.
   ``Did I hurt myself with people who voted for Jesse Jackson? The
answer is yes,'' he said. ``Did I do the right thing in raising
these issues? I think the answer is yes.''
   While campaigning for Gore, Koch criticized Jackson over his
policies toward Israel, saying Jews would be ``crazy'' to vote for
Jackson and calling him arrogant for failing to march in a Salute
to Israel Parade.
   Koch said, however, that he would endorse Jackson if the civil
rights leader won the Democratic nomination, but only because he
believed Vice President George Bush had the ability to cause more
harm.
   His remarks have drawn criticism from around the city and the
nation. New York Daily News columnist Jimmy Breslin said Wednesday
that Koch ``tried to disgrace an entire city.'' Rep. John Conyers,
D-Mich., said Koch ``has made it very difficult for those that are
trying to heal race differences.''
   Gov. Mario Cuomo, who is among those who have run against Koch
for mayor and lost, agreed that many voters found Koch's behavior
in the presidential primary ``unseemly.'' But Cuomo suggested that
they probably would forget it by next year.
   In the past, Koch's messy involvements in national politics have
done little to damage his local popularity.
   ``You have done me more damage than any other man in America,''
former President Jimmy Carter is said to have told him in 1980,
after the mayor endorsed Carter, then criticized his Mideast
policies. Koch, in a refrain familiar to New Yorkers, later said he
was only being honest.
   His candor has charmed, amused and impressed many New Yorkers
over the years, but others, blacks in particular, have found the
mayor lacking in diplomacy, tact and sensitivity.
   ``Leadership has an obligation to set the moral tone, it has an
obligation to expand and build a coalition, to relieve people of
their fears and insecurities,'' Jackson said Wednesday, speaking of
Koch. The mayor, he implied, was doing none of that.
</TEXT>
