<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Honduras-Nicaragua     04-20 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-Nicaragua,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduras OKs Delivery of U.S. Humanitarian Aid to Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will allow Honduran
territory to be used for the delivery of U.S. humanitarian aid to
the Nicaraguan rebels, the Foreign Ministry said Wednesday.
   In another development, Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega said
in Managua that the United States was violating a cease-fire accord
between his government and the guerrillas by providing humanitarian
aid.
   The Honduran government said its decision on aid for the rebels
was made by President Jose Azcona Hoyo after Nicaragua's leftist
Sandinista government and the U.S.-backed Contras agreed to the
60-day cease-fire starting April 1.
   Even though the Nicaraguan rebels have used Honduras a staging
area in their 6{-year-old war, the Honduran government has not said
it supports them.
   Few details of the aid operations were made public Wednesday.
Officials said the U.S. Agency for International Development, the
U.S. Embassy, the Roman Catholic Church and the private American
accounting firm Price Waterhouse will supervise the delivery of the
U.S. aid.
   The Honduran statement said the regional peace plan signed last
August by the presidents of Honduras, Nicaragua, Guatemala, El
Salvador and Costa Rica allows delivery of humanitarian aid.
   Ortega said the American government is already delivering
humanitarian help to the Contras in violation of the cease-fire
agreement.
   The Nicaraguan president, speaking at a regional meeting of
agriculture ministers, said the pact provides ``that the aid must
be delivered once a method of operation is agreed upon.''
   The cease-fire forged at meetings in Sapoa on Nicaragua's
southern border calls for rebel fighters to gather in seven zones
inside Nicaragua.
   It allows humanitarian aid to be distributed to the rebels by a
neutral organization once they have gathered in the zones.
   The cease-fire accord also obliges the two sides to discuss a
permanent truce.
   The Sandinistas and Contras met for the first time in Managua
last the weekend but failed to conclude any broader peace
agreement. They are to resume talks on April 28.
   The U.S. Congress has approved a $48 million package providing
humanitarian aid for the Contras and wounded children on both
sides. The package includes $10 million for independent
verification of the cease-fire.
   The Contras received CIA-operated air drops of both military and
other aid in a program that ended Feb. 29.
   President Reagan ordered 3,200 U.S. troops to Honduras last
month after receiving reports that up to 2,000 Sandinista soldiers
crossed the border in pursuit of Contras. The American soldiers
were airlifted home after training exercises.
</TEXT>
