<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 1750EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-OSHAHearings     04-20 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OSHA Hearings,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OSHA Chief Defends Agency Against Questions About Safety</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration on Wednesday vehemently denied a Senate committee
chairman's charge that the agency has been on a ``retreat from
safety'' under the Reagan administration.
   ``There has not been,'' OSHA Administrator John Pendergrass said
in reponse to the accusation from Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.
``I would never for a moment have taken this position if there had
ever been any hint that there would be a retreat from safety.''
   Pendergrass, his assistant, Frank White, and Assistant Labor
Secretary Michael Baroody sought Wednesday to counter two days of
previous testimony from career officials in the agency about delays
in issuing new regulations and efforts by some in the
administration to weaken existing ones.
   Kennedy, who chairs the Senate Labor and Human Resourcs
Committee, attempted during the committee's hearings to link some
of those efforts to Vice President George Bush, claiming the record
shows that ``Bush has personally supervised and pushed the effort
to roll back health protection for workers.''
   While a Bush-chaired regulatory task force called for some of
the rollbacks in 1981 and has monitored what has been done since
then, the link to Bush did not extend beyond circumstantial
evidence. However, the testimony did show that Baroody and the
White House Office of Management and Budget played significant
roles in attempting to carry out some of the task force's
recommendations.
   Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah, the ranking Republican on the
comittee, called the hearings ``unfair'' and suggested that Kennedy
should hold another round in the next month and call OMB officials
as witnesses.
   Baroody, meanwhile, testified that the agency in the last three
years has issued 20 new job health and safety regulations compared
with just 27 such rules in the previous 14 years.
   But he agreed with earlier testimony from agency critics who
said the pace is too slow.
   ``None of us wants to look back 19 years from now (and see) no
more than another 47 rules, especially if those rules cover no more
than an additional 47 individual health and safety threats,'' he
said. ``Many of us don't think more of the same is or has to be the
only choice for OSHA.''
   Pendergrass cited figures showing that occupational injury rates
have declined by more than 25 percent and injury rates by 40
percent since 1973.
   ``Those figures are completely distorted, inaccurate and don't
represent what's going on in the workplace,'' Kennedy said, citing
testimony from National Academy of Science experts about problems
with OSHA's statistics.
   Pendergrass acknowledged there are problems with the agency's
numbers, but said they still offer a fair representation of the
improvements that have occurred.
   A 22-page report by the Congressional Research Service citing
information from the National Safety Council bolstered the claim
that the agency has somewhat succeeded in reducing fatalities, at
least in the hazardous construction industry.
   The unpublished report said OSHA now is reaching only 11 percent
of the nation's workers with routinely scheduled inspections
instead of the 78 percent intended when Congress created the agency
in 1970.
   But it said all but 2 percentage points of that reduction was
ordered by Congress, the Supreme Court or the Carter administration
before President Reagan took office in 1981.
   ``By increments, Congress and OSHA, with some help from the
Supreme Court, have done this by ultimately excluding from OSHA's
target list essentially all workers except those in construction,
oil and gas extraction, maritime operations and high-hazard
manufacturing,'' the report said.
   The report was requested by the Senate commitee but did not come
up during the hearings. A copy was obtained by The Associated Press.
   ``OSHA's relative success in reducing injury and fatality rates
in the construction industry suggests that OSHA is getting some
positive effects from concentrating its limited resources,'' the
report said.
   As a result of the attention on construction, Pendergrass
acknowledged that the length of time between routine inspections _
those that are not in response to a specific complaint _ of
facilities in other industries is often lengthy.
   For example, in a high-hazard industry like meatpacking, he
said, each plant is routinely inspected only about once every three
years. Kennedy said that frequency of inspections is woefully
inadequate.
</TEXT>
