<1ST_LINE>r p AM-SuperDelegates     04-20 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Super Delegates,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Picks Up Congressional ``Super Delegates''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for story listed as AM-Congressional Caucus on the
digest</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis' victory in the New York
primary appeared to nudge a handful of congressional Democrats onto
his campaign bandwagon Wednesday as the House decided on its
``super delegates'' to the national convention.
   Thirtyeight of the 207 House members approved at a closed-door
meeting said they were backing Dukakis for the party's presidential
nomination. The Massachusetts governor gained the support of 12
delegates from the time the House nominated its delegate slate of
205 last week and gave final approval to 207 House members on
Wednesday.
   Jesse Jackson had the backing of 15 House members, and Tennessee
Sen. Albert Gore Jr., picked up 12. Illinois Sen. Paul Simon, who
has suspended his campaign, gained 10 House members.
   There were 132 uncommitted.
   On Tuesday, Democrats in the Senate held a ceremonial vote to
pick their 43 national convention delegates, with Dukakis garnering
the support of 13 senators and Gore getting seven, including
himself.
   Simon managed to win only one seat for himself and the backing
of fellow Illinois Sen. Alan Dixon. Twenty-one senator-delegates
remain uncommitted.
   The 250 congressional delegates will be among 643 super
delegates to attend the convention in Atlanta, July 18-21. These
delegates, who include governors, members of the Democratic
National Committee and other party leaders, receive their
convention credentials based on offices they hold or formerly held.
   Only New York's primary and California's on June 7 offer more
delegates than the behind-the-scenes ``primary'' on Capitol Hill.
   The candidates, battling for the 2,081 delegates needed to
nominate, have approached the large bloc of super delegates with
personal phone calls and extensive mailings.
   The Dukakis campaign, which has a well-organized network for
communicating with super delegates, has not changed its approach
despite the victory in New York, a spokeswoman said.
   ``We're not doing anything any differently today than we did two
weeks ago,'' said Susan Brophy, who handles delegate selection for
the campaign.
   ``I don't see a deluge,'' Ms. Brophy said, hours after the New
York win. However, she added that ``members of Congress seem to be
moving a little more quickly than DNC members.''
   Dukakis remains the front-runner in The Associated Press count
of super delegates with 117.65. Gore is second with 47.55, Jackson
third with 45.1 and Simon fourth with 28.5. The others are
uncommitted.
</TEXT>
