<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Israel     04-20 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Israel,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Killed When Israel-Backed Militia Attacks Guerrillas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli-backed militiamen ambushed
pro-Iranian guerrillas in south Lebanon Wednesday, and police said
four combatants were killed.
   A police spokesman said militiamen of the South Lebanon Army
fired on six guerrillas of the Islamic Resistance as they prepared
to launch an attack south of Jezzine, a town controlled by the
Israeli-supported militia.
   The spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said three
guerrillas and a militiaman were killed in the 20-minute firefight.
   South Lebanon Army gunners later pounded the Bekaa Valley towns
of Mashgara and Ein el-Tineh, east of Jezzine, with 155mm howitzers
to prevent the Islamic Resistance from reinforcing the men who were
ambushed.
   The Islamic Resistance movement is dominated by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   Hezbollah, made up of Shiites loyal to Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, is believed to be an umbrella for factions holding most
of the 22 foreigners missing in Lebanon.
   Hezbollah is active in the Syrian-policed Bekaa Valley and
Beirut's southern slums but was crushed in south Lebanon this month
by its main Shiite rival, the Amal militia led by Justice Minister
Nabih Berri.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, has 25,000 troops in
the Bekaa and north Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping
mandate.
   It also deployed 7,500 troops in Moslem west Beirut in February
1987 in an effort to end militia warfare.
</TEXT>
