<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PizzaDrugs     04-20 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pizza Drugs,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Dealers Forcing Pizza Shop Out Of Business</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By T.J. SIMONEAUX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Charles Town pizza parlor owner whose
restaurant became a hangout for drug dealers said Wednesday he's
been ordered to vacate his building, even though he asked police to
help drive the traffickers out.
   John Mao on Wednesday said he's been unfairly singled out
because drug dealers, rousted by a police crackdown one block away,
moved into his Frank's Pizza restaurant. His landlord has given him
until May 31 to move out.
   Charles Town city officials say they also may order Mao to close
his pizza parlor once a circuit judge backs an April 12 city
council resolution allowing them to shut down businesses that
create a public nuisance _ namely those that harbor drug dealers.
   ``They're just using me as a scapegoat,'' Mao said Wednesday.
``It makes me angry. I went down there to the police to ask for
help. Why are they doing this?''
   Frank's Pizza, which the 30-year-old Hong Kong native bought in
1980, is located in Hilldale Shopping Plaza in Charles Town, a town
of 2,800 in extreme eastern West Virginia. When police began
stepping up patrols in an area one block away frequented by drug
dealers, the dealers started moving into the mall's parking lot _
and into Frank's Pizza.
   Mao said he asked the police department for increased patrols
around his business. He said an officer occasionally strolled
through his restaurant, but it wasn't enough to keep the dealers
out.
   ``They were so brave and obvious,'' he said. ``They didn't care.
They weren't even scared of the police because the police never
hassled them.''
   Mao said he moved closing time from 11 p.m to 7 p.m. ``just so
they (drug dealers) wouldn't have a place to go.''
   On April 9, state and federal authorities staged a large raid on
dealers alleged to be involved in a cocaine trafficking ring based
in the Caribbean. Since the raid, part of which appeared on a
national ABC news broadcast on the drug problem, at least 40 people
have been indicted on charges involving the distribution of crack,
cocaine and marijuana.
   After the raid, U.S. Attorney William Kolibash said local police
officials were told to keep their hands off the crack dealers in
order not to interfere with the federal and state drug
investigation.
   ``This drug thing is a terrible thing for the town. I was hoping
it would stay away from the mall,'' said attorney Roger Perry, who
owns Hilldale Shopping Plaza.
   Mao said the April 9 raid helped clear the dealers out of his
restaurant, and Perry agreed that things have cleaned up since
then. But Perry still has told Mao he must leave the 10-store
shopping center by May 31 because of the drug activity that
occurred in the restaurant before the raid.
   ``The activity stepped up, so we decided to act,'' Perry said.
``We only had one recourse.'' He said he thought Mao was being
treated fairly.
   The city could also order Mao to shut the business down but has
not because it is waiting on Jefferson County Circuit Court to rule
on its request for an court order backing up its April 12
resolution.
   ``If it's a nuisance, we want it closed,'' Charles Town Mayor
D.C. ``Doc'' Master said.
   A hearing was scheduled Tuesday on the city's request for the
injunction, but Master said he and the council decided to hold off
because they didn't want to call as witnesses undercover officers
looking into the drug problem.
   The hearing has been rescheduled for May 9.
   Mao said he has tried to talk to Master twice and said the mayor
keeps putting him off. Master acknowledged that he hasn't talked to
Mao.
   ``I don't drink, I don't smoke, I don't even have a traffic
ticket in Charles Town,'' Mao said. ``I've worked very hard in this
business, and I don't want no hassle from either side.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
