<2ND_LINE>AM-Education Bill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0781,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Approves $8.3 Billion Education Bill With Dial-a-Porn
Provision</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 7th graf pvs, bgng: But lawmakers, to include vote
totals</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress gave final approval Wednesday to a
broad education bill that renews and expands programs for the
nation's students and contains a ban on pornographic telephone
message services.
   The Hawkins-Stafford School Improvement Act went to the White
House, where President Reagan was expected to sign it.
   The measure authorizes up to $8.3 billion in spending on
elementary and secondary education for fiscal 1989, more than half
of it on the government's Chapter 1 program of compensatory
education for disadvantaged children.
   The bill also contains new programs to prevent dropouts and help
high school students with weak skills, and greatly expands drug
abuse education and magnet schools.
   New money also was earmarked for math, science and
foreign-language programs that lawmakers said would improve the
productivity of future U.S. workers.
   Negotiators smoothing out differences in the House and Senate
bills had thrown out a dial-a-porn ban sponsored by Sen. Jesse
Helms, R-N.C., and replaced it with a system under which telephone
customers would not have access to the messages unless they called
and requested a hookup.
   But lawmakers in the House, their eyes on the November election,
restored the complete ban before accepting the House-Senate
compromise Tuesday on a 397-1 vote. The Senate ratified the entire
package on Wednesday on a voice vote.
   The American Civil Liberties Union said no court has ever upheld
a complete ban on non-obscene, ``indecent'' speech. The group said
the ban, which sprang from concern about children calling to hear
the lewd telephone messages, intrudes on the privacy and
free-speech rights of adults.
</TEXT>
