<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-20 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow in Michigan, New Hampshire, Nevada</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Spring snowstorms blanketed parts of Michigan, New Hampshire and
Nevada on Wednesday, while mountain areas in the West braced for
snow.
   Rain reached from California across eastern Oregon, northern
Nevada, southern Idaho, northwest Wyoming and southeast Montana.
The rain changed to snow in higher elevations.
   A winter storm warning was posted for the central and southwest
mountains of Idaho, and a winter storm watch was in effect for
higher elevations of the central and northern mountains of Arizona.
   Snow fell in the California mountains, and heavy rain at lower
elevations prompted flood advisories for some urban areas. Rain
also dampened northern Illinois, northern Indiana, northwest Ohio,
southern Michigan and southeast Wisconsin.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included 1.05 inches at the San Diego Naval Air Station and 0.54
inch at Imperial Beach, Calif.
   During the same period, 5 inches of snow fell at Mount
Washington, N.H., and 1 inch at Marquette, Mich. Austin, Nev., got
3 inches in the morning.
   Temperatures at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 30 degrees at Saranac
Lake, N.Y., to 91 at San Angelo, Tex. The nation's morning low was
17 at Warroad, Minn.
   Thursday's forecast called for rain, changing to snow in the
mountains, from the inland portions of the northern and central
Pacific Coast to southern California, from Idaho to Arizona and
Montana and from northwest of Colorado to South Dakota and northern
Nebraska.
   High temperatures were expected to reach the mid-30s over the
mountains of northern Arizona; the 40s and 50s from New England
across the Great Lakes, the upper Mississippi Valley, the northern
Plains, the Rockies, the northern plateau and the Great Basin; the
80s from South Carolina across Florida, the central Gulf states,
the lower Mississippi Valley and much of the southern Plains; the
90s over western Texas, and the 60s and 70s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
