<HEAD>Councilman Becomes Omaha's 45th Mayor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City Councilman Walt Calinger was picked
Wednesday as Omaha's 45th mayor, succeeding Bernie Simon, who died
last week of cancer.
   City Council selected the 48-year-old lawyer in a 4-3 vote over
Council President Fred Conley, who had contended he would not be
chosen because he is black.
   Calinger was sworn in immediately and pledged to work for
increased prosperity.
   ``The task that brings us here in some ways is not a pleasant
one,'' he said. ``Bernie Simon was a great mayor and a model for us
all. He was a healer of the city and I hope to be the same.''
   Calinger will serve the remaining 14 months of a four-year term
that originally was Mike Boyle's. Simon was chosen by the council
to replace Boyle in February 1987 after Boyle was recalled from
office. Simon died April 14.
   Conley said he had been done an injustice. `We're still working
or will be working toward that dream that one day everyone in this
country will be judged on the content of their character and not
the color of their skin,'' he said.
