<HEAD>House Selects Anderson To Head Committee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House formally selected Rep. Glenn
Anderson, D-Calif., on Wednesday to head the Public Works and
Transportation Committee, a position that has been vacant since the
death of Rep. James Howard, D-N.J.
   Anderson, the committee's ranking Democrat, has been acting
chairman since Howard died March 25 after suffering a heart attack.
   The House approved his selection by a unanimous voice vote. He
was not challenged for the job.
   The committee oversees billions of dollars in highway, mass
transit, aviation and water programs.
   Anderson, 75, has been chairman of the panel's surface
transportation subcommittee. David Smallen, spokesman for the
lawmaker, said he has still not decided whether he will relinquish
that position.
   The Los Angeles congressman has a low-key, non-confrontational
style that has largely kept him out of the limelight so far in a
20-year House career.
</TEXT>
