<HEAD>Middle East-Persian Gulf At a Glance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are Wednesday's developments in the Middle East and Persian
Gulf:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ALGIERS _ Shiite Moslem hijackers left a Kuwaiti jetliner after
15 days, apparently in exchange for safe passage to Lebanon or
Iran, and their remaining 31 hostages were freed.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   NICOSIA, Cyprus _ Iran reported full mobilization against ``the
evil triangle of America, Iraq and the reactionaries,'' and fired a
missile into Kuwait that was said to have exploded near a near a
U.S.-operated oil field. Iraq launched missiles at three Iranian
cities.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LONDON _ The increased conflict in the Persian Gulf this week
prompted Lloyd's of London to double insurance rates on ships
plying the waterway. The new premium is 2 percent of value for a
two-week voyage, or $200,000 on a $10 million hull.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon called off the search for a Marine
helicopter and its two crewmen missing in the gulf since clashes
Monday between U.S. and Iranian naval forces. Iran claims it shot
the chopper down.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   JERUSALEM _ Arabs in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip hung
black banners and held mock funerals for PLO military commander
Khalil Wazir, who was assassinated last week at his home in Tunis.
Mourners fought with Israeli soldiers, who shot one Palestinian to
death and wounded 10.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   DAMASCUS, Syria _ Hundreds of thousands of mourners followed a
gun carriage carrying Wazir's flag-draped coffin and vowed his
assassination would fuel the battle with Israel. ``In blood, in
soul, we shall be loyal to our martyr!'' they shouted at the
funeral of the PLO leader, also called Abu Jihad.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   JERUSALEM _ Israel mourned its war dead and then, after sundown,
celebrated its 40th birthday with a military show, barbecues and
street dancing. Mourning and celebration are coupled so ``our
children are aware of the sacrifice ... behind the joy of our
independence,'' a teacher said as her sixth graders put flowers on
the graves of soldiers.
</TEXT>
