<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LehderTrial     04-20 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lehder Trial,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lehder Offered To Sell Island Property To Shah</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carlos Lehder Rivas offered in 1979 to
sell part of a Bahamian island to the exiled Shah of Iran,
according to a letter introduced Wednesday at Lehder's
cocaine-smuggling trial.
   Lehder, 38, of Colombia, and Jack Carlton Reed, 57, of San
Pedro, Calif., are on trial on charges of conspiring to smuggle 3.3
tons of cocaine into the United States from Colombia via Norman's
Cay in the Bahamas from 1978 to 1980.
   The trial, in its 21st week, has heard from more than 100
prosecution witnesses.
   On May 3, 1979, Lehder wrote to Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi, then
staying at Paradise Island in Nassau, Bahamas, according to the
letter.
   ``It occurs to me that you might in fact be interested in
acquiring a portion of the land which we own at Norman's Cay in the
Exumas,'' said the letter.
   ``We are currently working on plans to extend the airport but it
is our intention to keep the island fairly private as we like our
privacy and knowing that this is your own feeling, we would not be
adverse to sharing this privacy with you, if you are at all
interested.''
   Six days later, Lehder received a reply from Kambiz Atabai, the
shah's chief of protocol, rejecting the offer.
   The letters were among documents found in four large boxes of
records from six Lehder companies.
   The records are being introduced into evidence during the
testimony of Wendell Welman, a criminal investigator for the
Internal Revenue Service.
   The government is attempting to discredit defense contentions
that Lehder was a legitimate businessman. It contends Lehder
operated Norman's Cay as his cocaine-smuggling base.
   The defense has claimed that Lehder planned to develop Norman's
Cay into a ``first-class private resort,'' as one of the documents,
a 1979 press release, stated.
</TEXT>
