<HEAD>British Tycoon Plans to Build World's Largest Ocean Liner</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf, ``The largest...'' with 2 grafs to show that
Norway is longest vessel and Sovereign of the Seas is heaviest.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British tycoon says he plans to build the
world's biggest luxury ocean liner, a ship longer than three
football fields.
   The ship will weigh 160,000 tons, measure 1,125 feet long,
accommodate 3,026 passengers and feature 12 swimming pools, the
world's largest casino and eight restaurants, according to
Indian-born Ravi Tikkoo, a British citizen.
   Designed with balconies overlooking the sea for its 1,513
cabins, the liner will cruise the Caribbean and Atlantic Ocean
after it is finished in 1992, he told a news conference Tuesday.
Tikkoo is expected to remain owner of the ship.
   He said the ship's size and design will revolutionize the
cruising industry and its construction will ``put Britain at the
top of the cruise ship-building nations.''
   The $456 million contract for the project, named ``Ultimate
Dream,'' was awarded to Harland and Wolff, a financially troubled
Belfast shipyard run by the British government in Northern Ireland.
   The heaviest luxury liner in use is the 74,000-ton Sovereign of
the Seas, which carries 2,284 passengers and 790 crew members. The
880-foot vessel was launched in January.
   The longest luxury liner is the 1,035-foot-long Norway, which
weighs 70,202 tons and carries 2,400 passengers.
</TEXT>
