<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 2055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KennedyFiles     04-20 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kennedy Files,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sirhan Prosecutor Doesn't Recall Any Destruction of Photographs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief prosecutor in the Robert F. Kennedy
assassination said Wednesday he doesn't recall any investigative
photographs being destroyed, as was revealed when the police files
were opened after two decades.
   Former Chief Deputy District Attorney Lynn D. Compton said he is
certain material wouldn't have been destroyed by police without
prosecutors knowing about it. He also said he is sure police didn't
destroy anything of importance.
   ``It always just annoys the hell out of me when self-appointed
experts surface years later and go at it like Agatha Christie. ...
That mentality escapes me,'' said Compton, now a state appeals
judge.
   Files of the investigation and evidence from the 1968
assassination at the Ambassador Hotel on the night of the New York
senator's Democratic presidential primary victory were made public
Tuesday at the state archives in Sacramento.
   The items included the .22-caliber gun Sirhan Bishara Sirhan
used to kill Kennedy on June 5, 1968, in the hotel kitchen.
   A certificate showed that 2,410 police photographs were burned
on Aug. 21, 1968. The documents also showed that door jambs and
ceiling tiles from the hotel kitchen were destroyed.
   Chief archivist John Burns speculated Tuesday the photos may
have duplicated others still in evidence. But he said the files
contain no such statement.
   Cmdr. William Booth, a Police Department spokesman, said he
could not confirm that photographs were destroyed but noted that in
1975 the department notified City Council of the routine
destruction of items gathered as potential evidence but which had
not turned out to be evidence.
   ``Whatever was destroyed was not anything that was needed or
used as evidence in the trial. If photographs were in fact
destroyed they would have fallen into that category and quite
likely were duplicates,'' Booth said.
   Greg Stone, a University of Wisconsin political scientist who
has studied the case for years, demanded a probe by the Los Angeles
Police Commission, a civilian group whose duties include monitoring
the Police Department.
   Commission Secretary Bill Moran did not immediately return a
telephone message.
   Compton said any destruction of material would not have been for
surreptitious reasons.
   ``It just could have been sheer volume of stuff _ that doesn't
mean anything,'' he said in a telephone interview from his home in
Lopez, Wash.
   He speculated the files may include ``a bunch of peripheral
material that we didn't feel necessary to use in the court
presentation. ... There were so many blind leads that were followed
in the case.''
   Former Police Chief Tom Reddin and the man who led the
investigation, then-Chief of Detectives Robert A. Houghton, told
the Los Angeles Times on Tuesday that they also did not recall that
any photographs were destroyed.
   Sirhan, a Jordanian immigrant who scribbled in his diary, ``RFK
must die,'' is serving a life term at Soledad prison. Second-gun
theories have haunted the case for many years. Sirhan says he was
the lone assassin.
</TEXT>
