<DOCNO> AP880420-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 2118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Economy     04-20 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Economy,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Encourages Chinese To Buy Their Homes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government outlined a program Wednesday for
expanding market-style economic reforms while fighting inflation,
the country's most pressing economic problem.
   Reform goals for 1988 include introducing competition for
company management posts and encouraging city dwellers to buy their
homes.
   So far, these measures have been introduced only experimentally
on a small scale.
   The program, announced by the official Xinhua News Agency, also
calls for such anti-inflation measures as tightening bank credit,
limiting state investment to major civic projects and limiting the
rapid growth of workers' wages and bonuses.
   Retail prices jumped 11 percent nationwide in the first quarter
of 1988, compared with a 7.3 percent increase in 1987. The price
increases have generated widespread grumbling.
   The reform program was devised by the State Commission for
Restructuring the Economy, which drew up the blueprints for China's
transformation from a centrally planned economy to one partially
directed by market forces.
   The commission, which was headed by the reformist Zhao Ziyang
until he took over as head of the Communist Party last year, now is
led by the new premier, Li Peng.
   The plan bears Li's stamp in its emphasis on fighting inflation
and its lack of new reform ideas. Li lacks Zhao's reputation as an
innovator and is believed to favor stability over rapid change.
   Xinhua did not carry comment from Li on the plan.
   The agency said the plan calls for 80 cities, including Beijing
and Shanghai, to reform their housing systems this year, a change
that is likely to generate widespread public opposition.
   Most urban houses and apartments are owned by the government or
by workplaces, which rent them for nominal fees.
   Housing reform, intended to save the government money, calls for
rents to be increased in line with maintenance costs and for
tenants to be encouraged to buy their apartments and houses. Xinhua
said the change is to be implemented nationwide within five years.
   Some local governments have said they will initially give
citizens subsidies to soften the blow of higher rents. Many Chinese
pay as little as $1.35 a month for rent.
   Under the program described Wednesday, the government will
expand its policy of letting state-owned enterprises make their own
economic decisions, and will introduce competition in filling
management posts, Xinhua said. Most managers are currently
appointed by the government.
   The program encourages businesses to use most of their profits
to improve production and to make sure workers' incomes do not grow
faster than productivity.
   Economists have blamed rising inflation in part on companies
using profits to give workers big bonuses.
   More enterprises will be allowed to issue bonds to the public,
Xinhua said, enabling them to raise cash while soaking up some of
the money supply.
   It said the government also will issue bonds to the public and
banks to make up its projected $2.2 billion deficit for 1988.
Government investment will be limited mainly to major road, bridge
and other infrastructure projects.
   Banks will issue fewer loans and increase their supervision of
companies that borrow money, the agency said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880420-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 2007EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Internment 4thLd-Writethru a0874 04-20 1210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Internment, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0874,1,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate OKs Payments to Japanese-American WWII Internees</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Inserts 2 grafs after 11th graf bgng: George Kondo ... to add
reaction; Inserts one graf after 24th graf pvs bgng: That and ...
to add Matsunaga comment on veto prospects, White House position.
Picks up 25th graf pvs bgng: The internment ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE GOULD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted Wednesday to give $20,000
tax-free payments to thousands of Japanese-Americans who were
forced from their homes and sent to internment camps during World
War II.
   Final passage came on a 69-27 vote after an emotional debate in
which senators recalled the sometimes-harsh treatment and financial
losses suffered by about 120,000 Japanese-Americans who were
interned after Japan attacked Pearl Harbor, Hawaii, on Dec. 7, 1941.
   The bill would require the United States government to apologize
for the mass roundups and would make each of the estimated 60,000
survivors eligible for $20,000 payments. A similar bill already has
passed the House.
   On votes of 67-30 and 61-35, the Senate defeated attempts to
strip the bill of the payments, while retaining the apology. It
then voted 91-4 to kill an amendment proposed by Sen. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., to withhold payments until Japan compensated American
families for losses suffered at Pearl Harbor.
   At one point, Sen. Spark Matsunaga, D-Hawaii, was brought to
tears as he told of an elderly Japanese-American internee being
killed by machine-gun fire when he strayed too close to a camp
fence.
   But Sen. Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo., argued that the internment
``was not a dishonorable act, it was the option of a nation in the
first days of a war.''
   Even if it was dishonorable, Wallop argued, it would be
``repugnant to think a clear conscience is to be had for a mere
$20,000 figure ... honor doesn't come with a dollar sign on it and
you don't buy it back.''
   The bill would cost an estimated $1.3 billion.
   Gordon Hirabayashi, a Japanese-American whose curfew violation
conviction in Seattle led to one of the Supreme Court rulings
upholding the internment, said, ``Like someone who's a victim of a
serious accident and becomes a quadriplegic, no matter what's voted
in the way of acknowledgement of error, it'll never be whole.''
   Hirabayashi, a retired sociology professor living in Edmonton,
Canada, said Japanese-American at this stage simply wanted ``an
acknowledgement that a wrong was done and a vote for an honorable
redress. They hope that the honorable redress will serve as a
deterrent for anything like this to happen to any other unfortunate
group.''
   George Kondo of San Francisco, director of the Northern
California-Western Nevada-Pacific region of the Japanese-American
Citizens League, said, ``I think we deserve everything that's
coming to us. ... At least they are recognizing the fact that there
was a wrongful act against their own citizens.''
   ``Pleased would be an understatement,'' said Cherry Kinoshita of
Seattle, who was interned at Minidoka, in Idaho in 1942 at the age
of 18 and who has been active in seeking redress since 1976.
   ``We've been working for over 10 years to see this happen. I
think it's great to see our nation admit an error, and take steps
to remedy what was a great injustice,'' she said.
   Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, a Japanese-American who lost his
right arm in combat with the Army in Italy, said: ``These payments
acknowledge the unconstitutional deprivation of liberty ... and the
stigma of being deemed unloyal.''
   ``If I were interned, I would consider $20,000 too little,''
Inouye said.
   Opponents, in addition to objections over the payments,
complained about a statement in the bill that the internment ``was
caused by racial prejudice, war hysteria and a failure of political
leadership.''
   ``Hindsight has proven us wrong,'' said Sen. Chic Hecht, R-Nev.
   ``But I cannot in good conscience go back and tell survivors of
Bataan, Iwo Jima and all those battles in the South Pacific and
tell them we have forgotten you but we are compensating the people
who we moved into camps,'' Hecht said.
   Matsunaga, the bill's chief sponsor, recalled in a floor speech
that he was an Army officer serving in Hawaii on Dec. 7, 1941.
   Matsunaga, a Japanese-American, recalled the story of an elderly
internee who was playing softball with his nephew when a ball
strayed too close to a fence.
   When the guard told the man to halt, Matsunaga quoted him as
replying, ``It's all right, I'm just going to pick up the
softball.''
   He moved forward and was killed by a burst of fire from the
guard's machine gun, Matsunaga told the Senate.
   At that point, Matsunaga halted in midsentence, unable to keep
his voice from breaking despite several attempts to resume speaking.
   ``I myself become overly emotional when I think about it even to
this day,'' he said after regaining composure.
   The measure is similar to a bill passed by the House last Sept.
17 by a 243-141 margin. The Senate version, however, authorizes
payments of up to $12,000 for surviving members of the Aleut Indian
tribes who were forcibly removed from the Aleutian Islands during
the Japanese attack on those islands in 1942.
   That and other minor differences would have to be worked out
before the bill could go to President Reagan, who has been urged to
veto it by the Office of Management and Budget because of its $1.3
billion price tag.
   Matsunaga, asked about veto prospects, said, ``We have mixed
reports'' from the White House. The White House supported the
measure going into the vote, said B.J. Cooper, a spokesman. But it
had also wanted certain changes to the bill, such as the deletion
of the Aleutian Island payments, which were not made. Cooper said
he did not know the White House position on the bill that was
passed.
   The internment camps arose from a 1942 order by President
Franklin D. Roosevelt that said the War Department could designate
military areas from which people could be excluded.
   Later military orders resulted in the exclusion of all people of
Japanese ancestry from California, Washington and Oregon, and some
in Hawaii. The orders affected 77,000 U.S. citizens and 43,000
legal and illegal resident aliens. All were taken to prison camps
in the Western states.
   The last camp was closed in January 1946.
   In all, about 120,000 people of Japanese ancestry were detained
in the camps, including 77,000 American citizens. An estimated
60,000 are still alive, and the bill would allow them to claim
individual $20,000 payments in return for waiving any further
wartime claims against the government.
   Congress has already awarded about $38 million in restitution
payments since the passage of a 1948 Evacuation Claims law. Five
years ago, however, a federal commission estimated that the
Japanese-Americans had suffered losses of up to $2 billion that had
never been compensated.
   About 900 Aleuts were moved from their homes and forced to live
in abandoned mines, canneries and camps about 2,000 miles away.
Lack of medical care and adequate food contributed to disease and
death and many of their homes were destroyed or vandalized in their
absence.
   About 450 Aleuts survive and would be eligible for $12,000
payments. Another $20 million would benefit Aleut villages and
provide for scholarships and the general welfare of the tribe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
