<2ND_LINE>AM-Editor Killed,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Columnist Slain In Street Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TIJUANA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper columnist known for his
biting articles on local politicians and businessmen was shot to
death in his car, authorities said.
   Hector Felix, the 46-year-old co-editor of Zeta, was hit in the
head and arm by three shotgun blasts as he drove alone, said
District Attorney Francisco Dominguez.
   There was no known motive for the morning attack two miles from
Zeta's offices and eight miles east of downtown, police said. A
possible witness was being questioned by Baja California State
Judicial Police, Dominguez said.
   Felix had founded Zeta with his longtime friend and partner,
Jesus Blancornelas.
   ``Right now we are recovering from the shock,'' Blancornelas
said in a telephone interview. ``The government has said that it
respects freedom of expression and that the police are among the
most advanced. ... We hope that both those things might be
demonstrated.''
   Felix, had been with Zeta since 1980. He wrote a column for the
weekly, which is published in the Mexican border city and
distributed throughhout Baja California. It has a circulation of
60,000.
   ``He was a satirist. He was very well known and popular here in
the state,'' said Miguel Cervantes, a writer for Zeta. Cervantes
said Felix had no known enemies and called the shooting ``an act of
cowards'' aimed at muzzling the press.
   Felix's column, ``A Little Bit of Something,'' dealt with
everday occurences in the state's political and social life. He
often focused his sarcasm on government officials and business
people, chiding them for what he termed know-it-all attitudes and
arrogance.
   ``He had a sense of humor with a lot of spark that left many
uncomfortable, especially officials,'' Blancornelas said.
   Last year, Zeta offices were sprayed with bullets from a passing
car. No one was injured and police never found those responsible.
</TEXT>
