<2ND_LINE>AM-Zimbabwe-Slaying,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>German Priest Slain While Trying To Halt Ax Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANGUS SHAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas armed with assault rifles
killed a West German priest when he tried to rescue another
missionary who was being attacked with a hatchet, a church
spokesman said Wednesday.
   Government troops combed western Zimbabwe for the four gunmen
believed responsible for the death Tuesday of Rev. Killian Knoerl,
58, a Roman Catholic missionary from Stuttgart.
   Rev. Oskar Wermter told a news conference that Knoerl was slain
at the Empandeni mission, about 12 miles from the Botswana border.
   The killing occurred hours after President Robert Mugabe
declared a general amnesty for rebels in the western province of
Matabeleland, where hundreds of civilians have been killed by
guerrillas in recent years.
   Knoerl was shot while coming to the aid of Rev. Johannes
Banning, who was being struck with a hatchet, Wermter said.
   Banning, 40, also a West German, was rushed to Central Hospital
in Bulawayo, the administrative capital of Matabeleland. His
condition was not known.
   The guerrillas, armed with AK-47 semiautomatic rifles, arrived
at the mission Tuesday night, ransacked homes and set fire to two
vehicles, Wermter said.
   The gunmen ordered a Zimbabwean priest, Rev. Luke Mlimo, to tie
up the other two priests and a third West German missionary and
strike them with the hatchet, the spokesman said.
   When Mlimo refused, one of the gunmen hit Banning on the head
with the hatchet, Wermter said. He said Knoerl ``grabbed the man's
ax and hit him. He was then killed with two rifle shots by one of
the bandits.''
   The attackers fled.
   Mugabe announced the amnesty on Tuesday, the eighth anniversary
of the country's independence. He said about 100 rebels remained in
Matabeleland, the traditional tribal stronghold of former
opposition leader Joshua Nkomo.
   Mugabe said the amnesty was the result of a unity pact signed
Dec. 22 with Nkomo.
   Mugabe and Nkomo led allied rebel armies fighting white rule
when Zimbabwe was a British colony known as Rhodesia. When
independence was declared and Mugabe became president, some Nkomo
supporters began fighting.
   In November, rebels hacked to death 16 white missionaries and
children at two farms south of Bulawayo.
</TEXT>
