<HEAD>Election Becomes Two-Man Race, According to London Bookmaker</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. presidential election has turned into a
race between Vice President George Bush and Gov. Michael Dukakis of
Massachusetts, with Bush the clear favorite, one of London's
biggest bookmakers said Wednesday.
   William Hill gave 2-5 odds for Bush, meaning a gambler would win
two dollars for every five wagered if Republican Bush won, said
Christine Stanley of the bookmaking firm. Bush's odds last week
were 4-9.
   The odds for Democratic front-runner Dukakis were 2-1, compared
with 11-4 last week, while the odds for his closest rival, Jesse
Jackson, were 25-1, compared with 12-1 last week, she said.
   ``(Bush) is the well-in-front favorite,'' she said.
