<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka-Rebels     04-20 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka-Rebels,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tamil Infighting Claims 38 Sri Lankan Lives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Tamil rebel factions clashed in
northern and eastern Sri Lanka, leaving 38 people dead in two days,
Sri Lankan military officials said Wednesday.
   Killed were 20 members of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam
and 16 members of the Eelam Revolutionary Organization of Students,
officials said. Two relatives of a rebel, one of them a 70-year-old
Tamil man, also died, they said.
   A senior military official said Wednesday that the separatist
groups, once allies, ``have been locked in mortal combat for the
last 24 hours.''
   ``Both groups are hell-bent on liquidating each other. We don't
know why,'' he added.
   The Sri Lankan military officials also said 27 Tamil Tigers were
killed Tuesday by Indian troops near Vavuniya, 100 miles north of
Colombo, but an Indian diplomat said she could not confirm the
account.
   ``We have absolutely no such reports,'' the spokeswoman for the
Indian Embassy said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The Tigers are the largest Tamil rebel group. Four years ago
they began a war against Sri Lanka's Sinhalese majority in which
more than 8,000 people have died.
   Tamils, who make up about 18 percent of Sri Lanka's population,
say the Sinhalese discriminate against them in jobs and education.
   Moderate Tamils want more autonomy for their communites in the
north and east of Sri Lanka, where they predominate, while
militants are fighting for a separate nation.
   India has sent more than 50,000 soldiers to Sri Lanka to enforce
a peace accord and is trying to disarm the rebels.
   The Sinhalese, who make up 75 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million
people, control the government and the military.
   The Sri Lankan officials, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the latest violence between the Tamil Tigers and the student
group began on Tuesday.
   They said Tiger gunmen raided a house in Pungundutivu in the
Jaffna peninsula, about 190 miles north of Colombo, killing eight
rival guerrillas and the grandfather and son-in-law of a rebel.
   Later in the day, the Tigers killed eight sleeping members of
the rival group at Mankulam village, 15 miles southwest of
Vavuniya, the officials said.
   On Wednesday, the Eelam Revolutionary Organization of Students
retaliated by ambushing and killing 20 Tigers riding in a truck at
Mutur, about 140 miles northeast of Colombo.
</TEXT>
