<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Gorbachev,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Discusses Party Conference with Regional Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev called regional Communist
Party leaders to Moscow to discuss an unusual party conference in
June, Tass said Wednesday. The June conference will give the Soviet
leader a chance to strengthen his hand against opponents. It
affords him the opportunity, between the party congresses that are
held every five years, to change the membership of the
policy-making party Central Committee.
   Gorbachev met party leaders from the Soviet Union's 15
republics, territories and regions in a series of conferences April
11, 14 and 18, the official news agency reported.
   ``The activity of party organizations in giving guidance to
perestroika (restructuring Soviet society) was discussed and there
was a detailed exchange of views on the course of preparations for
the ... conference,'' Tass said.
   ``A thorough analysis was made of proposals related to the need
for perfecting the political system.''
   Gorbachev has said that resistance to his policy of perestroika
extends all the way to the approximately 300 members of the Central
Committee.
   At a Central Committee meeting in February, Gorbachev said one
task of the party conference will be to strengthen the Soviet
political and governmental system to ensure that it is not subject
to the rule of only one person.
   Tass said participants in the three days of conferences with
Gorbachev stressed the need to strengthen his reform effort and
meet targets for priorities such as improving food supplies and
consumer goods.
</TEXT>
