<HEAD>Soviet Official Says Climate Being Created for Papal Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Tass official said on Wednesday that changing
conditions in the Soviet Union could help lead to a visit by Pope
John Paul II.
   Anatoly A. Krasikov, deputy director general of Tass and a
former Rome correspondent for the official Soviet news agency, was
asked at a news conference if the Soviet government wanted a visit
by the pope.
   ``There are no conditions on either part (for a papal visit) ..
. but `conditions,' in the sense of climate ... is another thing,''
he replied.
   ``I am absolutely sure that this climate is being created.''
   The question of a possible visit by the Roman Catholic leader to
the officially atheist country has been raised in particular
because 1988 is the 1,000th anniversary of the advent of
Christianity in the area now called the Ukraine.
   In a document released on Tuesday, the pope called for religious
freedom for Catholics in the Ukraine. John Paul has often expressed
his wish to go to the Soviet Union but has said he would go there
only if allowed to visit Roman Catholics throughout the country,
including the Ukraine.
   He also wants to be able to visit Lithuania.
   Before taking questions from reporters, Krasikov said he wanted
to talk about important developments in his country.
   ``We are all searching together for truth ... in the
construction of society ... We want more democracy,'' Krasikov
said, reflecting about the Soviet Union under Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   He said that with this point of view, ``freedom of religion is
important.''
