<2ND_LINE>AM-Presidential Money, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0856,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Financially Healthy; Gore Has Big Debt; Bush Fundraising
Finished</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 10th graf pvs, bgng: The other, with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with Jackson report</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential contender Sen. Albert Gore Jr.
ran up a debt of $1.6 million before the New York primary where the
fruits of his spending reaped only 10 percent of the vote this
week, his financial statement showed Wednesday.
   Gore has lost his eligibility for federal matching funds and
would need to attain an unlikely 20 percent of the vote in
Pennsylvania's primary next week in order to restablish his
eligibility.
   However, if he drops out of the race, he would be able to
receive federal matching funds to retire the debt, under election
law.
   On the Republican side of the presidential race, former TV
evangelist Pat Robertson continued to borrow heavily to keep his
campaign afloat, but since he is bumping up against the spending
limit he has had to dramatically scale back his massive campaign
operation, his campaign report showed Wednesday.
   Robertson spent $7.8 million during March alone just repaying
some of his previous bank loans.
   Robertson technically remains a candidate but has conceded that
Vice President George Bush will win the nomination.
   Gore, who was expected to suspend his campaign Thursday,
personally loaned his campaign $40,000 and took out bank loans of
$1.4 million during March, according to his campaign finance report
filed with the Federal Election Commission.
   Most of that was for the Super Tuesday series of primaries in 20
states on March 8.
   Meanwhile, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, who established
himself in New York as the clear frontrunner, is continuing his
flush financial status, his report shows.
   And the other Democrat still in the race, Jesse Jackson, raised
$2.8 million in his biggest fund-raising month ever. That included
$2 million from contributors, $330,189 in federal matching funds,
and a $250,000 loan.
   Jackson ended the month with $865,946 in cash on hand, a
outstanding bills of $678,973.
   Dukakis had burst in fund-raising in March, with $3.4 million in
total receipts, and ended the month with $1.7 million in cash on
hand to cover $697,162 in bills and to propel him into the costly
New York race.
   Dukakis' receipts included $621,098 in federal matching funds.
The $2.4 million he got from contributors was up from his February
total of $1.3 million in donations.
   Gore also had a substantial fund-raising month in March, taking
in $3.4 million, of which $336,312 was matching funds and $1.2
million came from contributions.
   He ended the month with a debt of $1.6 million, with only
$416,603 in cash on hand. His aides had said he would need no
additional loans to spend $1 million on a costly New York media
campaign, but aides subsequently disclosed that he borrowed at
least $100,000.
   Bush is effectively finished with fund raising, having raised
the maximum $27 million that election law permits primary
candidates to spend. During March, he raised $1.7 million, of which
$247,118 was in the form of federal matching funds.
   He ended the month with $3.6 million in the bank and close to $1
million in outstanding obligations. At the end of March he had
spent $18.9 million against the base spending cap of $23 million,
plus the maximum $4.6 million allowed for fund-raising expenses.
   Bush's treasurer Fred Bush said earlier this month that overall
fund raising for the campaign had hit $30 million. That included $3
million for legal and accounting costs, which are not subject to
the spending limit.
   Robertson was already within $2 million of the spending ceiling
as of Super Tuesday.
   In his new report covering the month of March, he reported
raising $2.3 million, of which $896,551 were federal matching
funds, and $873,444 was money from contributors. By the end of
March he had spent $20 million against the $23 million base cap,
plus the full $4.6 million fund-raising allocation, his report
showed.
   Robertson ended March with $1.4 million in debts and only
$61,890 in cash on hand.
   He personally loaned his campaign $25,000, and took out $385,000
in bank loans. He spent $7.8 million paying off previous loans.
   GOP contender Jack Kemp, the congressman from New York, who
dropped out of the race during March, is still in debt. He ended
the month $672,826 in the red, but was anticipating more than
$500,000 in federal matching funds to help retire that. He had only
$57,741 in the bank, after raising $604,586 during the month.
</TEXT>
