<HEAD>Jackson Apparently Wins In Vermont, Splits Delegates With Dukakis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with 100 percent of results, but
race too close to call based on unofficial results</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER GRAFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, showing strength in some
of Vermont's smallest, most rural communities, finished first
Wednesday in an unofficial count of Democratic state delegates
elected in local caucuses.
   With all of the state's communities reporting results from
Tuesday night's caucuses, an unofficial count by The Associated
Press gave Jackson 589 state convention delegates, compared with
581 for Michael Dukakis. There were 116 uncommitted delegates
elected, while Sen. Albert Gore picked up four delegates.
   The AP count showed the race so close that the official party
tabulation, expected next week, could place either Jackson or
Dukakis out front.
   Jackson bested Dukakis, the governor of neighboring
Massachusetts, in Vermont's largest city of Burlington, and he won
in many of the state's smallest, most rural communities.
   The delegates elected Tuesday night will attend next month's
state convention, at which time 14 of Vermont's 19 delegates to the
national convention will be chosen. The remaining five spots belong
to Gov. Madeleine Kunin, a Dukakis backer, and four state party
officials, all but one of whom are likely to support Dukakis.
   The town-by-town returns showed that, with the exception of
Burlington, Dukakis did best in the larger communities while
Jackson picked up delegates in the smallest towns.
   ``It's a tremendous victory for us,'' said Liz Blum, the Jackson
state coordinator.
   ``We would sure like to have 10 more votes,'' said William
Wasserman, the Dukakis state coordinator. ``We knew it would be
close.''
   ``We have a very high regard for the excellent field work the
Jackson campaign did,'' said Wasserman. ``They organized in the
smallest of communities, as well as the larger ones. That showed
real persistence, real dedication to detail.''
   Dukakis had won Vermont's presidential primary March 1, winning
56 percent of the vote, while Jackson gained 26 percent. But the
primary was non-binding and had nothing to do with the selection of
delegates.
</TEXT>
