<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Ex-CopShot     04-20 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ex-Cop Shot,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Cop Blames Shooting On Three Attackers, San Diego Police
Question Story</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAITH CONROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NINEMILE FALLS, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former San Diego police
lieutenant who once testified against a fellow officer claimed on
Wednesday to have been tied up and shot by intruders in his home,
but ex-colleagues suggested he staged the attack.
   Doyle F. Wheeler was treated at a hospital and released Tuesday
after authorities found him at home with a gunshot wound, said
Stevens County Sheriff Richard Andres. The shot grazed his head,
Andres said.
   Wheeler said he was attacked by three men.
   ``He (Wheeler) reported that someone tried to kill him, but
there was only a graze wound and powder burn,'' San Diego Police
Chief Bob Burgreen told the San Diego Tribune. ``He was handcuffed,
tied up and had to dial 911 with his tongue. I find all of this
very interesting.''
   ``It was absolutely physically impossible for me to do it to
myself,'' Wheeler said. ``It is impossible to hogtie and shoot
yourself.''
   Local authorities have refused to release details about the
shooting and have declined comment on any connection to Wheeler's
testimony on behalf of Sagon Penn, who was acquitted of murder and
attempted murder in the 1985 shooting of two San Diego police
officers.
   Wheeler testified the 1985 shooting was a racially motivated
attack provoked by the white officers. Penn is black.
   Neighbors on Tuesday reported seeing Wheeler's car being driven
away from his home about the time the shooting occurred. However,
they said they did not see who was driving or how many people were
in the car, which is missing.
   ``They intended to kill me and they thought they killed me,''
Wheeler told the Spokane Chronicle on Wednesday. ``I am afraid for
my life. I have my family in a safe place and I will be joining
them.''
   The incident ``makes no sense,'' Harry O. Eastus II, a police
officer and director of the San Diego Police Officers Association,
told the San Diego Tribune on Wednesday. The association is the
officers' union.
   ``Based on (Wheeler's) past performance, there is a strong
likelihood that he could have done that to himself or paid sombody
to do it,'' Eastus said.
   Wheeler, who was a member of the San Diego force on and off for
about 10 years, left the department briefly in 1977 on
stress-related disability, San Diego police said. He retired on
stress disability in 1985, police said.
   Paul Sands, news director for KGTV in San Diego, said Wheeler
had called station anchorman Michael Tuck two weeks ago to report
threats against his life and Tuck's. Tuck had plans for a TV movie
about the Penn case.
   The San Diego Tribune quoted Tuck as saying Wheeler warned him
that a member of the San Diego Police Department told him that
officers planned to kill Tuck and Wheeler.
   The sheriff said investigators had sent evidence from the
Wheeler home to a Spokane crime lab for analysis.
</TEXT>
