<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Hart-Lies     04-20 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hart-Lies,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Hart Press Secretary Admits Lying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gary Hart's former press secretary says he
told two lies, both last May when the candidate's White House bid
was collapsing.
   Kevin Sweeney made the admission in a review in Wednesday's San
Francisco Examiner of ``Speaking Out, Inside the Reagan White
House'' by Larry Speakes, the former White House spokesman who
admitted fabricating quotes for Reagan.
   ``I told two lies, both last May when Hart's original 1988
campaign crumbled to its apparent end,'' wrote Sweeney.
   Sweeney, Hart's press secretary from 1985 to May 1987, when Hart
temporarily pulled out of the race for the Democratic presidential
nomination, said he lied when he told a Washington Post reporter
that Hart was asleep.
   ``I was trying to buy time after being told yet another
potentially fatal revelation,'' he said.
   He said he lied again when he emphatically denied to an ABC
reporter who called at 4 a.m. that Hart's campaign was about to end.
   ``I was trying to protect the Harts' privacy as they left for
home,'' he said.
   Sweeney, who lives in San Bruno south of San Francisco, said
that because the campaign was ending, he no longer cared about his
credibility.
   He added that during his tenure he also told ``tiny lies'' on
those occasions when he said he thought Hart had done well when he
in fact he hadn't.
   ``My substantive lies I regret, my subjective lies I do not,''
said Sweeney. ``But since my first day as press secretary, the
steps away from the absolute truth (be they small or large)
constantly presented themselves as the single greatest ethical
dilemma in my life.''
   ``Frankly most press secretaries are liars,'' he said.
   Speakes, in his book, admitted twice attributing to Reagan
quotes he never made.
   In once instance, he quoted Reagan as telling Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev during the 1985 summit: ``There is much that
divides us, but I believe the world breathes easier because we are
talking here together.''
</TEXT>
