<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Independence 2ndLd-Writethru   04-20 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Independence, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0815,0737</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Marks 40th Anniversary, Mourns War Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to CORRECT period covered by Memorial Day,
which ended at sundown Wednesday, sted Tuesday; picks up 3rd graf
pvs: Festivities this year...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel mourned its war dead Wednesday and then,
after sundown, celebrated its 40th birthday with a military show,
barbecues and dancing in the streets.
   Memorial Day, during which Israelis honor the 16,450 soldiers
killed in seven wars and in clashes with Arab guerrillas, ran from
sundown Tuesday until sundown Wednesday, followed by the 24-hour
Independence Day celebration.
   Festivities this year were tempered by anxiety over more than
four months of Arab rebellion in the occupied lands.
   Authorities suspended travel to Israel by the 1.5 million
Palestinians in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip through the
weekend to prevent terrorist attacks.
   In a special Independence Day message aimed at an Arab audience,
President Chaim Herzog called on Palestinians to end anti-Israeli
protests and said they were being misled by leaders making
unrealistic promises.
   ``The hope of the Palestinians does not lie in the hapless
attempt to defeat Israel, but in acceptance, compromise and
co-existence,'' he said. His remarks, read in Hebrew but peppered
with Arabic phrases, were broadcast on Israel's Arabic-language
television.
   In a separate address aimed at a Jewish audience, Herzog
emphasized Israel's achievements, adding that ``the clouds which
overcast Israel's skies in the 40th year of its independence are
passing clouds.''
   Israel gained its independence on May 14, 1948, and the
celebration Wednesday coincided with the date on the Hebrew
calendar.
   Mourning and celebration are coupled each year ``so that our
children are aware of the sacrifice that went behind the joy of our
independence,'' teacher Ruth Dafnai told a reporter as her sixth
graders put flowers on graves at the Mount Herzl cemetery in
Jerusalem.
   Israeli leaders planned many festivities for the 40th
anniversary, with a nostalgic theme.
   Hikes were scheduled for Thursday along routes taken by
pre-state Jewish fighters. Israel's Declaration of Independence is
on display at the parliament building.
   A highlight of the holiday Wednesday evening was the nation's
first mass public display of armaments since a military parade in
1973. It included parachute jumps, fighter jets, tanks and
fireworks.
   Israel has avoided displaying its military might in the past,
preferring not to emphasize the role of wars in its short history.
   Teachers say Independence and Memorial Day ceremonies at schools
help prepare children for military duty.
   Army service is a central part of life in Israel, where
18-year-old Jewish men serve three years of compulsory duty
followed by at least 40 days a year in the reserves until age 54.
   At Denmark High School in Jerusalem, bereaved parents lectured
in classrooms Wednesday and pupils saluted those killed in combat
and in training accidents.
   Cyrus Weiler, 81, who immigrated from the Soviet Union 25 years
ago and has lost two sons in battle, urged 50 high school juniors
to learn from his children's example of sacrifice.
   ``Everyone has to defend our homeland,'' he said. ``If you
continue in this path of helping the country, there will be value
to your life.''
   Weiler's son Adam was killed in 1970 during a battle with
Egyptians at the Suez Canal, and Gideon was slain in a Golan
Heights tank battle with Syrians during the 1973 Arab-Israeli war.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and Yitzhak Rabin, the defense
minister, delivered Memorial Day speeches in Jerusalem and Tel Aviv.
   ``We are facing one long war,'' Rabin said. ``In order to live
here as a people and a state we must be strong and ready to defend
ourselves. We know that the first time we lose a war, it will be
our last.''
   Shamir said at another ceremony that ``we reiterate our
determination to defend our homeland,'' and told a group of
American Jewish fund-raisers the Palestinian uprising is not
``demonstrations or sit-ins. It is war.''
   Of soldiers who serve in the occupied territories, the prime
minister said: ``I can tell that they know that what they are doing
now is just as important for the country's future as anything they
have done in the past and we're just as proud of them now as we
were then.''
</TEXT>
