<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PolkaDot     04-20 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polka Dot,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kennedy Assassination `Polka Dot Dress' Story Was Lie, Witness
Said</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Kennedy Files</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who reported seeing a
mysterious ``girl in a polka dot dress'' running from the scene of
Robert F. Kennedy's assassination admitted two weeks later that she
lied, according to newly released files.
   Sandra Serrano, a college student at the time, said she had
confronted the woman on the night of Kennedy's shooting at the
Ambassador Hotel in Los Angeles just after midnight June 5, 1968.
   The files, made public Tuesday by state officials, showed that
Miss Serrano first told her story to officers at 4 a.m. that day at
police headquarters in Los Angeles, where she was one of hundreds
of witnesses interviewed.
   Miss Serrano, who said she was chairman of the Youth for Kennedy
chapter in Pasadena, said she had come to hear Kennedy speak but
left the hotel ballroom because it was too crowded.
   She said that as she sat on a step outside she heard shots or
backfire and ``about half a minute later this girl comes tearing
down the stairs saying _ she said, `We shot him. We shot him.' And
I said, `Who did you shoot?' And she said, `Senator Kennedy.'''
   She said the girl was in a white dress with dark polka dots.
   She stood by her story for a time and even went with police to
the Ambassador Hotel for a re-enactment, the file showed. But on
June 20, 1968, when told she had failed a lie-detector test, she
declared, ``The whole thing was a lie.''
   Asked by Police Sgt. Enrique Hernandez why she had not corrected
the story sooner, she said: ``I didn't want to look like a fool,
which I look like now. You know, I thought I was supposed to see
more _ more than I did.''
   The following day, June 21, police canceled an all-points
bulletin for the girl in the polka-dot dress, but the story did not
die.
   When the Kennedy files were released Tuesday, among the items on
display in a glass case was a black and white polka dot dress
police had bought to try to jog the memories of witnesses who might
have seen the mystery woman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
