<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0899,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Government Lifts State of Emergency</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEDES with 6 grafs to UPDATE with lifting of emergency. Picks
up 6th graf pvs, ``The official ...; edits 4th graf pvs, ``The
Reagan ... to conform.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Assembly voted Wednesday
to revoke a state of emergency imposed a month ago after an
abortive coup against the country's de facto ruler, Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega.
   The move was announced in a local television broadcast which
said the Assembly had acted at the request of civilian President
Manuel Solis Palma.
   There was no immediate comment from the government.
   Technically called a ``state of urgency'' by Panama's
Constitution, the action permitted the government to suspend a wide
range of civil liberties, including freedom of speech and assembly
and the right to private property.
   The government invoked the decree on March 18, two days after
dissident officers tried to remove Noriega as head of Panama's
Defense Forces.
   Earlier Wednesday, a U.S. official said that four high-ranking
Panamanian military officers will attend a seminar at Fort McNair
near Washington next week.
   The official, who spoke on condition that he not be identified,
said the four would participate in a course at the Inter-American
Defense College.
   The seminar will bring together officers from several member
nations of the Organization of Amrican States, including those from
Panama.
   The Reagan administration has been using economic pressure to
try to force the ouster of Noriega, head of Panama's Defense
Forces. It has let it be known it would welcome a coup by junior
officers.
   The Panamanians attending the seminar were identified as Col.
Elias Castillo, a ranking member of the Defense Forces; Col. Julio
Ow Young, the nation's police chief; and Majs. Daniel Delgado
Diamante and Arosemena King.
   Delgado is a specialist on the Panama Canal Treaty and King is
the No. 2 man in military intelligence. All four are based at
Defense Forces headquarters in Panama City.
   The 15,000-member Defense Forces includes the military and
police.
   Noriega has been indicted in the United States on
drug-trafficking and money-laundering charges, which he has denied.
   Ranking members of Noriega's staff are said to be seldom
accessible to U.S. diplomats. The military officers thus may be
sought out by Pentagon officials upon their arrival at Fort McNair.
   The U.S. official who described the trip said he did not know
when the four would arrive in the United States or how long they
would be attending the seminar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
