<1ST_LINE>a a PM-OntheMoney Adv21   04-20 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-On the Money, Adv 21,0647</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday April 21</NOTE>
<HEAD>Playing It Safe on Interest Rates</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As interest rates have edged upward in recent
weeks, many savers and investors have begun looking for ways to
avoid the same mistakes they made last spring.
   Yields on long-term Treasury bonds, one closely watched gauge of
overall trends in interest rates, have climbed lately from about
8.3 percent to just above 9 percent as of early this week.
   Wall Street is filled with talk that the Federal Reserve might
soon tighten credit further, in order to keep an unexpectedly
strong economy from touching off increased inflationary pressures.
   All this carries a familiar ring for people who remember what
happened in late March through May 1987, when a surge in interest
rates sent values of many long-term interest-bearing investments _
for example, bond mutual funds _ tumbling by 10 percent to 15
percent.
   Forecasting interest rates is a notoriously difficult task. When
the great majority of people expect them to rise, they are
perfectly capable of doing just the opposite.
   Still, for anyone for wants to avoid getting caught in an
exposed position should rates keep moving up, there is a wide
variety of choices available.
   The key to reducing interest-rate risk is to shorten maturities
_ that is, to move into investments with lives short enough that
their market values aren't much affected by changing conditions.
   Reg Green, publisher of the Mutual Fund News Service, recently
provided the example of a three-year government note, yielding
about 7.4 percent. It would rise or fall in value by about 2.5
percent for each decline or increase of one percentage point in
long-term interest rates.
   By contrast, a 15-year Treasury bond yielding about 8.7 percent
would fluctuate about 10 percent in value if long-term rates rose
or fell one percentage point.
   If you want to eliminate any ups and downs whatsoever in the
dollar value of your principal, you can opt for very short-term
investments that are collectively referred to in the investment
business as ``cash.''
   These include Treasury bills, available in maturities of three
months to one year; money market mutual funds, whose total assets
have lately hit record highs; and bank money market accounts or
certificates of deposit maturing in, say, three to six months.
   Should interest rates rise substantially at any point, yields on
money market funds would naturally follow them, with a lag time
that depends on the average maturity of the securities in the
fund's portfolio.
   A popular new breed of money funds invests in short-term
municipal securities, and thus provides income that is exempt from
federal income taxes.
   But their appeal might not be as great as it looks. Suppose you
are faced with the choice of a taxable money fund yielding 6.43
percent and a tax-free fund returning 4.58 percent.
   If you are in the 33 percent tax bracket, which applies this
year to a relatively small number of higher-income savers and
investors, you would come out with a slightly higher after
tax-return in the tax-free fund.
   But if you were in the 28 percent bracket, you would actually
realize a few more aftertax dollars with your money in the taxable
fund than in the tax-free one.
   Suppose you are chary of the long-term bond market, but not
satisfied with yields available in the money markets. There are
plenty of ways to compromise with an investment maturing in the
``medium term,'' or somewhere roughly 18 months to 10 years from
now.
   Options in this range include bank CDs; Treasury securities
bought directly from the government or through a bank or broker,
and ``limited maturity'' bond mutual funds.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs April 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880420-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 1351EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv21   04-20 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 21,0654</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday April 21</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Elevator Always Goes Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The elevator goes up but never comes down. The
higher it gets the faster it goes. There is no stop button.
   The situation recalls the hair-raising serials that once were a
staple of early movie houses, in which each sequence ended in awful
peril followed in a week by impossible escape.
   But there may be no escape from this difficulty unless the
corporations involved are even more creative than directors of
those old movies, and certainly more ingenious they have been to
date.
   The subject is the total income _ both salary and bonus _ of top
corporate officers. Only a couple of decades ago it was measured in
the low six figures, more recently in seven digits, and now on
occassion in eight numbers.
   One of the problems is that executive bonuses _ General Motors
granted $157 million in stock bonuses last year _ are almost always
based on good short-term performance.
   The situation can reach an acute stage when the industry is
cyclical, which the automotive industry is. That is, years of big
sales, high profits, rising stock prices and the like alternate
with off years.
   There is rarely a price to be paid for off years. But there is
almost always a reward to be gained for good years.
   Professor Eugene Jennings, professor of business at Michigan
State University and a confidential adviser to corporate chiefs and
boards, says the ever-rising incomes are developing into a public
relations problem for companies.
   In lean years, he observes, some executives are given bonuses
based on the justification that money will motivate them to produce
fat years. When the fat years arrive their bonuses are justified as
in the interests of equity.
   Equity in this instance means it is fair that executives be
compensated for enhancing shareholder values. But when that and
other explanations cannot be made, it is sometimes argued that
bonuses are needed to retain valued people.
   When those reasons fail, market parity is used. It means that an
executive of one company certainly cannot be compensated lower than
that of a comparable executive in a similar company. It is said
that market wages must be paid.
   There is some evidence that in lean years boards do indeed grant
fewer or smaller salary and bonus increases.
   But, says Jennings, ``as soon as one of these justifications can
be made, increases in bonuses occur of such proportion as to make
up for ground lost in the lean years.''
   He is convinced that if there were no lean years total incomes
would be smaller. But, he observes, lean years set the foundation
for subsequent large bonuses.
   He maintains ``there is no doubt in my mind and in minds of many
chief executives I have advised that you could pay one-half the
salaries and bonuses that America pays to corporate officers and
still get competent management.''
   The problem is that no one company can make the cuts and
survive. ``It has to be across the board,'' and that might mean a
national conference of chiefs to decide on controls, a prospect he
does not think will take place.
   Illustrating the difficulty in making changes, General Motors
last year announced that future bonuses would be tied to long-term
performance. One year later it contradicted itself, announcing big
short-term bonuses.
   While growing as a public relations problem, he believes the
rising incomes have not yet reached a critical stage in terms of
public concern, but that they will. The totals will grow swiftly as
the amounts involved are compounded.
   And no one company, he says, has access to the ``stop'' button.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs April 21</NOTE>
