<1ST_LINE>s i BC-France-Election Adv24   04-20 1020</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-France-Election, Adv 24,1046</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 24, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>French Presidential Campaign Boils Down To Two-Way Race</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Sunday in 2nd graf is April 24. An accompanying story is
BC-France-Thumbnails, b0512.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The campaign for France's presidential election has
boiled down to a two-way contest: President Francois Mitterrand,
the Socialist turned centrist, against Premier Jacques Chirac, a
smoothed-over conservative banking on his record.
   Seven other candidates are running in the first round of the
election Sunday, but none appear to have a realistic chance of
making it to the runoff May 8 between the top two vote-getters.
   With polls indicating the 71-year-old Mitterrand will easily win
the first round, the contest likely to gain most attention is that
between Chirac, 55, and another conservative, former Premier
Raymond Barre, 64, for second place and a trip to the runoff.
   The wildcard is Jean-Marie Le Pen, leader of the extreme right
National Front whose score may upset predictions.
   All have appealed to the center in their campaigns.
   Abandoning most of his Socialist rhetoric, Mitterrand says that
if he wins a second seven-year term he will try to form a new
``presidential majority'' in the present conservative National
Assembly. To do that, he would have to win over wavering
center-right deputies. Otherwise, he says, he will dissolve the
National Assembly and call new legislative elections.
   Chirac says he too will keep the present National Assembly,
where he has a slim three-seat majority, but would ask his new
premier to enlarge the Cabinet to encompass more of the center.
   Polls indicate the French have grown weary of the ideological
right-left wrangling that has characterized politics since Charles
de Gaulle established the Fifth Republic 30 years ago.
   Many are satisfied with the current ``cohabitation'' of a
leftist president (Mitterrand) and rightist premier (Chirac)
created by the right's victory in the 1986 parlimentary elections.
   The polls indicate Mitterrand will defeat either Chirac or Barre
in the runoff May 8, although his margin of victory has shrunk from
as much as 10 percent to as little as 4 percent, depending on the
poll.
   One survey indicated 52 percent of the voters would like to see
some of the current rightist leaders take part in a Mitterrand
government, and 63 percent feel that Socialists should participate
in a Chirac or Barre Cabinet.
   The candidates seem to be listening.
   Former Foreign Minister Roland Dumas, a Socialist and friend of
the president, said recently: ``The election is going to
redistribute the whole political landscape. It's like the
Shakespeare play `Macbeth,' the trees are going to move.''
   On issues, however, indications are that few voters expect any
startling changes, no matter who wins.
   In laying out his platform, Mitterrand proposed only two
concrete ideas: reimposing the wealth tax and reducing the
presidential term to five years.
   The wealth tax, affecting France's 100,000 richest people, is an
old idea, promulgated by the Socialists in 1981 and repealed by the
conservatives in 1986. The five-year term was floated by former
President Valery Giscard d'Estaing last year. It incited little
enthusiam on the right or left.
   Mitterrand, who has carefully nurture$ an image as the wise
grandfather above the daily political slogging, stuck to
generalities in his short campaign. His objectives in domestic
policy focus on modernizing business and agriculture to make them
more competitive and to giving priority to education, professional
training and research. His foreign policy objectives aim at what he
calls the ``construction of Europe'' and ``reducing the gap that
separates rich and poor countries.''
   Chirac, who is president of the neo-Gaullist Rally for the
Republic, also focuses on economic themes and tries to stick the
Socialist label firmly on Mitterrand's back.
   ``From 1981 until 1986, under the empire of the Socialists, our
country fell five years behind,'' Chirac said during the campaign.
``Make no mistake, socialism today, even if it doesn't want to use
the name, is not any the less dangerous.''
   Barre, an economics professor, likes to stress that he is a
member of no political party, though he is supported by the
center-right Union for French Democracy, a part of Chirac's
governing coalition.
   Of all the candidates, he has proposed the most detailed
program, a $23-billion plan for measures that would include
strengthening education, fiscal reform, investment aid to help
create jobs and a guaranteed income for the unemployed. He is vague
on where the money will come from.
   Then there is the 59-year-old Le Pen, vilified by all political
leaders but nonetheless representing 10 to 12 percent of the vote.
   The left is contending that the right cannot win the election
without support from National Front voters backing Le Pen, who has
campaigned on a France-for-the-French theme and has railed against
immigrants, particularly Arabs from North Africa.
   Chirac does indeed need National Front votes, but has repeatedly
vowed he will never work a deal with Le Pen for his votes in the
runoff. The premier's chances depend very much on how much of the
extreme right vote he can collect in the second round and how many
of Barre's first-round voters he can entice.
   Some of Le Pen's supporters are disgruntled Communists unhappy
with their party's pro-immigrant stand. Analysts say many of them
will return to their natural leftist camp in the runoff, or
abstain. They also predict that about a third of Barre's centrist
supporters could end up in the Mitterrand column on May 8.
   Among the others on the ballot is Andre Lajoinie, 58, the
official candidate of the Communist Party, which once was a power
on the left representing nearly a quarter of the vote but now has
fallen on hard times.
   Adding to the Communists woes is the candidacy of Pierre Juquin,
58, expelled from the party last year after assailing what he
called the party's archaic structure and demanding party reform.
   At the bottom are Antoine Waechter, 39, an ecologist candidate
seeking to increase voter awareness about the environment; Arlette
Laguiller, 48, a Trotskyist making her third race, and Pierre
Boussel, 67, another Trotskyist.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 24</NOTE>
</DOC>
