<1ST_LINE>s i BC-France-Thumbnails Adv24   04-20 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-France-Thumbnails, Adv 24,0543</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 24, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Thumbnail Sketches of French Presidential Candidates</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-France-Election, b0511</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are brief sketches of the four pivotal
candidates in the first round of the French presidential elections
Sunday, April 24:
   
   FRANCOIS MITTERRAND, 71 _ He took office in 1981 in his third
run for the presidency, defeating Valery Giscard d'Estaing, the
incumbent conservative. His victory was followed by a Socialist
sweep in National Assembly elections the same year. After series of
costly spending measures early in his tenure, Mitterrand and his
Socialists reversed themselves and instituted austerity. The result
was a dropoff in Mitterrand's popularity _ from 60 percent early in
his term to 27 percent at mid-term. He has since moved from the
left to center-left, distancing himself from his party, and is
perceived by many to be above day-to-day politics. A life-long
politician, Mitterrand was first elected to the National Assembly
in 1946 and held 11 ministerial posts until 1958. He founded the
modern Socialist Party in 1971.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   JACQUES CHIRAC, 55 _ The premier since 1986 and mayor of Paris
since 1977, Chirac heads the conservative neo-Gaullist Rally for
the Republic party and is in his second presidential race. He was
eliminated in first round of voting in 1981, when Mitterrand
defeated Giscard d'Estaing. Chirac was first elected the the
National Assembly in 1967. From 1968 to 1974, he served in a series
of Cabinet posts, becoming premier under Giscard d'Estaing in 1974.
He resigned in 1976 after a dispute with the conservative
president. Chirac took over the Gaullist party in 1976. When an
alliance of conservatives and centrists won legislative elections
in 1986, by a three-seat margin, Mitterrand appointed Chirac
premier. Chirac advocates a free-market liberalism with emphasis on
improving economy by favoring business investment and tax breaks.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   RAYMOND BARRE, 64 _ This is the first presidential race for the
former professor of economics and former premier. Barre is a member
of no political party, but is supported by the center-right Union
for French Democracy. He entered government as the head of the
office of the minister for industry and commerce in 1959 and has
served on several commissions. He was appointed premier by Giscard
d'Estaing after Chirac's resignation in 1976 and stepped down from
that post after Mitterrand's election in 1981. He currently is as
member of the National Assembly.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   JEAN-MARIE LE PEN, 59 _ He is the leader of extreme right
National Front and this is his second presidential race. A former
Foreign Legionnaire and member of rightist groups since his student
days, he won just 0.75 percent of the vote in the 1974 presidential
race. Le Pen came to prominence with his party in the 1984
elections to the European Parliament, winning 10 percent of vote.
In 1986 legislative elections, his National Front won 35 seats in
the National Assembly and Le Pen became a political force, focusing
largely on his opposition to non-European immigration and on law
and order issues. He poses serious problems for Chirac and Barre,
who need rightist votes but can't be seen as approving Le Pen's
extremist views.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 24</NOTE>
