<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Amnesty-Calif Adv24   04-20 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Amnesty-Calif, Adv 24,0665</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 24, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Program's Success Depends on Viewpoint</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Immigration Amnesty</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MANNING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In Southern California, the year-long program
for illegal aliens is being hailed as a success by those running it
and bemoaned as a crippling blow by some industries in constant
need of cheap labor.
   ``It's been an incredible experience and I think very effective
_ especially our outreach,'' said Harold Ezell, Western region
commissioner for the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
   ``In March, we had everything from amnesty fairs to luaus for
Tongan people. We've sacrificed the lives of some 13 or 14 pigs for
the mission of amnesty.''
   But the INS program has hurt some businesses in Southern
California, particularly the garment industry, said Garth Ward,
president of the Garment Contractors Association of Southern
California Inc. and president of Fashion Sportswear Inc.
   Apparel manufacture is California's fifth largest industry and
the third largest in Southern California.
   ``Historically, we've had an almost unlimited supply of warm
bodies that were trainable. Now we have a very limited supply of
workers,'' Ward said.
   Illegal aliens who can prove they have lived in this country
continuously since Jan. 1, 1982, have until May 4 to apply for
amnesty.
   ``The saddest thing about the program is that it's going to
leave a lot of people without any protection whatever,'' said Josie
Gonzalez, a Los Angeles immigration attorney.
   ``The vast majority of people in California will remain
undocumented. The principal reason is they entered (the country)
too late. The second reason is they can't document their
residence,'' she said.
   Ward and Ms. Gonzalez said worker shortages within the garment
industry are the result of several factors.
   While as much as 70 percent of the labor pool doesn't qualify
for amnesty, Ms. Gonzalez said, ``those who do qualify often leave
for other kinds of jobs. Once they are not afraid of deportation,
they will look around for better jobs.''
   ``A year ago, I had 140 people. I hit a low of 80, and we are
hiring people with no experience and offering them $4 an hour and
going to $4.25 (the new state minimum wage) and higher in July,''
Ward said.
   Ezell's region, with 36 offices in California, Arizona, Nevada,
Hawaii and Guam, is processing 5,400 applications a day this month,
compared to 1,200 applications a day in December.
   ``These are big numbers. We're going full bore,'' Ezell said.
   Ezell objects to any extension of the application deadline, as
proposed by Congress. But Ms. Gonzalez, Archbishop Roger Mahony of
the Los Angeles Roman Catholic Archdiocese and Bernard Brown,
president of the Coalition of Apparel Industries in California,
believe more time is needed.
   ``Some of the things they are doing at the last minute should
have been done early on,'' Brown said. ``There wasn't enough
information given to these people. A lot of these people don't know
if they can be documented or not.''
   Mahony argues for a one-year-extension to allow ``the
potentially eligible population time to learn of the policy
adjustments, modifications and clarifications that INS has made, .
.. to resolve issues affecting eligibility presently being
litigated, and to give the application population a reasonable
chance to (acquire) the proofs necessary and the fees.''
   But Ezell pointed out the program was designed to be
self-funding. ``We have broken even so far,'' he said. ``Can you
guarantee you can produce 300,000 more people for six more months
or do you think the taxpayers should come up with $30 million or
$40 million more to fund it for another six months?
   ``There's no need for that extension, any more than an extension
on the November elections or filing of income tax. ...
Procrastination is one of the major problems of those who haven't
filed yet,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 24</NOTE>
</DOC>
