<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 1401EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Amnesty-NewYork Adv24   04-20 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Amnesty-New York, Adv 24,0697</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 24, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Cheap Labor Harder to Come By These Days</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Immigration Amnesty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sign adjacent to an employment agency in a
grimy corridor full of job shops reads ``lava platos'' and offers
$200 to $250 a week ``and cuarto comida'' _ room and board.
   But if you want that dishwashing job, you have to have a green
card. The new immigration law is changing the way staffing patterns
of New York restaurants, heretofore heavily dependent on the labor
of illegal aliens.
   ``If you go to the restaurants, always they ask for the card,''
said Ruben Roldan, 36, an unemployed short-order cook and Mexican
immigrant who has been in and out of this country since 1973.
   ``I think it's going to be a big problem for people,'' he said
in a blend of Spanish and English as he stood next to the card case
outside the Apollo employment agency, one flight up from
Manhattan's bustling, gritty 14th Street.
   The Apollo's manager, Mike Melik, leaned against the case and
eyed a prospective client. ``You have a green card?'' he asked. The
man nodded yes, and they disappeared inside.
   ``I have to ask'' because of the new immigration law requiring
proof of citizenship or legal residence for all workers, Melik said
later.
   If the answer is yes, ``we see what kind of job'' is available,
he said. ``If it's no, we try to help them to be legal. I think
plenty don't have the card.''
   Under the law, employers must be prepared to prove their workers
live here legally. Employers who knowingly hire illegal aliens face
jail terms of up to six months and $10,000 fines.
   Immigration and Naturalization Service officials say they will
begin imposing penalties June 1.
   The law also provides amnesty to aliens who arrived in the
United States before 1982 _ if they apply by May 4. In New York, as
elsewhere, the results of the amnesty offer have been
disappointing, officials said.
   Jack Byrnes, chief legalization officer for the New York INS
district, said that as of March 25, 63,000 applications for amnesty
had been filed. Officials had expected 300,000 applications from
New York City, Long Island and seven upstate counties.
   Only 12,600 of the applications came from workers in service
jobs, a fraction of the region's illegal restaurant and hotel
workers. That leaves the city's restaurants in a quandary.
   ``One fellow in particular told me if he can't get his help
legally, he may close up shop. It's very difficult to get Americans
to take these positions,'' said Jeffrey Margolis, an immigration
lawyer who has run seminars about the law for one of his clients,
the New York State Restaurant Owners Association.
   ``A lot of people said that without `Juan,' we couldn't be as
successful as we are,'' Margolis added. ``Here's the kind of
employment that does not require an advanced degree, does not
require fluency in a language and requires someone who will work
hard for low wages.''
   Albert, a worker at World Employment who declined to give his
last name, said, ``A lot of people come in here without papers and
there's no way in the world we're going to send them to jobs
without them.''
   He said about 25 percent of those seeking jobs lacked documents.
They come from places like Senegal, South America, Trinidad and
Jamaica.
   ``Five minutes ago, I spoke to a Spanish guy. I had a great job
for him, but he didn't have a Social Security card or a green
card,'' Albert said. ``He acted disappointed. He knows that's the
law.''
   Attorney Ned Bassen, on the other hand, said the two dozen
members of the Restaurant League he represented had reported few
such problems.
   ``It may be far too early to determine whether restaurants are
going to have problems and what the impact is going to be,'' Bassen
said. ``It's going to take a while before the law is in full
swing.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 24</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880420-0272 </DOCNO>
