<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Several of the nation's largest banking companies _ Citicorp,
Bankers Trust New York Corp., Wells Fargo & Co., Bank of Boston
Corp. and Mellon Bank Corp. _ reported an increase in their first
quarter profits.
   Analysts said Tuesday that the results, with the exception of
Bankers Trust, were better than expected, and showed the banks were
off to a positive start after suffering losses or reduced earnings
in 1987 due to the Third World debt problem.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lee Iacocca earned nearly $18
million last year in salary, bonuses and exercised stock options,
Chrysler Corp. says.
   Iacocca's 1987 earnings of $17.9 million included nearly $13.5
million by exercising stock options granted earlier in the decade,
when Chrysler's stock was worth a fraction of its present value,
the company disclosed Tuesday.
   Meanwhile, Chrysler's chief labor negotiator said the company
wants to cut costs by setting a minimum age for workers taking
early retirement and seeks union leaders' support for flexible work
agreements.
   UAW Vice President Marc Stepp refused to comment on any specific
proposals.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inspectors have examined almost all of Eastern
Airlines' 267 jets and found most in compliance with safety rules,
although 43 planes were removed from service to correct problems,
the Federal Aviation Administration says.
   The FAA said Tuesday the 508 inspections at airports around the
country have covered all but 11 of Eastern's planes, some of the
aircraft three or four times. In 33 of the cases, flights were
delayed because problems had to be corrected, said an agency
spokesman.
