   Unreasonable fear of AIDS could cause a
substantial disruption of the workplace unless employees are
educated about how to deal with co-workers who have the fatal
disease, according to a new survey.
   The survey, released Tuesday by the American Red Cross, said
that of 2,000 employees questioned across the country, 42 percent
said they would not work with anyone who has AIDS. Twenty-nine
percent said they felt so strongly about it that they would quit
their jobs before working with an AIDS patient.
