<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Futures Prices Fade After Monday's Runup On Persian Gulf Fighting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Profit-taking and technical factors have sent
oil futures tumbling, continuing a price slide that began following
an Monday's short-lived rally sparked by Persian Gulf combat.
   Contracts for May delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark U.S. crude, closed down 49 cents at $18.03 per barrel in
Tuesday's trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Among refined products, May contracts for wholesale unleaded
gasoline ended at 52.14 cents per gallon, down 1.16 cents, while
wholesale heating oil contracts closed at 49.68 cents per gallon,
off 0.82 cent.
   Analysts said traders grew increasingly bearish as prices failed
to bounce back from Monday's lows.
   Prices had surged early Monday amid reports that U.S. Navy
vessels destroyed two offshore Iranian oil platforms, sunk an
Iranian patrol boat and bombed two Iranian navy frigates, while
Iran had fired on at least two U.S. vessels.
   Nervous traders rushed to buy futures because of uncertainty
over the fighting's ultimate impact on Persian Gulf shipments.
   But by midday Monday the attacks ceased, and the tide turned.
After the May crude contract _ which had leaped 55 cents to $18.92
_ failed to move higher, sellers took over and cut the gain to 15
cents by the close.
   On Tuesday, that downward trend continued throughout the day.
   Donald Morton, an analyst at the Boston office of
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., called Monday's early rally ``a
one-time deal, a Monday-morning panic-type situation.''
   ``The market has more than likely seen its top,'' he said.
</TEXT>
