<1ST_LINE>r f PM-DigitalComputers     04-20 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Digital Computers,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DEC Unveils New Mid-Range VAX Computers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Digital Equipment Corp.'s new line of mid-range
computers offers a significant price performance increase and
should intensify competition with rival International Business
Machines Corp., industry analysts say.
   Digital, looking to bounce back after reporting flat earnings
for its latest quarter, on Tuesday introduced its second line of
new systems in the last two months.
   ``It's a good move for DEC,'' said Bruce Watts, an analyst with
Needham & Co. ``It was time for them to upgrade their mid-range of
systems.''
   Digital officials said the new VAX 6200 series is designed to
compete with IBM's existing 9370 and 4381 computer.
   ``It's partly intended to place them in a strongly competitive
position when IBM announces its code-named Silverlake products this
summer,'' Watts said. ``DEC is getting their products out into the
market first in order to prevent IBM from taking customers away.''
   Digital, based in Maynard, Mass., is the world's second-largest
computer company and considered the industry leader in
mid-performance range computers.
   The announcement came one week after Digital reported a 0.8
percent decrease in profits for the latest quarter while IBM
announced a 16.3 percent rise, reversing a two-year trend in the
battle between the companies.
   Digital stock rose 12{ cents to $101.12{ a share in composite
New York Stock Exchange trading Tuesday.
   The new computers, which will cost between $131,600 and
$653,200, will be available immediately, Digital said.
   Digital last month introduced several mainframe computers in its
VAX 8800 series in a direct challenge to IBM.
   Sonny Monosson, a Boston-based independent analyst, said the new
series provides high performance and processing capacity for a low
price.
   ``I think this price performance is significant,'' he said.
``IBM and (Digital) are competing and this is a good price
performance.''
   Monosson said the competition between the two giants could have
a side effect on smaller companies in the mid-range computer
market, such as Prime Computer and Data General Inc.
   ``The byproduct of all this IBM-DEC competition is going to hurt
all the other vendors,'' he said.
   The company said the single-processor 6210 computer provides 2.8
times the performance of its VAX 11@780 system. The system can
accommodate up to four processors at once.
   Upgrades will cost between $100,200 and $173,500, Digital said.
</TEXT>
