<HEAD>Sears To Test Free-Standing Auto Centers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co., which is acquiring
Western Auto Supply Co., will test a further expansion of its
automotive operations with a new chain of free-standing auto
service centers, according to a company spokesman.
   The free-standing centers generally will be smaller than those
attached to 797 Sears stores but will offer a similar array of
services, including oil changes, tire installation and suspension
repairs, spokesman Gordon Jones said Tuesday.
   Specific dates, numbers of stores and locations have not been
determined, Jones said. The centers will carry the Sears name, he
said.
   ``The purpose of this test is to appeal to a broader range of
motorist customers,'' he said.
   The Chicago Sun-Times reported Tuesday that Sears, the nation's
largest retailer, would open 50 to 100 of the new outlets annually,
each about 5,000 square feet in size with up to six service bays.
The newspaper attributed the information to retail sources it did
not identify.
   Industry analysts said the free-standing centers would
complement Sears' acquisition of Kansas City, Mo.-based Western
Auto, which Sears said last month it would acquire in a $402
million deal.
   ``It's a good fit with Western Auto,'' said Don Wampach of
Oberweis Securities. ``It could tie those two operations together.''
   Wampach said there was room for growth in the auto-care market,
especially with K mart, the nation's No. 2 retailer, no longer
including auto service bays in its new stores.
</TEXT>
