<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoTalks Bjt   04-20 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Talks, Bjt,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler Seeks Minimum Age for Early Retirement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Auto Workers negotiators will
not give up ground the union has won in past contracts, a top UAW
official said after Chrysler Corp. proposed limiting the age at
which workers may get early retirement benefits.
   ``We aren't taking any concessions...we aren't going to tolerate
any takeaways,'' UAW Vice President Marc Stepp said Tuesday.
   The union and the nation's third-largest automaker entered their
third day of talks today over a contract covering about 66,000
active and laid-off workers in 15 states and 65,000 retirees.
   Negotiators attempting to fit to Chrysler an industry pattern
contract established last fall at General Motors Corp. and Ford
Motor Co.
   Stepp declined to comment further on Chrysler contract proposals
presented Tuesday, including the cost-cutting early retirement
changes that are expected to meet opposition from labor.
   UAW workers won the right to retire early after 30 years of
service during General Motors Corp. talks in 1970 after a 69-day
strike. The right was limited to workers 58 or older, with the
minimum age lowered to 56 in 1972.
   But the age minimum was eliminated in 1973 after a nine-day
strike against Chrysler and workers are not expected to accept a
floor on early retirement easily.
   Anthony St. John, the Chrysler vice president who is the
automaker's chief negotiator, said Chrysler wanted the minimum
early retirement age and union support for flexible work agreements
_ both changes from the pattern contract, because:
   _Chrysler is smaller than GM and Ford so its costs to produce
each car and truck are higher. St. John estimated the pattern
contract would cost Chrysler $3 to $3.50 more an hour than it costs
GM and 50 cents more an hour than it costs Ford.
   _Chrysler's work force is aging rapidly, with an average age o
44. It has only 1.1 active workers supporting each retiree.
   _Chrysler doesn't need to trim its work force as much as GM and
Ford and would rather keep its already trained workers on the job
during more of their prime. Under so-called ``30-and-out''
retirements, a worker who entered the factory at age 18 can retire
at age 48 and receive $1,350 a month in pension payments.
   St. John said Chrysler's new proposal would set a minimum age
such as 55 for 30-and-out retirements.
   ``We need to overcome those natural disadvantages by enhancing
our ability to compete with them as well as the transplants and the
foreign competition,'' St. John said. The so-called transplants are
Japanese-owned factories in the United States, which by 1990 will
be capable of producing at least 2.5 million vehicles annually.
   UAW and Chrysler officials expect to complete a new contract in
two to three weeks. If they are successful, the new contract will
replace the old three-year pact before its scheduled Sept. 14
expiration.
   Chrysler also wants UAW leaders to support the company's push
for Modern Operating Agreements, or plant contracts that organize
workers into teams and give the company flexibility in using
workers.
   Six plants have adopted MOAs and Chrysler wants similar
agreements at all its other plants. But many workers believe the
team concept, which reduces the need for workers who fill in for
absentees, inspect products and repair others' mistakes, reduces
job security.
   Most MOAs have been adopted under threat of a plant closing or
loss of work to other plants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
