<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Japan-Markets     04-20 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also running on general news wires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell back today against the
Japanese yen in Tokyo, while stock prices made a healthy rebound.
   The dollar finished at 123.90 yen, down 0.47 yen from its close
of 124.37 yen Tuesday. It had opened the day at 124.08 yen and
fluctuated between 123.85 yen and 124.09 yen.
   ``The market was quiet and the dollar traded in a narrow range
throughout the day,'' said Michiko Kawai of the Bank of Tokyo.
   Selling pressure was not strong as participants were nervous
about intervention by the Bank of Japan, she said.
   Traders said the central bank bought a modest amount of dollars
during morning trade. The bank does not officially comment on its
market activity.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
issues, a modest 14.45-point loser Tuesday, gained 207.09 points,
or 0.77 percent, to end the day at 26,864.09.
   ``The setback during the past three trading days made share
prices reasonable for investors,'' said an official of a major
securities company, who demanded anonymity.
   The Nikkei index lost 454.35 points between last Friday and
Tuesday.
   ``The stabilized U.S. dollar and firmness on Wall Street also
made investors optimistic,'' the brokerage official said, adding
that the overnight easing in New York was not seen in Tokyo as a
loss of its strength.
   The market also got a boost from the perception among many
investors that Japan's major brokerages will support the market any
time the Nikkei index fall too far from the 27,000-point level,
traders said.
   Trading was moderately active with volume of the first section
trade at 1 billion shares, up from 600 million shares Tuesday.
Advacing issues outpaced decliners 595 to 305, while 156 issues
were unchanged.
   Steels, electricals and autos were popular. Drugs, foodstuffs
and shippings rose. Losers include oils, nonferrous metals and some
of the constructions.
</TEXT>
