<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Recall,0149</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Recalling '84 Ranger, Bronco II Trucks, EPA Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. is recalling about 106,000 1984
Ranger and Bronco II trucks to bring their emissions control
systems into compliance with federal regulations, the government
and Ford said.
   The Environmental Protection Agency said Tuesday the recall
affects only the trucks with 2.8-liter engines and automatic
transmissions. California trucks, which are built to meet different
emissions standards, are not involved.
   The EPA said its tests had discovered the trucks' exhausts put
out hydrocarbons and carbon monoxide in excess of federal
regulations, but the agency was unable to identify a defective
component or part failure as the cause.
   ``Ford has agreed to adjust the choke and ignition timing to new
specifications and install new carburetor metering jets to bring
the trucks into compliance with the standards,'' the EPA said.
</TEXT>
