<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru   04-20 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Housing Starts Up; Stocks Decline</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: grafs 1-5 new to UPDATE with consumer prices report; picks up
2nd graf pvs: The department ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices, propelled by a record rise in clothing costs,
shot up 0.5 percent in March, the biggest increase since January
1987, the Labor Department said today.
   The overall gain _ amounting to 6.4 percent on an annual basis _
seemed sure to further economists' concerns that inflation may be
rebounding.
   Besides the 2.0 percent jump in apparel costs, retail prices
were also driven upward by a 0.4 percent gain in gasoline costs,
the first rise since August, and a 0.3 percent hike in food prices.
   Taken together, clothing, food and transportation price
increases accounted for half the March jump, which was more than
double the 0.2 percent gain of February.
   But in the housing sector, a sharp rise in construction of
single-family homes in March more than offset a decline in
apartment construction, according to the Commerce Department.
   The department reported Tuesday that housing starts rose 1.9
percent overall to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.54
million units in March after a 9.6 percent advance in February.
   The report didn't help the stock market, which finished
generally lower after a daylong rally faded.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 blue-chip stocks finished down 8.62
at 1,999.50, after being up by 32 points at midafternoon. Most
broader market indices also fell.
   Mark Obrinsky, an economist with the U.S. League of Savings
Institutions, said the back-to-back rises in housing starts
indicated the housing industry has recovered from its slump in
December and January.
   Housing starts plummeted 15.8 percent in December and drifted
another 1.2 percent lower in January. Analysts attributed the
decline to builders' fears that the October stock market crash
would dampen home buying and to the pre-crash buildup in mortgage
interest rates.
   ``Whatever problems there might have been in the worst of the
winter months, housing seems to have recovered pretty much,''
Obrinsky said. ``It's not going to be a boom year for housing, but
the decline from last year should be pretty moderate.''
   Housing construction hit an eight-year high of 1.81 million
units in 1986 and fell 10 percent in 1987. Analysts are projecting
another 4 percent to 8 percent decline this year.
   Rates for 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages, which shot up above
11.5 percent before the stock market crash, dipped below 10 percent
in February and March before rising to 10.19 percent last week.
Economists are projecting rates of about 11 percent by the end of
the year.
   The strength in starts last month came in construction of
single-family housing, which rose 7.1 percent to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 1.18 million units after an even stronger
8.9 percent climb in February.
   Construction of multi-family units fell 12.3 percent to an
annual rate of 358,000 units. The construction of buildings with
five or more units was at its lowest rate since June 1982, during
the last recession.
   Apartment construction has been slumping because the new tax law
passed in 1986 removed many of the tax shelter benefits of
investing in real estate. The old law also had encouraged
overbuilding in some areas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
