<2ND_LINE>BC-Chevron Loss,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Company Changing 1986 Profit to $1.4 Billion Loss; Hikes 1987
Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chevron Corp. is changing its 1986 profit
to a $1.4 billion loss and is raising its 1987 profit from $1
billion to $1.25 billion because of a routine bookkeeping
requirement.
   The oil company said on Tuesday the change was needed to meet
the provisions of the Statement of Financial Accounting Standards
No. 96 which was approved by the Accounting Standards Board last
December.
   Because of the change, the company had to restate its 1986 and
1987 earnings, resulting in the 1986 net loss and an increase in
1987 profits.
   The accounting change resulted from Chevron's 1984 acquisition
of Gulf Oil.
   The change led the company to post the $1.4 billion net loss for
1986 instead of the previously announced $715 million net profit
and a $1.25 billion profit for 1987 instead of the previous $1
billion.
</TEXT>
