<HEAD>Sulzberger Promoted to Deputy Publisher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also running on general news wires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arthur Ochs Sulzberger Jr. has been named deputy
publisher of The New York Times and Lance R. Primis has been named
president, the newspaper said in announcing a number of senior
management changes.
   Sulzberger, 36, had been assistant publisher since January 1987.
Primis, 41, had been executive vice president and general manager
since 1986.
   ``Arthur and Lance have proved themselves ready to take on
additional responsibilities,'' Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, Times
publisher and chairman and chief executive officer of The New York
Times Co., said in a statement Tuesday. ``Together with Max
Frankel, our executive editor, they will position the newspaper to
meet the challenges of tomorrow.''
   The younger Sulzberger is the publisher's son. He started at the
Times as a general assignment reporter in 1978 and has held a
series of positions in advertising, corporate planning and
production.
   Primis has worked at the Times since 1969 in a variety of sales
and executive posts in the advertising department, becoming senior
vice president for advertising in 1982.
   In other changes:
   _J.A. Riggs Jr., 54, was appointed executive vice president for
operations.
   _Russell T. Lewis, 40, will become senior vice president for
production.
   _Howard Bishow, 59, was named senior vice president for
operations.
   _John M. O'Brien, 45, was named senior vice president for
finance and human resources.
   _Elise J. Ross, 44, was named senior vice president for systems.
   _William L. Pollack, 32, was named director of circulation.
