<HEAD>Sumita Says U.S.-Japan Trade Balance Improving</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita warned
Wednesday that currency and financial markets should not overreact
to monthly U.S. trade data and stressed that the U.S. international
trade performance is still improving.
   Speaking at a regularly scheduled press conference, Sumita said
his assessment about the U.S. trade performance is based on a
sustained decline in its trade deficit in terms of volume.
   ``The U.S. trade balance should also show an improvement in
terms of value in the future,'' he added.
   Sumita also reiterated that there is no change in the dollar's
undertone, despite its recent volatility triggered by last week's
release of a disappointing $13.8 billion trade deficit for February.
