<1ST_LINE>u f PM-AT&TMeeting 3rdLd-Writethru   04-20 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AT&T Meeting, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AT&T Shareholders Meet In Wake Of Chairman's Death</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: rewrites throughout with more details from meeting.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone & Telegraph Co.'s board
elected President Robert E. Allen as chairman and chief executive
officer to succeed James E. Olson, who died from cancer two days
ago, the company said today.
   AT&T also announced today its profit rose 10.6 percent in the
first quarter to $492 million.
   Allen, 53, had been serving as acting chairman since Olson's
death and was considered a clear favorite to succeed the man who
guided AT&T out of the confusion surrounding the 1984 breakup of
the Bell System.
   The company said the board made its choice Tuesday night. The
board named no successor for Allen as president.
   ``I fully intend to continue leading AT&T on the course Jim set
out for us,'' Allen said in a statement. ``The other officers and I
concurred in the basic strategies Jim laid out in 1986 and they are
no less worthy today than they were at that time.''
   AT&T said its first-quarter profit equaled 46 cents per share,
up from $445 million, or 40 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue
rose 2.8 percent to $8.35 billion, from $8.12 billion a year
earlier.
   At a news conference, Allen said it was the company's ``firm
commitment'' to keep profits growing through 1988 at the first
quarter rate.
   He also promised to carry on the legacy of Olson.
   Allen was born in Missouri, grew up in Indiana and joined
Indiana Bell in 1957 after being graduated from Wabash College in
Indiana.
   He later worked in managerial posts there and at Bell of
Pennsylvania, Illinois Bell and the Chesapeake and Potomac
Telephone companies.
   He became executive vice president and chief financial officer
of AT&T in July 1983, and assumed the duties of AT&T president and
chief operating officer in September 1986.
   Olson died early Monday at age 62 of colon cancer, less than a
month after undergoing surgery for removal of a tumor from his
colon. He had been in the job 20 months.
   Olson was a forceful and tenacious leader. Allen conceded that
he is not perceived as a dynamic speaker but said he was working on
his delivery.
   Allen said his management ability and his willingness to
delegate responsibility were among his greatest strengths.
   ``First and foremost, I'm a team player,'' he said.
   In addition to receiving a report from Allen, shareholders were
to complete voting on a pair of resolutions regarding affirmative
action.
   A resolution urging AT&T to phase out its affirmative action
policies, which involve the hiring and promotion of minorities and
women, was made by the National Alliance, a white supremacist
organization.
   AT&T has urged shareholders to vote against the National
Alliance resolution. But it also has opposed a resolution urging
more affirmative action, introduced by Alex Tillman, a black
manager at Bell Laboratories.
   Members of a local of AT&T's largest union, the Communication
Workers of America, said they planned a ``rally against racism''
outside today's meeting.
   Speculation on who would succeed Allen as president centered on
Randall Tobias, 45, youngest of AT&T's vice chairman. The other
vice chairmen, Morris Tanenbaum, 59, and Charles Marshall, 58, were
expected to remain in their current posts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
