<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 1246EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-MergerSpoils Adv24   04-20 1025</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Merger Spoils, Adv 24,1056</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday April 24 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Losing Bidders Share in Division of Spoils</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To the victor belong the spoils, except in the
merger business these days, where even some losing bidders have
taken home a cut of the pot.
   The list of ``losers'' in some recent takeover battles includes
names like developer Donald Trump, appliance maker Whirlpool Corp.
and retailing giant R.H. Macy & Co.
   But it's not as if these players walked away empty-handed.
   Where vanquished raiders once faded from the scene with legal
scars or a cash consolation prize, players now are demanding assets
_ and getting them in the form of real estate, trademark rights,
even factories.
   It's all a matter of saving money and saving face. Winners don't
like running up the price of their acquisitions in a bidding war
any more than losers like getting shut out.
   So while some rivals might turn up their noses to the idea of
settling for half a loaf, other more creative competitors are
discovering that strategic advantage can be gained by carving up
the pie.
   ``I think we will see more (negotiated settlements) in larger
transactions where there are pieces that may be of different value
to different players,'' said Robert Willard, head of mergers and
acquisitions at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Trump's recent struggle with entertainer Merv Griffin over
Resorts International Inc. is a case in point. The New York
developer had been trying to take the gaming and casino concern
private since January and was less than genteel when Griffin began
publicly outlining his own strategy for acquiring the company.
   ``It got a little testy, indeed,'' said one observer involved in
the deal.
   But after weeks of public jousting, the two met in Trump's
office, where it took just a few hours to sketch out a deal.
Advisers and lawyers worked into the evening, and Trump and Griffin
were able to formalize the terms the next day by phone.
   ``Without that face-to-face meeting, there may well have been no
deal,'' said Jack Nusbaum, Trump's attorney, who called the
settlement a ``terrific result.''
   Trump got what he said he wanted all along _ the Taj Mahal
casino under construction in Atlantic City, N.J., and Griffin got
the rest of the company in part by purchasing Trump's controlling
interest for an undisclosed price.
   ``It's a rational way of resolving a situation rather than
having, at the end of the day, prolonged the uncertainty,'' one top
takeover lawyer said.
   In another case this past week, fabric maker West
Point-Pepperell Inc. and the investment firm Odyssey Partners sat
down at the bargaining table after waging an extended bidding war
for textile giant J.P. Stevens & Co.
   Hammering out an agreement to divvy up the goods is a quick way
to stop bids from escalating, even though boards of directors want
to keep the auction going for as long as possible to get the best
price for their shareholders.
   ``Boards are more reluctant to accept one offer and lock out
other bids,'' said Willard of Prudential-Bache.
   Rival bidders, however, have an interest in ``limiting their
exposure from paying a higher price. A negotiated settlement may
result in your accomplishing your objective at a lower net cost,''
noted one takeover expert.
   Michael Hoffman, senior vice president at Smith Barney, Harris
Upham & Co., said in some cases it is ``the ego factor (that) can
keep the bidding going to a point where the numbers don't make
sense.'' Many observers say that was the case in Canadian Robert
Campeau's battle for Federated Department Stores Inc.
   Like most protracted takeover scenarios, Campeau's skirmishes
with Macy occurred largely in the courtroom. Investment banking and
legal fees were estimated to total at least $200 million, involving
a battalion of more than 200 investment bankers and lawyers.
   ``It does make sense to reach an accommodation with a competing
bidder, otherwise you can litigate forever,'' said one lawyer
involved in a recent takeover who spoke on the condition of
anonymity.
   Campeau got the company for $6.6 billion, but an agreement to
sell two prized Federated operations to Macy for $1.1 billion
allowed both companies to walk away as winners.
   The alternative would have been for the bidders to ``just offer
a higher price, assuming it can be financed,'' said one lawyer
involved in the deal.``But Macy's and Campeau both are rather thin
in terms of financing.''
   The meeting of rival bidders, or their attempts to meet, happens
often, insiders say.
   ``Those sorts of feelers are thrown out quite frequently in
transactions that make business sense. The only difference is that
these companies have reached agreements,'' said one takeover lawyer.
   A negotiated agreement sometimes allows even the losing party to
say it achieved its goals. After splitting the spoils of the Roper
Corp. with General Electric Corp., Whirlpool Chairman David Whitwam
was quick to note that ``gaining the Roper brand name was one of
Whirlpool's key strategic objectives'' in going after the Georgia
appliance maker in the first place.
   Roper had signed a definitive agreement to be acquired by
Whirlpool before General Electric came on the scene. GE, known for
its deep pockets, ultimately offered $507 million, topping
Whirlpool's best bid by about $37 million.
   Whirlpool called GE shortly before its offer was about to
expire, and there was ``a very prompt resolution to the
situation,'' said one lawyer involved in the deal. Indeed, an
agreement was unveiled a day after the two companies said they were
holding discussions.
   Among the terms of the agreement, GE gets Roper and its
manufacturing operations, while Whirlpool will acquire rights to
the Roper name for major appliances.
   ``Part of it is how you portray the settlement to the world, and
everyone likes a winner,'' said one attorney involved in a recent
hostile bid.
   Willard of Prudential-Bache predicted that more takeover battles
would result in negotiated settlements, particularly those that
involve large, multi-dimensional targets.
   ``To the extent that the target keeps an auction going, there's
going to be more talking among rivals,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday April 24</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880420-0299 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 1251EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-OPECOutlook Adv24   04-20 0837</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-OPEC Outlook, Adv 24,0861</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday April 24 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Despite Parallels To 1986, Repeat Oil Crash Seen Unlikely</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ In the chaotic kitchen of global oil
politics, OPEC is cooking with some of the same ingredients it used
in 1985-86 to serve up history's most spectacular oil price flop.
   This time, however, the recipe includes some less explosive
elements, and experts say this means a remake of the price crash is
unlikely.
   For consumers, that means the retail price of gasoline and other
products refined from crude oil may be fairly steady this summer.
   New clues to the future direction of oil prices are expected to
emerge from two meetings of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries this week. On Tuesday, a five-man OPEC panel will meet
with representatives of several non-OPEC oil producing nations, and
on Thursday, all 13 cartel members are to open private talks.
   In some significant ways, OPEC's current struggle to stop
free-market forces from pushing down oil prices is unfolding much
as it did three years ago.
   The most obvious similarity is that OPEC once again is losing
the battle; the world price of oil has been below the cartel's
target level of $18 per 42-gallon barrel for much of this year.
   Beyond that, there are these parallels:
   _Saudi Arabia, the cartel's biggest producer, is going it alone.
   In mid-1985, Saudi King Fahd declared he no longer would let
Saudi production decline while other OPEC members were cheating on
price and output rules. This was the beginning of the end of OPEC's
attempts to regulate the world price. Last month, Fahd publicly
reasserted this policy, meaning, if effect, that the cartel had
again lost hope of single-handedly defending a fixed oil price.
   _Key OPEC members, including Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and Indonesia,
appear to have decided the cartel should stop fighting the price
decline by cutting production. When this feeling became widespread
in OPEC in late 1985, the result was a kind of anarchy. OPEC hoped
to win back part of its market share from non-OPEC producers, but
it did not expect the stunning price collapse that followed.
   This time, however, the memory of what happened in 1986 _ when
prices tumbled below $10 a barrel _ is likely to persuade the
cartel leadership to at least keep existing production controls in
place. Also, Iran is more aggressively fighting to retain the OPEC
strategy of cutting production.
   _OPEC is turning to independent producers for help in limiting
oil production.
   When prices were falling gradually in early 1985, OPEC saw that
its production cuts were too little. Unable or unwilling to cut
more, the cartel stepped up efforts to win restraint from non-OPEC
producers. Oil ministers from Mexico, Egypt, Malaysia and other
independent oil-producing nations attended several OPEC meetings in
1984-85 as observers, but the contacts yielded few results. By 1986
the outsiders had stopped coming to the OPEC meetings.
   This week OPEC is returning to this tactic. Its price-monitoring
committee _ comprised of the oil ministers of Saudi Arabia,
Nigeria, Venezuela, Algeria and Indonesia _ is to meet with
representatives of several non-OPEC producers, including Mexico and
Egypt, to press for cooperation in limiting production.
   In OPEC's view, all oil producers share a responsibility for
restraining production in order to keep prices high enough to
justify the level of investment needed to find oil supplies for the
future.
   Many non-OPEC countries don't agree. The world's two largest oil
producers, the Soviet Union and the United States, and major
producers Britain and Norway will not be attending the Vienna
meeting.
   The chances of OPEC and independent producers reaching agreement
any time soon on joint production cuts appear slim. In the event
they are unsuccessful the key question is: What will OPEC do next?
   In 1985, the cartel's response to getting a cold shoulder from
non-OPEC was to declare an unofficial ``price war.'' This time that
is much less likely to happen, given the severe financial wounds
that OPEC member countries have suffered in recent years.
   The odds of OPEC letting prices fall uncontrollably also are
lessened by the fact that prices, adjusted for inflation and the
depreciation of the U.S. dollar, already are as low as they were in
1986.
   The outlook for OPEC is further clouded by growing friction
within the cartel. Relations between the Saudis and Iranians have
been at a low ebb since riots in the Islamic holy city of Mecca, in
Saudi Arabia, last summer killed 402 people, including 275 Iranians.
   The political climate between Iran and its Persian Gulf
neighbors has worsened this spring with Iranian gunboat attacks on
United Arab Emirate shipping and oil facilities in the Gulf and the
hijacking of a Kuwait Airways plane by Shiite Moslem gunmen
demanding the release of 17 pro-Iranian terrorists held in Kuwait.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Robert Burns has covered OPEC for The Associated
Press for six years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday April 24</NOTE>
</DOC>
