<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Future Open Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade as concerns about dry weather
faded from the pits.
   Reports of unusually dry conditions in the central and northern
Plains gave the grain markets a scare Tuesday and drove prices up.
But those fears evaporated today on forecasts for rain in the
affected areas.
   ``Basically we had a little bit of a weather-type move yesterday
but traders who had been buying on that information are having
second thoughts this morning,'' said Walter Spilka, an analyst in
New York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   Spilka said it was early in the season to be worried about
weather damage to corn and soybeans. Planting of those crops is
barely underway.
   But analysts say the weather is likely to figure strongly in
price movement this season because of market fears about tight
supplies of corn and soybeans.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to } cent lower with May
at $3.13{ a bushel; corn was \ cent to { cent lower with May at
$2.05\ a bushel; oats were 1} cents to 2 cents lower with May at
$1.66{ a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to 3{ cents lower with May
at $6.69{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly higher while pork futures were mostly
lower in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .33 cent to .52 cent higher with April at 75.15
cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .22 cent higher with
April at 79.15 cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to .25 cent lower
with April at 44.45 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .17
cent lower to . 28 cent higher with May at 52.05 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
