<HEAD>Irving Says Banca Commerciale Revises Tender Offer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 13th graf, Irving said ... next year., to make it
`by about $1.60' sted `to about'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banca Commerciale Italiana, Italy's second
largest bank, has revised its cash tender bid for Irving Bank Corp.
by raising the price per share by $10 but lowering its proposed
stake in the company, both banks announced today.
   At the same time, Irving's plans to boost its annual dividend to
$4.50 a share from $2.42 next month were left in doubt after the
Federal Reserve objected to an increase to that level.
   The revised Banca Commerciale offer _ part of a complex
restructuring plan aimed at thwarting a hostile takeover bid by
Bank of New York Co. _ calls for the Italian bank to pay $75 a
share for 8.5 million shares, or 45 percent of Irving.
   The original proposal, announced on Monday, was for $65 a share
for 9.5 million shares, or about 51 percent of the outstanding
shares.
   Bank of New York is offering $15 in cash and 1.575 of its common
shares for each of Irving's roughly 18.1 million common shares
outstanding. It began its tender offer last month after receiving
approval from the Fed and New York State Banking Board.
   Bank of New York, which holds a 4.9 percent stake in Irving, is
also running a slate of 16 nominees to Irving's board of directors.
   Irving Chairman Joseph A. Rice said the amended offer would
provide shareholders with ``substantially more value than the offer
by the Bank of New York Co., and we urge our shareholders to reject
the BNY offer'' at the annual shareholders' meeting on Saturday.
   In a statement, Irving said Banca Commericiale ``believes that
the $75 per share cash prices of the revised offer better refelects
the overall value of IBC (Irving Bank Corp.) common stock through
market purchases.''
   But Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady maintained the revised
offer ``in our opinion is worse as a whole, is worse especially for
small sharehodlers.''
   ``It's a typical front-end load deal,'' he said. ``They're
putting a lot of stuff up front, and it's uncertain whether some of
the benefits ... will ever be realized.''
   In midday trading on the New York stock exchange, Irving stock
was unchanged at $60.75 a share while Bank of New York was up 12{
cents to $31.50.
   Irving's retructuring plan included the sale of some assets,
including its 50-story Wall Street headquarters, the increased
annual dividend and several cost-cutting mesures. In addition, a
special $10-a-share dividend would be payable to shareholders upon
completion of the Banca Commerciale deal.
   Irving said it hoped to raise net income by about $1.60 a share
in 1988 and $2.75 next year.
   Banca Commerciale, based in Milan, has assets of around $60
bilion and is Italy's seocnd largest bank, behind Banca Nazionale
del Lavoro. About 64 percent of Banca Commerciale is owned by the
giant state holding company Istituto per la Ricostruzione
Industriale.
   Irving's assets total about $24 billion.
</TEXT>
