<HEAD>Accounting Change Lifts Profit Despite Sales Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northrop Corp. said a tax accounting change
was responsible for more than tripling its first-quarter profit
despite a 3 percent sales decline.
   The aerospace contractor said Tuesday that its net income rose
to $139.6 million, or $2.97 a share, for the first three months of
the year from $40.6 million, or 87 cents a share, in the same
period last year.
   First-quarter sales fell to $1.37 billion from $1.41 billion in
1987.
   The latest results were helped by a tax accounting change that
increased earnings by $135.1 million, the company said.
   Northrop's operating profit in its aircraft, electronics and
services businesses fell 35 percent to $67.5 million from $103.6
million a year earlier.
   The reduction in sales was attributed to lower sales in the
company's electronic countermeasures product line and to a lower
level of customer-sponsored research and development.
   Nonetheless, the company reported increased deliveries of the
main fuselage section for the Boeing 747 jetliner and increased
sales in the MX Peacekeeper program.
   Northrop is the prime contractor on the B-2 Advanced Technology
Bomber, also known as the ``stealth bomber'' because of its
radar-evading characteristics.
   The company said the earnings were also depressed by an
unspecified amount as the company continued to spend on development
of a prototype of the Air Force's 21st century warplane, the
Advanced Tactical Fighter.
</TEXT>
