<HEAD>Bristol-Myers Reports 21 Percent Earnings Increase On Record
Quarterly Sales</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to include per-share earnings for 1987 quarter;
uppicks third graf: Sales were...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bristol-Myers Co.'s earnings jumped 21 percent
in the first quarter this year, boosted by record sales of the
company's drug and consumer products.
   Net income for the three months ended March 31 was $210.64
million, or 73 cents per share, compared to $173.88 million, or 61
cents per share, for the same quarter last year. The 1987 per-share
figure was adjusted to reflect a two-for-one stock split.
   Sales were up 13 percent from $1.35 billion to $1.52 billion,
which the company said was a record for its 101-year history.
   Chairman Richard L. Gelb said exchange rate fluctuations
accounted for about 1 percent of total sales growth.
   The New York-based company makes toiletries, drugs, hair care
and household products and nutritional and vitamin products.
