<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 1353EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Brokerages     04-20 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Brokerages,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shearson's First Quarter Earnings Up Slightly, Includes Hutton
Acquisition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Shearson Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc. said Wednesday that
first-quarter earnings rose slightly and revenue jumped 47 percent,
which the brokerage giant attributed partly to its post-crash
purchase of E.F. Hutton Group Inc.
   Wall Street analysts said the results were respectable,
considering the enormous trading losses suffered by many firms
after the Oct. 19 market collapse, including those of Hutton, which
was acquired late last year.
   The parent of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. said earnings totaled
$81 million for the three months ended March 31, up 2.6 percent
from the $78 million earned a year earlier.
   Per-share earnings were 81 cents, the company said. It did not
provide year-earlier per-share earnings because at that time the
stock was held by American Express Co. and wasn't sold publicly
until last May. Shearson has about 99 million shares and
equivalents outstanding.
   First-quarter revenues totaled $2.5 billion, up 47 percent from
$1.7 billion a year earlier. Much of the gain was derived from the
company's increased customer base as a result of the Hutton
acquisition.
   But first-quarter expenses also surged from $1.6 billion to $2.4
billion, a 51 percent gain that Shearson attributed partly to costs
associated with the incorporation of Hutton's staff and property
into its operations.
   Investment banking revenues more than doubled, from $172 million
to $357 million, reflecting strong merger and acquisition and
merchant banking activities, the company said.
   ``We are particularly pleased with the quarterly increase, given
the lower levels of investor participation in the financial markets
and the non-recurring charges associated with the Hutton acquisiton
that are being recognized in 1988,'' said Peter A. Cohen, chairman
and chief executive officer.
   Shearson's earnings were reported a day after several other
major brokerages reported sharply lower first-quarter results,
which they ascribed to a business slump following the crash.
   Perrin Long, a brokerage analyst at Lipper Analytical Securities
Corp. in New York, said one reason for the healthier results from
Shearson is ``that they're somewhat better managed.''
</TEXT>
