<1ST_LINE>u f AM-SpringerFeud Bjt   04-20 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Springer Feud, Bjt,0651</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Springer Heirs Win Power Struggle</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This stands for item on business news digest listed as
AM-Spring Feud</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heirs of the late newspaper magnate,
Axel Springer, have won a bitter power struggle to gain control of
the West German publishing empire, the company announced Wednesday.
   The Axel Springer company said Franz and Frieder Burda _ two
stockholders who control 25.9 percent of the company's shares _ had
sold their holdings to Springer's heirs.
   That gives the Springer family a 52 percent majority interest in
the concern, according to the statement, which was also issued in
the name of the Burda brothers.
   The Burdas' action marks a sharp turnaround and a defeat for Leo
Kirch, a wealthy film distributor who had been trying to increase
his power within the Springer company.
   ``We (the Springer heirs and the Burdas) feel we are doing
things along the lines Mr. Springer wanted before he died,'' Ernst
Cramer, adviser to the Springer family, said in a telephone
interview from his West Berlin office.
   Peter von Maydell, spokesman for the Burda brothers, also
confirmed the stock sale.
   The industry newspaper ``Neue Medien'' in Hamburg reported the
deal was worth 530 million marks (about $320 million). Maydell said
he could not confirm the reported price.
   Friede Springer, Axel Springer's widow, had been trying to block
Kirch's efforts to increase his power within the company. Mrs.
Springer and the Burdas are members of the company's supervisory
board, but Kirch is not.
   Powers within the Springer company have been squabbling since
the 73-year-old Axel Springer died on Sept. 22, 1985, leaving his
wife and two sons as direct heirs.
   Springer built a family-owned empire that in addition to Bild,
West Germany's largest newspaper, also includes a respected
conservative daily, Die Welt.
   Before his death, Axel Springer converted his empire into a
joint stock company.
   Under a complicated formula, Springer's heirs and executors were
given control of 26.1 percent of the company shares, the Burda
brothers 25.9 percent and Kirch 10 percent. The rest went to the
stock exchange.
   Last month, Kirch and the Burdas signed an agreement to pool
their Springer shares in an effort to gain control of a majority of
the company stock. Kirch said he had gained support from the
holders of a further 16 percent of Springer stock.
   Kirch and the Burdas said at the time they had concluded the
agreement as a means to ending the feuding at Springer and to
ensure the company had a good future.
   But the federal Cartel Office last week said Kirch and the
Burdas together had failed to come up with a majority of the shares.
   The Burdas, who own a string of printing plants, said in a
statement Wednesday they decided to sell their holdings to the
Springer family in the best interests of the company.
   ``After it became clear this solution (the attempt to form a
majority with Kirch) could not be realized, they (the Burdas) saw
no reason for that kind of partnership,'' the statement said.
   The Burdas decided to sell their holdings to the Springer heirs
because ``the future-oriented development of Axel Springer Verlag
has the highest importance,'' the statement said.
   Cramer, spokesman for the Springer family, said he saw no
contradiction between Axel Springer's wishes for his company and
the Burdas selling their stock to Springer's heirs.
   ``He divided the stocks, that is true. But that was not meant to
be against the family. He specified he wanted the stocks to be used
to keep up the strength of the company. We feel we are doing
that,'' said Cramer.
   Kirch's spokeswoman, Armgard von Burgsdorff, said from her
Munich office that Kirch would not comment on the Burdas' action.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
