<HEAD>Dollar Unchanged in Slow Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AM version is expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar remained little changed against
major foreign currencies Wednesday in lethargic European trading.
   Gold prices also steadied.
   Dealers said the threat of central bank intervention prevented
dealers from selling the dollar short.
   The dollar was unaffected by a 0.5 percent rise in the U.S.
consumer price index in March, which was in line with market
expectations, they said.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.8930, unchanged
from Tuesday's late rate.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell to a closing 123.90 Japanese yen from
124.37 yen at Tuesday's close. Later, in London, it edged up to
123.95 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday:
1.6635 West German marks, up from 1.6625; 1.3745 Swiss francs, down
from 1.3752; 5.6490 French francs, up from 5.6465; 1.8630 Dutch
guilders, down from 1.8642; 1,234.50 Italian lire, down from
1,235.75; and 1.2283 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2337.
   Gold bullion edged up in active trading in Zurich to a late bid
price of $457.50 from $457 bid late Tuesday. In London, the metal
was bid at $456.50, unchanged from Tuesday's late price.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose to a closing bid of $458.94
from $457.59 bid late Tuesday.
   Silver bullion was quoted at a late bid price of $6.46,
unchanged from Tuesday's late bid price.
</TEXT>
