<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-RalstonPurina     04-20 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Ralston Purina,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ralston Purina Reports Increase In Second-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ralston Purina Co. on Wednesday reported a 30.5
percent increase in second-quarter earnings due to improved sales
of human and pet foods.
   Net income for the second quarter was $93.3 million, or $1.35 a
share, on sales of $1.49 billion, compared with net income of $71.5
million, or 98 cents a share, on revenue of $1.44 billion for the
same period in 1987.
   Human and pet foods showed improved performance on higher
volumes and tuna on higher margins, company spokesman Patrick
Farrell said. In addition, Continental Baking showed improved
performance on higher bread and cake margins, Farrell said.
   Profit for Eveready Battery increased on strong international
volumes, although domestic battery profits were down slightly due
to increased advertising and promotion in a highly competitive
market, Farrell said.
   For the six-month period ending March 31, net income was $225.7
million, or $3.25 a share, on sales of $3.05 billion, compared to
$370.4 million, or $5 a share, on revenue of $2.95 billion for the
same period last year.
   Last year's first six months included a gain of $2.82 per share
on the sale of the company's domestic agricultural business.
   Excluding this gain and a loss on early retirement of debt from
last year's first-half results, earnings increased substantially
over the adjusted prior period results, benefiting from lower tax
rates and improved operating results.
   International agricultural products showed improved profits for
the six-month period on both improved margins and volumes.
</TEXT>
