<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Rockwell     04-20 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Rockwell ,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Earnings up Up 24 Pct. in 2nd Qtr.; Tax Adjustment Credited</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rockwell International Corp., the
aerospace, automotive and electronics firm, reported second-quarter
earnings rose 24 percent, but gave most of the credit to a tax
adjustment.
   Rockwell said Wednesday that profits rose to $218.4 million, or
81 cents per share, from $175.6 million, or 62 cents per share, in
the second quarter of 1987.
   Sales totaled $3 billion in the three months ended March 31,
down from $3.16 billion for the comparable period in 1987, largely
because of a 24 percent decline in sales of B1-B bombers. Rockwell
expects to deliver the 100th, and last, B1-B to the Air Force late
this month.
   The favorable tax adjustment resulted from deferral of income on
the B1-B program from previous years for tax purposes. The
earnings, deferred under the completed contract method, are taxed
at a lower rate under the new tax law.
   Donald R. Beall, chairman and chief executive officer, said
earnings excluding the tax adjustment were comparable with last
year.
   Earnings for the first half of the current year were $411.3
million, or $1.52 per share, up from $325 million, or $1.15 per
share in the first half of 1987. First-half revenues were $5.7
billion, off from $6 billion in the first half of last year.
</TEXT>
