<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-GeneralDynamics     04-20 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-General Dynamics,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Dynamics Reports Slight Increase In First-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense contractor General Dynamics on
Wednesday reported a slight increase in first-quarter earnings due
to its F-16 program.
   Net income for the first quarter was $105.7 million, or $2.52 a
share, on revenue of $2.4 billion, compared with net income of
$105.4 million, or $2.45 a share, on revenue of $2.3 billion for
the same period in 1987.
   Net earnings for the quarter reflect benefits of $20 million, or
48 cents per share, from tax law changes resulting in reductions of
deferred taxes. Comparable benefits for the first quarter in 1987
were $20 million, or 46 cents a share.
   ``Increased procurement on the F-16 program results in an
overall improvement in the government aerospace segment,'' said
Stanley C. Pace, chairman and chief executive officer. Pace said
the improvement was made despite continued investments in advanced
aircraft programs and lower production of the ground-launched
Cruise missile as that contract nears its scheduled completion
during 1988.
   Results of the company's submarine operations reflect increased
production activity on the Trident program, Pace said.
   Pace said San Juan, the first ship equipped with the new system,
is currently on sea trials and performing successfully.
   Pace said that Cessna remained profitable as a result of
continued cost containment efforts. In other lines of non-defense
business, he said the company continued to invest in production of
18 Atlas-Centaur Launch Vehicles.
   Backlog reached a record high, with funded backlog at $17.3
billion and total backlog at $24.9 billion. Comparable accounts in
1987 were $15.7 billion and $21.7 billion.
   The 1988 backlog includes recent contract awards for development
if the Navy's advanced tactical aircraft, construction of the 15th
Trident submarine, and the majority of fiscal year 1988
procurements of Standard and Sparrow missles, as well as a
multiyear contract for the Stinger missile.
</TEXT>
