<1ST_LINE>r f BC-JournalPlans     04-20 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Journal Plans,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dow Jones Plans Third Section of Wall Street Journal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Wall Street Journal will be published in
three sections rather than two starting in September in an effort
to make the newspaper more convenient for readers to use, the
chairman of Dow Jones & Co. said Wednesday.
   Warren H. Phillips, who is also chief executive of the company
that publishes the Journal, said ``coverage of market trends and
investment opportunities will be developed further, extended well
beyond the stock markets and organized in a separate third section
for easier access.''
   He also said price quotations will be made more readable and
unusual price or volume developments or trends will be pointed up
in new ways.
   The Journal has been published in two sections since June 1980.
   A spokesman for Dow Jones, Danforth Austin, said the addition of
a new section would not necessarily increase the number of pages in
the newspaper. He said the change was seen as a way to organize
coverage in a better fashion.
   Phillips disclosed the plans at the annual meeting of Dow Jones
shareholders.
</TEXT>
