<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-AmericanBrands     04-20 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-American Brands,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Brands Reports First Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Brands Inc. on Wednesday
reported a 15 percent jump in first-quarter earnings and announced
plans to sell its Andrew Jergens Co. subsidiary for an undisclosed
price.
   Earnings for the quarter totaled $150 million, or $1.40 a share,
compared with earnings of $131 million, or $1.15 million in the
year-ago quarter.
   The company attributed higher earnings per share in part to
stock repurchases. Including shares acquired in connection with the
company's acquisition of E-II Holdings Inc., 13 million shares have
been purchased to date.
   Sales during the period totaled $2.91 billion, up from $2.2
billion in the same period a year ago.
   American Brands Chairman and Chief Executive Officer William J.
Alley noted strong performances by the company's tobacco, distilled
spirits and financial services core businesses.
   The company's major brands include Lucky Strike, Pall Mall and
Tareyton cigarettes, Jim Beam bourbon and Windsor Canadian whiskey,
and the Franklin Life and Southland Life insurance companies.
   Separately, American Brands announced it sold its Jergens
subsidiary to Kao Corp. of America, a division of Kao Corp. of
Japan. American Brands said in December it planned to sell the
subsidiary.
   Kao manufactures soaps, detergents, hair care products,
disposable diapers and industrial chemicals. Jergens manufactures
hand and body lotions, soaps and other personal care products.
</TEXT>
