<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   04-20 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures closed lower Wednesday
on the Chicago Board of Trade _ soybeans sharply so _ as rain in
the Plains states washed away fears about weather damage to crops.
Wheat advanced slightly.
   Profit-taking took soybean prices down sharply near the close
but prices had trended lower throughout the session.
   The sell-off in the corn and beans followed two days of gains
triggered by fears that dry conditions in the northern Plains would
extend into the major corn-and-soybean regions of the Midwest.
Analysts said the worries were premature since corn and soybean
planting has only begun.
   ``I think the markets are going through their usual gyrations
this time of year,'' said Walter Spilka, an analyst in New York
with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. ``You get a brief rally on
weather information, then you get a little rain in the corn belt
and that puts some pressure on the markets just because they've
been up a little.''
   Wheat futures were supported by expectations of new export
business, analysts said.
   At the close, wheat was { cent to 2{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.15} a bushel; corn was 1 cent to
1{ cents lower with May at $2.04 a bushel; oats were 2 cents lower
to \ cent higher with May at $1.66{ a bushel; soybeans were 5{
cents to 6\ cents lower with May at $6.66{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
