<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Stevens     04-20 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stevens,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Word On Accord Between Bidders For Stevens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival bidders for J.P. Stevens & Co. had not
reached an agreement as of Wednesday in their $1.22 billion battle
to acquire the textile giant.
   Odyssey Partners, which has an agreement to acquire Stevens for
$1.22 billion, and rival bidder West-Point Pepperell Inc. said
Tuesday that they had begun discussing a possible cash buyout of
Stevens at $68.50 a share, the same price offered by Odyssey.
   A spokesman for Pepperell confirmed that those discussions were
taking place in New York. But he had not comment on whether a
resolution might be at hand.
   ``They haven't announced that they've stopped (negotiations),''
said David Kronfeld, who represents the West Point, Ga., textile
maker.
   Pepperell is bidding in conjunction with NTC Group, parent of
textile manufacturer Bibb Co. Pepperell has said it will sell half
of Stevens' bath lines and 20 percent of its sheet lines to NTC if
it is successful in the takeover.
   Analysts have speculated that fabric maker Pepperell and
Odyssey, an investment group, probably were working toward an
accord to split up Stevens' assets.
   Stevens' board of directors endorsed Odyssey's outstanding
$68.50-a-share tender offer last week. The board rejected
Pepperell's competing $67-a-share tender offer, which represented
the third round of bidding in the heated takeover contest.
   A spokesman for Stevens had no comment.
</TEXT>
