<2ND_LINE>AM-First City, Bjt,0760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abboud: First City To Make Profit</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HT4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new chairman of First City Bancorporation of
Texas Inc. said Wednesday he was confident the revitalized company
will make a profit its first year after a $1.6 billion federally
assisted reorganization plan is completed.
   ``First City's flag is flying high. This is the moment we've all
been waiting for,'' said Chicago investor A. Robert Abboud, the
company's new chairman and chief executive.
   Late Tuesday, after a day of completing the necessary paperwork,
the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. transferred $970 million to the
ailing bank, Abboud said.
   ``It wasn't the parting of the Red Sea, but it's close to it,''
he said. ``After a long night, we successfully completed the
transaction and obviously we're all pleased.''
   The bailout plan, the second largest such rescue in U.S.
history, also calls for a spinoff of $1.79 billion of poorly
performing assets and a $500 million infusion of capital raised
privately by a group headed Abboud.
   As part of the restructuring, First City obtained a revolving
line of credit with San Jacinto Savings Association of Houston as
the lead lender. San Jacinto Savings agreed to lend $68 million of
the initial $108 million First City needs to pay off its debt
holders.
   Abboud has predicted that the new First City, the state's
fourth-largest bank holding company, will make $74 million in its
first year, $104 million by its second year, and $119 million by
the third year.
   ``Certainly, the figues that have been put forward are those
that we're operating under,'' he said at a Wednesday news
conference.
   An analyst that follows First City, however, said Abboud is
being too optimistic.
   ``In our opinion, it is going to be difficult to meet the
forecasted loan growth assumptions,'' said Sandra Flannigan,
analyst with PaineWebber in Houston.
   First City last posted a profit during the second quarter of
1986. For 1987, the company posted a $1.1 billion loss. In a report
to the Securities and Exchange Commission filed last month, First
City said it expected to lose $43 million by the time the rescue
plan was completed.
   The rescue plan, implemented three months behind schedule, was
stalled by debt holders who were reluctant to tender their
securities for less than face value. The company originally had
wanted 90 percent participation but then lowered the threshold to
70 percent.
   By a Monday deadline, the company's sixth, only 67.5 percent, or
$152.4 million, of the bank's $225.8 million in bonds had been
tendered, Abboud said.
   ``We had hoped to achieve a target around 68 percent or
better,'' he said.
   ``The half-percent is something we will take on to the books of
the new First City and we will find it a challenge to take on that
particular differential. We would have been substantially closer,
but we had some withdrawals by savings and loans.''
   First City senior debt holders were offered 45 cents on the
dollar for their debt under the plan, while subordinated debt
holders were offered 35 cents.
   Bonds not tendered by the deadline could be worth as much as 100
cents on the dollar.
   Some investors who initially agreed to participate in a private
placement of new First City securities got cold feet and backed
out, observers said. But Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., a New York
investment company, guaranteed the sale of $100 million in the
placement, Abboud said.
   Abboud also said First City entered a 10-year agreement with
Electronic Data Systems Corp. to manage First City Services Corp.,
the company's data processing subsidiary that employs 400.
   ``This is not a sale. This is not a sale of a First City
company,'' Abboud said.
   First City, with 59 banks in Texas and one in South Dakota, grew
quickly during the Texas oil boom, but was hit hard by energy and
real estate losses when oil prices plummeted.
   Leadership of the 122-year institution will move from longtime
Houston banker James A. Elkins Jr. to Abboud, who has been working
as a consultant for the company since September for $1 and a $2.25
million expense account.
   The assistance plan is the second largest by the FDIC. The
federal agency pumped $4.5 billion to rescue Continental Illinois
Corp. of Chicago in 1984.
   Ownership of First City by existing shareholders will go from
100 percent to 2 percent once the deal is completed.
</TEXT>
