<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Railroads     04-20 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Railroads,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Pacific Profit Up 13 Pct.; Conrail Earnings Off</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Consolidated Rail Corp. reported a 44 percent drop in
first-quarter profit Wednesday, while Union Pacific Corp. said its
earnings increased 13 percent.
   Conrail blamed the decline on the loss of tax breaks when the
company was sold to public ownership by the government last year.
   The freight railroad, which is based in Philadelphia, reported
an after-tax profit of $48 million, or 69 cents per share, for the
first three months of the year. That was down from $86 million, or
$1.28 per share, in the same period of 1987, when Conrail was
sheltered from federal taxes by carrying forward losses incurred in
earlier years.
   Revenues rose 5.5 percent to $831 million from $788 million.
   The company said that discounting the previous tax break, its
earnings declined just 2 percent for the quarter.
   The tax advantage was canceled by federal legislation that
allowed Conrail to go public in a stock offering on March 26, 1987.
   First-quarter earnings in 1987 also were boosted by gains of $17
million from real estate sales.
   Union Pacific, which has its headquarters in New York, said it
earned $137.8 million, or $1.21 per share, up 13 percent from a net
of $121.9 million, or $1.07 per share, in 1987. Revenues rose to
$1.57 billion from $1.43 billion.
   The company said earnings were up at all its operations _ the
Union Pacific Railroad, oil and natural gas, real estate holdings
and overnight transportation.
</TEXT>
