<HEAD>Dun & Bradstreet Reports 15.4 Percent Rise in Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dun & Bradstreet Corp. reported Wednesday it
sold a record amount of business information during the first
quarter, pushing its profit up 15.4 percent from a year ago.
   The business information and services company reported after-tax
income for the January-March quarter of $114.03 million, or 75
cents per share, on revenue of $882.14 million. That compared to
earnings of $98.83 million, or 65 cents per share, on revenue of
$828.48 million in the same period a year earlier.
   The New company said business information service revenues grew
8.2 percent, while the publishing segment was up 3.4 percent and
marketing services rose 6.5 percent.
   Chairman Charles W. Moritz said future revenues are expected to
climb even more as Dun & Bradstreet completes the previously
announced acquisition of several companies.
   Subsidiaries of the company include Moody's Investors Service
and Nielsen Media Research, the television ratings service.
