<1ST_LINE>u f AM-LuckyStores     04-20 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lucky Stores,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lucky Seeks Alternatives to American Stores' Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Stores Co. declined comment
Wednesday on a report it will raise its bid from $45 to $50 a share
for Lucky Stores Inc., which said it is talking to other parties
about a possible sale of the supermarket chain.
   Mike Holt, spokesman for Salt Lake City-based American Stores,
said he would not comment on a report by all-business radio station
KMNY in Los Angeles quoting unnamed Lucky sources saying American
would raise its bid soon.
   Meanwhile, Dublin-based Lucky issued a statement that it is
``continuing to review a variety of alternatives to the pending $45
tender offer by American Stores with a view of providing Lucky
stockholders with greater value.''
   Holt responded with the comment, ``they've been saying that all
along.''
   However, Lucky also said for the first time it has had
discussions with ``a number of lending institutions with respect to
a possible leveraged recapitalization of the company.''
   None of the parties was named in the statement.
   Lucky's shares gained 50 cents Wednesday to $53.75 in composite
New York Stock Exchange trading.
   Lucky's board of directors has not made a decision to sell and
such a decision will be made ``only after a review of available
alternatives is completed,'' the statement said.
   The merger of Lucky and American Stores could create the
nation's largest supermarket chain.
   Lucky said earlier this month its board rejected the unsolicited
tender offer of $1.74 billion as ``inadequate'' and not in the best
interest of the company or its stockholders.
   The rejection came 17 months after Lucky derailed a hostile
takeover attempt by New York investor Asher Edelman.
</TEXT>
