<1ST_LINE>u f AM-StateIncomes 1stLd-Writethru   04-20 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-State Incomes, 1st Ld-Writethru,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Connecticut Leads Nation In Per Capita Income</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: CORRECTS last graf to show that per capita income fell in
Wyoming and Alaska.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Connecticut residents had the highest average
income in the nation last year, more than double the per capita
income of Mississippi residents, who had the lowest, the government
said Wednesday.
   The Commerce Department said that residents of Connecticut
earned $20,980 for every adult and child in 1987, an increase of
6.9 percent over 1986. Mississippi ranked last with a per capita
income of $10,204, a 5.2 percent increase over the previous year.
   New Jersey, with income of $20,067, ranked second and
Masschussetts, with income of $18,926, was third. The District of
Columbia, with income of $20,303, would have been second if it was
included in the rankings.
   Alaska, which took over the No.1 spot from Connecticut at the
start of the oil boom in 1973 and held it until 1985, fell to fifth
in 1987. Its average income actually fell 0.7 percent last year to
$17,886.
   Rounding out the top 10 were New York, Maryland, California, New
Hampshire, Illinois and Virginia.
   Seven of the 10 states with the lowest per capita income were in
the South. In addition to Mississippi, they were West Virginia,
Arkansas, Louisiana, Alabama, South Carolina and Kentucky. Utah,
New Mexico and Idaho _ energy and mining states _ were also in the
lowest 10.
   For the nation, per capita income averaged $15,340, a 4.8
percent increase over a year earlier. That was slower than the 5.2
percent growth rate during the previous year and the 6.1 percent
rate in 1985.
   When adjusted for inflation, which was 4.4 percent, 1987 income
growth was the smallest since the recession year of 1982.
   The state growth rates showed that the nation's bicoastal
economy _ the phenomena of a healthy economy in the Northeast and
California and a relatively weaker economy in states in between _
became more pronounced.
   New Englanders, boosted by jobs in high technology and military
industries, averaged $18,329, a 6.7 percent increase over 1986.
Income in the Mid-Atlantic states grew 6.0 percent to $17,538.
   The Southwest and Rocky Mountain states, plagued by economies
dependent on oil and mining, had the slowest growth rates. Per
capita income of $13,512 in the Southwest was only 2.2 percent
above 1986. Rocky Mountain states' average income of $13,631 was up
only 3.6 percent from the previous year.
   However, Rudolph E. DePass, an analyst with the Commerce
Department, noted that growth is accelerating from extremely low
levels in the battered Southwest and Rocky Mountain states, while
it is decelerating from higher levels elsewhere.
   In 1986, the growth rate had been 0.9 percent in the Southwest
and 3.5 percent in the Mountain states. In New England and
Mid-Atlantic states, growth rates were a booming 7.6 percent and
6.5 percent respectively.
   Wyoming was the only state, in addition to Alaska, in which
average income declined in 1987. It fell by 0.1 percent to $12,759,
but the shrinkage was not as bad as the 1.1 percent decline in 1986.
</TEXT>
