<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Airlines     04-20 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Airlines,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Airlines Parent Records Earnings Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The parent company of American Airlines Inc. reported Wednesday
its quarterly earnings more than tripled, fueled by improved market
conditions during the normally weak quarter.
   AMR Corp. reported net earnings of $68.4 million, or $1.12 per
share, for the first three months of 1988, up from $19.9 million,
or 34 cents per share, in the same quarter a year earlier.
   First-quarter revenue increased by 30.2 percent to $1.96
billion, vs. $1.5 billion in the same period a year ago.
   ``Normally, the first quarter is a period of weak traffic and
rather broad discounting. This year, we experienced both strong
demand and strong revenues,'' Chairman Robert L. Crandall said.
   The average amount of revenue per passenger mile increased by 11
percent from the prior year to 11.53 cents, while revenue passenger
miles jumped 21.5 percent.
   American, headquartered in the Dallas-Fort Worth area, serves
160 cities worldwide.
   Meanwhile, Air France, France's state-owned airline, said its
consolidated net income more than doubled last year to a record
$214 million from $100 million in 1986, but attributed most of the
increase to a change in accounting practices.
   On a comparable basis, it said, last year's net income would
have shown an increase of 72 percent, or $71.7 million.
   Air France said the improved earnings performance reflected a
14.6 percent rise in passenger traffic last year that boosted its
average load factor from 65.2 percent to 69.5 percent.
</TEXT>
