<HEAD>Former Brewery Executive Pleads Innocent To Kickback Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Anheuser-Busch Inc. executive indicted
in an alleged kickback scheme pleaded innocent to the charges
Wednesday in federal court.
   Joseph E. Martino, who was indicted last week along with another
former brewery executive, entered the plea before U.S. Magistrate
William Bahn.
   Bahn denied Martino's request for unrestricted travel while
under indictment. Martino, who went to work for the Miller Brewing
Co. in Milwaukee after being dismissed by Anheuser-Busch last year,
will be allowed to travel only to places pre-approved by the court,
Bahn said.
   Martino and Micheal A. Orloff, who pleaded innocent last week to
the charges against him, are both accused of taking illegal
payments for sales promotion business they sent to two St.
Louis-based companies.
   Both were indicted on federal charges of mail fraud, conspiracy
and filing false income tax returns. Martino also was charged with
eight counts of interstate transporation of fraudulenty obtained
securities.
   Martino was vice president of sales for Anheuser-Busch when he
was dismissed March 12, 1987, after an internal investigation by
the company. He is now on paid leave of absence from his job as
vice president of marketing at Miller ``in order to permit him to
pursue a proper and full defense in this situation,'' a spokesman
said.
   Orloff was vice president of Anheuser-Busch's wholesale
operations when he was fired.
</TEXT>
