<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Bonds     04-20 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bonds,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prices Post Advance for First Time in Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices finished higher Wednesday for the
first time in a week as the market overcame some early worries
about inflation.
   The Treasury's key 30-year bond, which has fallen $25 per $1,000
in face amount since last Thursday, rose \ point, or about $2.50.
   The bond's yield, which moves inversely to its price and is an
important signal of interest rate trends, slipped to 9 percent from
9.04 percent late Tuesday. A week ago the bond yielded 8.73 percent.
   Bond prices initially sagged after the Labor Department reported
a 0.5 percent jump in March consumer prices, the biggest increase
since January 1987. The advance was larger than most analysts had
expected and it drove bond prices lower because it provided
additional evidence that inflation may be accelerating. Bond
investors fear inflation because it erodes the value of their
holdings.
   But bond prices reversed course later in the day and headed
higher.
   William V. Sullivan Jr., director of money market research for
the investment firm Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., said the recent
decline in bond prices has been so quick and deep that some traders
felt it may have gone too far for the moment.
   He said some traders also saw that a major reason for the strong
consumer price growth in March was rising clothing costs, and
concluded the surge could be temporary.
   ``Without the rise in apparel costs, the CPI would have been up
by 0.4 percent or so and that is seen as being more manageable,''
Sullivan said.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, short-term
maturities edged up 1-32 point, intermediate maturities were up by
between [ point and \ point and 20-year issues rose ] point, the
financial information service Telerate Inc. reported.
   The movement of a point equals a change of $10 in the price of a
bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Merrill Lynch Daily Treasury Index, which measures price
movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with maturities of a
year or longer, rose 0.17 to 110.52. The Shearson Lehman Hutton
Daily Treasury Bond Index, which makes a similar measurement, rose
1.65 to 1,156.33.
   In corporate trading, industrials rose } point and utilities
rose \ point in moderate dealings.
   Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures
price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years
or longer, fell 0.37 to 278.20.
   Among tax-exempt municipal bonds, prices edged down [ point in
light trading.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose 2 basis points to 5.82
percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point.
Six-month bills rose 2 basis points to 6.24 percent but year bills
were unchanged at 6.62 percent.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 7} percent, up from 613-16 percent late Tuesday.
   Sullivan said it was unclear whether the rise in the funds rate
indicated a tightening of the Federal Reserve's money policy
because Wednesday was the end of a reserve reporting period for
banks. The short-term lending rate often rises sharply on such days
as financial institutions borrow to meet reserve requirements.
</TEXT>
