<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-GM Subsidiaries,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GMAC Earnings Fall, Hughes, EDS Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp.'s financing subsidiary
reported lower first-quarter earnings Wednesday, while the
automaker's computer and electronics units both posted sharply
higher profits.
   General Motors Acceptance Corp., GM Hughes Electronics Corp. and
Electronic Data Systems Corp. all report earnings separately from
GM, which was scheduled to release its own first-quarter results
Thursday.
   GMAC, the financial, insurance and mortgage unit, said net
income was down 26 percent in the quarter ended March 31 because of
a slimmer margin between the money it makes in interest and the
cost of obtaining funds.
   The subsidiary's net income was $354.4 million, down from $481.4
million in the first quarter of 1987. GMAC has no stock issue
separate from GM's, and thus no separate per-share earnings figure,
a spokesman said.
   GMAC's total earning assets were $94.7 billion, up 9 percent
from a year earlier. The company's average cost of borrowing rose
to 7.94 percent, up from 7.67 percent in the first quarter of 1987.
   Earnings at GM Hughes Electronics Corp., the auto and
electronics subsidiary, jumped 44 percent in the first quarter.
Earnings were $251.9 million, or 63 cents per share of GM Class H
common stock, up from $175.2 million, or 44 cents a share, in the
first quarter of 1987.
   Revenues at the company _ comprising Hughes Aircraft Co. and
Delco Electronics Corp. _ were unchanged at $2.7 billion. The
earnings jump was attributed to sale of part of Hughes' stock
holdings in Nippon Avionics Co. Ltd. and to an accounting change at
Delco.
   Earnings jumped 38 percent at Electronic Data Systems Corp.,
GM's Dallas-based computer and communications services company, on
the strength of government and private data processing contracts in
the United States and Europe.
   EDS had net income of $89.1 million, or 73 cents per share of GM
Class E common stock, on revenue of $1.12 billion, up from $64.6
million, or 53 cents a share, on revenue of $1.03 billion in
first-quarter 1987.
</TEXT>
