<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 1931EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Trade 1stLd-Writethru f0143 04-20 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0143,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Move to Drop Plant-Closings Plan as Trade Bill Nears House
Floor</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New throughout with plant closings provision in jeopardy</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration won a round in
skirmishing over trade legislation Wednesday, raising chances that
lawmakers might still drop plant-closings provisions believed
certain to draw a veto.
   ``It is my hope that through this motion we will be able to get
a trade bill that can actually be enacted into law,'' Minority
Leader Robert H. Michel, R-Ill., said following action in the House
Rules Committee.
   The panel granted Michel's request for a floor vote Friday on
whether to send the bill back to a House-Senate conference
committee with orders to strip out the controversial provisions
requiring employers to provide 60-day notice of all but the
smallest plant closings and large-scale layoffs.
   The Reagan administration has been threatening a presidential
veto over the plant-closings provision, and there are substantial
doubts about whether enough support exists to override such a veto.
   Lawmakers whose home districts are hungering for such other
provisions as repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil companies
and massive farm subsidies reportedly have been losing enthusiasm
for anything that would draw a veto.
   The measure's central provisions streamline the system under
which the United States imposes import curbs and takes other
actions to retaliate against trade violations and aid American
industries threatened by surges in foreign competition.
   If Michel wins his battle to send the measure back to the
conference committee, a floor vote on the bill itself, scheduled
for Thursday afternoon, in the House could be delayed.
   The Democratic-controlled Rules Committee was not obliged to
grant Michel's request for a vote to send the bill back to the
conference committee with instructions to strip out the
labor-backed plant-closings provisions.
   But Michel aide Joanna Schneider said she believed concern over
how a plant-closings veto could have affected the windfall profits
tax, the farm subsidies and a host of other narrow issues might
well have prompted lawmakers to scuttle the bill on the floor, even
without sending it back to committee.
   Rules Committee meetings are normally fairly quick but
Wednesday's action was delayed for hours because of Democratic
fears that granting Michel's request would jeopardize the
plant-closings provision.
   The Republican leader had sought earlier to delay action on
grounds of a rule that newly minted legislation should sit for a
minimum of three days before going to the passage stage on the
House floor.
   ``In this case we are dealing with a piece of legislation 1,000
pages long and containing some of the most profound changes in U.S.
trade law in a decade or more,'' Michel said in a letter to Rules
Committee Chairman Claude Pepper, D-Fla.
   ``We have yet to see the language in this legislation but
nevertheless you are clearing the way for a vote for it within 24
hours,'' he said. ``We are not even certain it will be printed in
time for the floor vote.''
   The bill itself is expected to pass the House without much
trouble when the passage vote comes. The major question has been
whether there will be enough votes to sustain a veto if the
plant-closings provision remains in.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
